{"title_page": "Albert Ho", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Use Hong Kong English|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Albert Ho Chun-yan\n| native_name = {{nobold|\u4f55\u4fca\u4ec1}}\n| native_name_lang = zh-hk\n| image = File:Lee-cheuk-yan-confirmed-legco-by-election-candidacy-4 (cropped).jpg\n| imagesize =\n| caption = Albert Ho in 2018\n| office2 =Member of the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong|Legislative Council]]\n| constituency4 = [[District Council (Second)]]\n| term_start4 = 1 October 2012\n| term_end4 = 30 September 2016\n| predecessor4 = ''New constituency''\n| successor4 = [[Roy Kwong]]\n| constituency3 = [[New Territories West (constituency)|New Territories West]]\n| term_start3 = 1 July 1998\n| term_end3 = 30 September 2012\n| predecessor3 = ''New parliament''\n| successor3 = [[Kwok Ka-ki]]\n| constituency2 = [[New Territories West (constituency)#1995 Constituencies|New Territories West]]\n| term_start2 = 11 October 1995\n| term_end2 = 30 June 1997\n| predecessor2 = ''New constituency''\n| successor2 = ''Replaced by [[Provisional Legislative Council]]\n| office1= Chairman of the [[Hong Kong Alliance in Support of Patriotic Democratic Movements in China]]\n| deputy1=[[Richard Tsoi]]<br />[[Mak Hoi-wah]]\n| term_start1=15 December 2014\n| term_end1=\n| predecessor1=[[Lee Cheuk-yan]]\n| successor1 = \n| office = Chairman of the [[Democratic Party (Hong Kong)|Democratic Party]]\n| term_start = 17 December 2006\n| term_end = 10 September 2012\n| predecessor = [[Lee Wing-tat]]\n| successor = [[Emily Lau]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1951|12|1}}\n| birth_place = [[British Hong Kong]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality =\n| party = [[Hong Kong Affairs Society]] {{small|(1985\u201390)}}<br />[[United Democrats of Hong Kong|United Democrats]] {{small|(1990\u201394)}}<br />[[Democratic Party (Hong Kong)|Democratic Party]] {{small|(since 1994)}}\n| residence  =\n| spouse = Tang Suk-yee \n| alma_mater = [[University of Hong Kong]]\n| occupation = Solicitor}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n|order=\n|showflag=\n|t=\u4f55\u4fca\u4ec1\n|j=Ho<sup>4</sup> Zeon<sup>3</sup> Yan<sup>4</sup> \n|y=H\u00f2h Jeun Y\u00e0hn\n}}\n\n'''Albert Ho Chun-yan''' ({{zh-t|\u4f55\u4fca\u4ec1}}; born 1 December 1951) is a solicitor and politician in Hong Kong. He is the current chairman of the [[Hong Kong Alliance in Support of Patriotic Democratic Movements in China]] and former chairman of the [[Democratic Party (Hong Kong)|Democratic Party]] from 2006 to 2012. He is a [[solicitor]] and a former member of the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong]] for [[District Council (Second)]] constituency.\n\n==Early life and education==\nHo was born in what was then [[British Hong Kong]] on 1 December 1951 in a big family with six children. His father worked in a shipping company by day and as a translator by night, along with two other jobs that he had.<ref name=\"interview\">{{cite news|title=Albert Ho Chun-yan|work=HK Magazine|url=http://hk-magazine.com/article/inside-hk/interviews/3941/albert-ho-chun-yan|first=Jan|last=Leung}}</ref> Ho got his [[Bachelor of Laws]] with honors in the [[University of Hong Kong]] in 1974, obtained [[Postgraduate Certificate in Laws]] in 1975.<ref name=\"Martin\">{{cite web|title=Albert Ho Chun-yan|url=http://www.martinlee.org.hk/BiosAlbertHo.html}}</ref>\n\nHe attended lectures given by Hsu Kwan-san, a Chinese historian who later became a professor at the [[Chinese University of Hong Kong]], whom Ho cited his political belief and Chinese national sentiment were influenced by. During his college life, he developed his liberal ideals and actively involved in student politics and campaigned for [[Mak Hoi-wah]] who ran for the [[Hong Kong University Students' Union]] against the Maoist nationalists who dominated the student union in the 1970s.\n\n==Legal and early political career==\nHo got [[admission to practice law]] in 1977 and appointed a [[notary public]] of the common law in 1988. He was employed for Messrs. C.Y. Kwan & Co. as a solicitor for nearly 20 years, then left to set up his own law firm, Ho, Tse, Wai & Partners. His [[litigation]] experience varied from banking cases and commercial law to land law and matrimonial disputes, as well as in criminal and medical negligence cases. Albert Ho worked a number of human rights cases on a [[pro bono]] (undertaken voluntarily and without payment) for the [[Pro-democracy camp in Hong Kong|pan-democracy camp]].<ref name=\"Martin\"/>\n\nHo stepped into politics when he was first appointed to the [[Kowloon City District Council|Kowloon City District Board]] from 1982 to 1983.<ref name=\"Martin\"/> In 1985 he co-founded the [[Hong Kong Affairs Society]] (HKAS) to participate in the electoral politics during the transition period. During his spell as the leader of the HKAS, he demanded the faster pace of democratisation in Hong Kong and safeguarding the freedom and lifestyles after the handover of Hong Kong to Mainland China after 1997. In 1989, he co-founded the [[Hong Kong Alliance in Support of Patriotic Democratic Movements in China]] to support the [[Tiananmen protests of 1989]] and critical of the Beijing government's bloody crackdown. He became the third chairman of the alliance since 2014, succeeding [[Lee Cheuk-yan]].\n\nHe ran for the [[Urban Council of Hong Kong|Urban Council]] in Kowloon City West in the [[1986 Hong Kong municipal elections|1986 municipal election]] but was defeated by incumbent [[Peter Chan Chi-kwan]]. He ran again in the [[1991 Hong Kong municipal elections|1991 Urban Council election]] in [[Southern District, Hong Kong|Southern District]] but was again lost to incumbent Joseph Chan Yuet-sut of the conservative [[Liberal Democratic Federation of Hong Kong]]. He was elected to the [[Regional Council of Hong Kong|Regional Council]] in the [[1995 Hong Kong municipal elections|municipal elections]] in 1995, receiving the largest number of votes in Regional Council.<ref name=\"Martin\"/> He kept served on the council through 1997 until it was abolished by then [[Chief Executive of Hong Kong|Chief Executive]] [[Tung Chee-hwa]] in 2000.\n\nHe had also been member of the [[Tuen Mun District Council]] for [[Lok Tsui (constituency)|Lok Tsui]] since the [[1999 Hong Kong local elections|1999 District Council election]]. He had been targeted by the radical democrats, including [[Albert Chan]] of the [[People Power (Hong Kong)|People Power]] in the [[2011 Hong Kong local elections|2011 District Council election]] who opposed Democrats' compromise with the Beijing officials on the [[2010 Hong Kong electoral reform|2012 constitutional reform proposals]] and in the [[2015 Hong Kong local elections|2015 District Council election]] by [[Civic Passion]]'s [[Cheng Chung-tai]]. He kept the seat for 15 years but was defeated in 2015 by [[pro-Beijing camp|pro-Beijing]] lawyer [[Junius Ho]] in 2015 by a narrow margin of 277 votes.\n\n==Legislative Councillor==\nIn April 1990, Ho and other pro-democracy activists co-founded the [[United Democrats of Hong Kong]] (UDHK), the first major pro-democracy party in the city, in which he became the founding vice chairman. The party transformed into today's [[Democratic Party (Hong Kong)|Democratic Party]] in 1994 where he was the member of the party's first executive committee. In 1992, he ran for the [[1992 New Territories West by-election|by-election]] in [[New Territories West (constituency)#1991 Constituencies|New Territories West]] as his first attempt to the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong|Legislative Council]] after incumbent Democrat [[Ng Ming-yam]] died of cancer. He was defeated by conservative rural leader [[Tang Siu-tong]] by only four percent of the votes. He ran again in New Territories West in [[1995 Hong Kong legislative election|1995 Legislative Council election]], receiving 54 percent of the popular vote.\n\nHe stepped down from the colonial legislature on 30 June 1997 on the eve of the [[handover of Hong Kong]] after the Beijing government dismantled the \"through train\" agreement of allowing the 1995 elected legislature to transition beyond 1997. The Democratic Party boycotted the [[Provisional Legislative Council]] controlled by Beijing and refused to take part in it. In November 1997, Ho was nominated by the Democratic Party to run for a seat in the [[National People's Congress]], but excluded from competition when failed to obtain the minimum number of nominations from the 400-strong Beijing-appointed election conference.<ref name=\"Martin\"/>\n\nIn the [[1998 Hong Kong legislative election|first Legislative Council election]] of the SAR period in 1998, Ho won a seat in the New Territories West with his party colleague [[Lee Wing-tat]]. With his strong basis in his strategic district [[Tuen Mun]], he was re-elected in 2000 with one of the three Democratic Party tickets. [[Albert Chan]] who had strong basis in [[Tsuen Wan]] was also elected on the expense of Lee Wing-tat. Ho was re-elected in 2004. After the election, he unsuccessfully challenged [[Rita Fan]] in the [[President of the Legislative Council of Hong Kong|Legco presidential]] election.\n\n=== 2006 attack ===\nOn 20 August 2006, Ho was assaulted by three unidentified men using [[baseball bat]]s and a [[Club (weapon)|baton]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/index.cfm?id=1224922006 |title=Baseball bat attack on MP at democracy rally |accessdate=2006-08-21 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070313004148/http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/index.cfm?id=1224922006 |archivedate=13 March 2007 |df=dmy }}, ''[[The Scotsman]]'', 20 August 2006</ref> in a McDonald's restaurant in [[Central, Hong Kong]], after he had attended a protest against the government's plan to adopt a [[Goods and Services Tax (Hong Kong)|Goods and Services Tax]]. He suffered injuries to his head, arm and face, including a broken nose.<ref>\n[http://www.scmp.com/portal/site/SCMP/menuitem.2af62ecb329d3d7733492d9253a0a0a0/?vgnextoid=b5f6d67abe33d110VgnVCM100000360a0a0aRCRD&ss=Hong+Kong&s=News SCMP, ''South China Morning Post'' article, \"Assailant thumps lawmaker and shoves banana in his face\"]. Retrieved 26 October 2008.</ref> Democratic Party chairman Lee Wing-tat claimed that the attack was related to a lawsuit Albert Ho was working on, and had nothing to do with politics. Hong Kong Chief Executive [[Donald Tsang]] condemned the attack, declaring that the attackers would be pursued to the \"ends of the earth\". [[Secretary for Security]] [[Ambrose Lee]] also condemned it.\n\n===Democratic Party Chairman===\nBetween 2004 and 2006 he was the vice chairman of the [[Democratic Party (Hong Kong)|Democratic Party]]. In December 2006, he was elected as party chairman in the [[2006 Democratic Party (HK) leadership election|leadership election]], defeating [[Chan King-ming]] of the reformist faction. Under his spell, the party absorbed [[Emily Lau]]'s [[the Frontier (Hong Kong)|The Frontier]] in 2008.\n\nIn June 2010, he led the Democratic Party delegation to the [[Liaison Office of the Central People's Government in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region|Liaison Office]] to negotiate the [[2010 Hong Kong electoral reform|electoral reform package]] with the representatives of the Beijing government, for the first time since the 1989 Tiananmen massacre. The Beijing government eventually accepted the Democratic Party's modified proposal to allow five new directly elected [[District Council (Second)]] seats.<ref>Cheers and jeers for political reform vote, ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', Gary Cheung, Albert Wong and Fanny WY Fung, 25 June 2010</ref> The compromise sparked extreme discontent among the radical democrats and created a major unrest among the pan-democracy camp. He was challenged by radical democrat legislator [[Albert Chan]] in his [[Lok Tsui (constituency)|Lok Tsui constituency]] in the following [[2011 Hong Kong local elections|2011 District Council election]] and barely retained his seat.\n\nIn the [[2012 Hong Kong legislative election|2012 Legislative Council election]], Albert Ho ran in the newly created District Council (Second) constituency and was elected with 228,840 votes. However, his party continued being attacks from the radical democrats and received the worst results in history, retaining only six seats. Ho resigned as party chairman right after the election results came out and was taken over by Emily Lau as acting chairwoman.\n\n===2012 Chief Executive bid===\nAlbert Ho announced in [[Causeway Bay]], Hong Kong on 4 October 2011 that he would challenge the [[2012 Hong Kong Chief Executive election|2012 Chief Executive election]] which was elected by 1200-member [[Election Committee]] controlled by Beijing.<ref>{{in lang|zh-hk}}[http://orientaldaily.on.cc/cnt/news/20111005/00176_014.html \u4f55\u4fca\u4ec1\u64ec\u9078\u7279\u9996 \u641e\u5168\u6c11\u6295\u7968] ''Oriental Daily''. 5 October 2011.</ref> With the pan democrats securing an estimated 205 votes, Albert Ho took part in a pan-democrat primary election on 8 January 2012 against [[Association for Democracy and People's Livelihood]] lawmaker [[Frederick Fung]] and won.<ref>Lee, Diana. (13 December 2011). [http://www.thestandard.com.hk/news_detail.asp?we_cat=11&art_id=117940&sid=34758031&con_type=1&d_str=20111213&fc=1 Pan-democrat camp ready for next fight] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908231034/http://www.thestandard.com.hk/news_detail.asp?we_cat=11 |date=8 September 2015 }} ''The Standard''.</ref> Ho ran against the two pro-Beijing candidates, ex-convenor of the [[Executive Council of Hong Kong|Executive Council]] [[Leung Chun-ying]] and former [[Chief Secretary for Administration|Chief Secretary]] [[Henry Tang]]. Since being widely conceived of having no chance winning the Beijing-controlled election, Ho's popularity trailed behind Leung and Tang over the election. Out of the 1,132 EC votes, Albert Ho came third with only 76. Leung Chun-ying was declared duly elected by the Returning Officer.<ref name=kalman20120325latimes>Kaiman, Jonathan (25 March 2012). [https://www.webcitation.org/66QejlwF5?url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/world_now/2012/03/reporting-from-beijing-pro-beijing-candidate-leung-chun-ying-was-chosen-by-a-hong-kong-election-committee-as-the-territ.html \"Thousands protest pick for Hong Kong executive post\"]. ''Los Angeles Times'' Archived from [http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/world_now/2012/03/reporting-from-beijing-pro-beijing-candidate-leung-chun-ying-was-chosen-by-a-hong-kong-election-committee-as-the-territ.html the original] on 25 March 2012.</ref>\n\n===Snowden incident===\nIn 2013, Ho grabbed international headlines after it was revealed that he had assisted [[Edward Snowden]] during the latter's stay in Hong Kong.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lam|first=Lana|title=Hong Kong lawyer Albert Ho says 'middleman' urged Snowden to leave|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/article/1267373/exclusive-human-rights-lawyers-hong-kong-reveal-they-worked-closely|newspaper=South China Morning Post|date=24 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2014 Hong Kong protests===\nIn October 2014, during [[2014 Hong Kong protests|pro-democracy protests]] that began on 26 September, Albert Ho said he was prepared to take a bullet if demonstrations turned violent. He did not support violence in the cause of democracy, but was willing to make a \"sacrifice\" on behalf of young people \"because the future belongs to them.\"<ref>Ed Flanagan & Alastair Jamieson (2 October 2014). [http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/hong-kong-protests/hong-kongs-albert-ho-i-will-take-bullet-democracy-n216501 \"Hong Kong's Albert Ho: I Will Take A Bullet For Democracy \"]. NBC News.</ref>\n\n==Life after tenure as a member of the Legislative Council==\n=== 2019 Hong Kong anti-extradition bill protests ===\n[[File:Albert Ho (\u4f55\u4fca\u4ec1), solicitor and politician; Hong Kong anti-extradition bill protest; June 9, 2019.jpg|thumb|Albert Ho, current chairman of the Hong Kong Alliance in Support of Patriotic Democratic Movements in China, took part in the Hong Kong anti-extradition bill protests on 9 June 2019]]\n\nAlbert Ho took part in [[2019 Hong Kong anti-extradition bill protests|Hong Kong anti-extradition bill protest]] on 9 June 2019. Organizers of the demonstration said more than 1 million strong came out on Hong Kong streets, while the Hong Kong police called number of about 300.000. Controversial extradition bill was proposed by Hong Kong Government as if for extradition of a suspect in Taiwan. However, the Hong Kong government has extended the scope in this bill of relevant countries and regions for extradition, including mainland China. The protesters believe if Hong Kong people had been extradited to the mainland China, their judicial rights would not be guaranteed.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u6297\u8bae\u6e2f\u5e9c\u4fee\u8ba2\u9003\u72af\u6761\u4f8b \u9999\u6e2f\u7206\u53d1\u8fd1\u7a7a\u524d\u89c4\u6a21\u5927\u6e38\u884c |url=https://www.voachinese.com/a/hong-kong-extradition-protest/4951674.html |author=\u7533\u534e |author2=\u8c2d\u5609\u742a |date=9 June 2019 |website=Voice of America, Chinese |language=zh |accessdate=13 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Being attacked again ===\nAlbert Ho was attacked at around 7pm in Tin Hau on 19 September. As he exited Tin Hau MTR station to return home, a black-clad group reportedly followed him into a nearby street and beat him with rods.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/11/19/former-hong-kong-lawmaker-albert-ho-attacked/|title=Former Hong Kong lawmaker Albert Ho attacked|last=Cheng|first=Kris|date=2019-11-19|website=Hong Kong Free Press HKFP|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref> Ho criticized that it was organized crime, and urged that the police must investigate seriously.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hk01.com/\u653f\u60c5/400193/\u4f55\u4fca\u4ec1\u9047\u8972-\u6c11\u4e3b\u6d3e-\u5147\u5f92\u5c3e\u96a8\u81f3\u6a6b\u8857\u65bd\u8972-\u660e\u986f\u6709\u7d44\u7e54\u72af\u4e8b|title=\u3010\u4f55\u4fca\u4ec1\u9047\u8972\u3011\u6c11\u4e3b\u6d3e\uff1a\u5147\u5f92\u5c3e\u96a8\u81f3\u6a6b\u8857\u65bd\u8972 \u660e\u986f\u6709\u7d44\u7e54\u72af\u4e8b|last=\u912d\u6995\u7b1b|date=2019-11-19|website=\u9999\u6e2f01|language=zh-HK|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n\n===Arrest===\nOn 18 April 2020, Albert Ho was arrested as one of 15 Hong Kong high-profile democracy figures, on suspicion of organizing, publicizing or taking part in several unauthorized assemblies between August and October 2019 in the course of the anti-extradition bill protests. Following protocol, the police statement did not disclose the names of the accused.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/18/world/asia/hong-kong-arrests.html |title = Amid Pandemic, Hong Kong Arrests Major Pro-Democracy Figures|first1=Elaine|last1=Yu|first2=Austin|last2=Ramzy|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date = 18 April 2020|access-date = 18 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://hongkongfp.com/2020/04/18/8-hong-kong-pro-democracy-figures-arrested-in-latest-police-round-up-party-says/ |title = Amid Pandemic, Hong Kong Arrests Major Pro-Democracy Figures|first=Rachel|last=Wong|newspaper=[[Hong Kong Free Press]]|date = 18 April 2020|access-date = 18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{commonscategory|Ho Chun Yan, Albert}}\n* [[List of graduates of University of Hong Kong]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-new|party}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Vice Chairperson of [[United Democrats of Hong Kong]]|years=1990\u20131994\n|with=[[Yeung Sum]]}}\n{{s-non|reason=Merged into [[Democratic Party (Hong Kong)|Democratic Party]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lau Chin-shek]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Vice Chairperson of [[Democratic Party (Hong Kong)|Democratic Party]]|years=1999\u20132000\n|with=[[Yeung Sum]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Law Chi-kwong]]<br />[[Lee Wing-tat]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Law Chi-kwong]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Vice Chairperson of [[Democratic Party (Hong Kong)|Democratic Party]]|years=2002\u20132006\n|with=[[Lee Wing-tat]] (2002\u20132004)\n|with2=[[Chan King-ming]] (2004\u20132006)}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Sin Chung-kai]]<br />[[Tik Chi-yuen]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lee Wing-tat]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chairperson of [[Democratic Party (Hong Kong)|Democratic Party]]|years=2006\u20132012}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Emily Lau]]}}\n{{s-par|hk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tang Siu-tong]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Legislative Council\n|district=[[New Territories West (constituency)#New Territories West|New Territories West]]\n|years=1995\u20131997}}\n{{s-non|reason=Replaced by [[Provisional Legislative Council]]}}\n{{s-new|parliament}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Legislative Council|district=[[New Territories West (constituency)|New Territories West]]|years=1998\u20132012}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Kwok Ka-ki]]}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Legislative Council|district=[[District Council (Second)]]|years=2012\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Roy Kwong]]}}\n{{s-off|hk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lo Chun-hung]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of [[Tuen Mun District Council]]\n|district=[[Lok Tsui (constituency)|Lok Tsui]]\n|years=2000\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Junius Ho]]}}\n{{s-npo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lee Cheuk-yan]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chairman of the [[Hong Kong Alliance in Support of Patriotic Democratic Movements in China|Alliance in Support of Patriotic Democratic Movements in China]]|years=2014\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Candidates in the Hong Kong Chief Executive election, 2012}}\n{{HK Democratic Party}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ho, Albert}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Members of the Regional Council of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Leaders of political parties]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Legislative Council of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:District councillors of Kowloon City District]]\n[[Category:District councillors of Tuen Mun District]]\n[[Category:Solicitors of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Charter 08 signatories]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party (Hong Kong) politicians]]\n[[Category:United Democrats of Hong Kong politicians]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong Affairs Society politicians]]\n[[Category:HK LegCo Members 1995\u20131997]]\n[[Category:HK LegCo Members 1998\u20132000]]\n[[Category:HK LegCo Members 2000\u20132004]]\n[[Category:HK LegCo Members 2004\u20132008]]\n[[Category:HK LegCo Members 2008\u20132012]]\n[[Category:HK LegCo Members 2012\u20132016]]\n[[Category:Members of the Election Committee of Hong Kong, 2017\u20132022]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Use Hong Kong English|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Albert Ho Chun-yan\n| native_name = {{nobold|\u4f55\u4fca\u4ec1}}\n| native_name_lang = zh-hk\n| image = File:Lee-cheuk-yan-confirmed-legco-by-election-candidacy-4 (cropped).jpg\n| imagesize =\n| caption = Albert Ho in 2018\n| office2 =Member of the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong|Legislative Council]]\n| constituency4 = [[District Council (Second)]]\n| term_start4 = 1 October 2012\n| term_end4 = 30 September 2016\n| predecessor4 = ''New constituency''\n| successor4 = [[Roy Kwong]]\n| constituency3 = [[New Territories West (constituency)|New Territories West]]\n| term_start3 = 1 July 1998\n| term_end3 = 30 September 2012\n| predecessor3 = ''New parliament''\n| successor3 = [[Kwok Ka-ki]]\n| constituency2 = [[New Territories West (constituency)#1995 Constituencies|New Territories West]]\n| term_start2 = 11 October 1995\n| term_end2 = 30 June 1997\n| predecessor2 = ''New constituency''\n| successor2 = ''Replaced by [[Provisional Legislative Council]]\n| office1= Chairman of the [[Hong Kong Alliance in Support of Patriotic Democratic Movements in China]]\n| deputy1=[[Richard Tsoi]]<br />[[Mak Hoi-wah]]\n| term_start1=15 December 2014\n| term_end1=\n| predecessor1=[[Lee Cheuk-yan]]\n| successor1 = \n| office = Chairman of the [[Democratic Party (Hong Kong)|Democratic Party]]\n| term_start = 17 December 2006\n| term_end = 10 September 2012\n| predecessor = [[Lee Wing-tat]]\n| successor = [[Emily Lau]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1951|12|1}}\n| birth_place = [[British Hong Kong]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality =\n| party = [[Hong Kong Affairs Society]] {{small|(1985\u201390)}}<br />[[United Democrats of Hong Kong|United Democrats]] {{small|(1990\u201394)}}<br />[[Democratic Party (Hong Kong)|Democratic Party]] {{small|(since 1994)}}\n| residence  =\n| spouse = Tang Suk-yee \n| alma_mater = [[University of Hong Kong]]\n| occupation = Solicitor}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n|order=\n|showflag=\n|t=\u4f55\u4fca\u4ec1\n|j=Ho<sup>4</sup> Zeon<sup>3</sup> Yan<sup>4</sup> \n|y=H\u00f2h Jeun Y\u00e0hn\n}}\n\n'''Albert Ho Chun-yan''' ({{zh-t|\u4f55\u4fca\u4ec1}}; born 1 December 1951) is a solicitor and politician in Hong Kong. He is the current chairman of the [[Hong Kong Alliance in Support of Patriotic Democratic Movements in China]] and former chairman of the [[Democratic Party (Hong Kong)|Democratic Party]] from 2006 to 2012. He is a [[solicitor]] and a former member of the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong]] for [[District Council (Second)]] constituency.\n\n==Early life and education==\nHo was born in what was then [[British Hong Kong]] on 1 December 1951 in a big family with six children. His father worked in a shipping company by day and as a translator by night, along with two other jobs that he had.<ref name=\"interview\">{{cite news|title=Albert Ho Chun-yan|work=HK Magazine|url=http://hk-magazine.com/article/inside-hk/interviews/3941/albert-ho-chun-yan|first=Jan|last=Leung}}</ref> Ho got his [[Bachelor of Laws]] with honors in the [[University of Hong Kong]] in 1974, obtained [[Postgraduate Certificate in Laws]] in 1975.<ref name=\"Martin\">{{cite web|title=Albert Ho Chun-yan|url=http://www.martinlee.org.hk/BiosAlbertHo.html}}</ref>\n\nHe attended lectures given by Hsu Kwan-san, a Chinese historian who later became a professor at the [[Chinese University of Hong Kong]], whom Ho cited his political belief and Chinese national sentiment were influenced by. During his college life, he developed his liberal ideals and actively involved in student politics and campaigned for [[Mak Hoi-wah]] who ran for the [[Hong Kong University Students' Union]] against the Maoist nationalists who dominated the student union in the 1970s.\n\n==Legal and early political career==\nHo got [[admission to practice law]] in 1977 and appointed a [[notary public]] of the common law in 1988. He was employed for Messrs. C.Y. Kwan & Co. as a solicitor for nearly 20 years, then left to set up his own law firm, Ho, Tse, Wai & Partners. His [[litigation]] experience varied from banking cases and commercial law to land law and matrimonial disputes, as well as in criminal and medical negligence cases. Albert Ho worked a number of human rights cases on a [[pro bono]] (undertaken voluntarily and without payment) for the [[Pro-democracy camp in Hong Kong|pan-democracy camp]].<ref name=\"Martin\"/>\n\nHo stepped into politics when he was first appointed to the [[Kowloon City District Council|Kowloon City District Board]] from 1982 to 1983.<ref name=\"Martin\"/> In 1985 he co-founded the [[Hong Kong Affairs Society]] (HKAS) to participate in the electoral politics during the transition period. During his spell as the leader of the HKAS, he demanded the faster pace of democratisation in Hong Kong and safeguarding the freedom and lifestyles after the handover of Hong Kong to Mainland China after 1997. In 1989, he co-founded the [[Hong Kong Alliance in Support of Patriotic Democratic Movements in China]] to support the [[Tiananmen protests of 1989]] and critical of the Beijing government's bloody crackdown. He became the third chairman of the alliance since 2014, succeeding [[Lee Cheuk-yan]].\n\nHe ran for the [[Urban Council of Hong Kong|Urban Council]] in Kowloon City West in the [[1986 Hong Kong municipal elections|1986 municipal election]] but was defeated by incumbent [[Peter Chan Chi-kwan]]. He ran again in the [[1991 Hong Kong municipal elections|1991 Urban Council election]] in [[Southern District, Hong Kong|Southern District]] but was again lost to incumbent Joseph Chan Yuet-sut of the conservative [[Liberal Democratic Federation of Hong Kong]]. He was elected to the [[Regional Council of Hong Kong|Regional Council]] in the [[1995 Hong Kong municipal elections|municipal elections]] in 1995, receiving the largest number of votes in Regional Council.<ref name=\"Martin\"/> He kept served on the council through 1997 until it was abolished by then [[Chief Executive of Hong Kong|Chief Executive]] [[Tung Chee-hwa]] in 2000.\n\nHe had also been member of the [[Tuen Mun District Council]] for [[Lok Tsui (constituency)|Lok Tsui]] since the [[1999 Hong Kong local elections|1999 District Council election]]. He had been targeted by the radical democrats, including [[Albert Chan]] of the [[People Power (Hong Kong)|People Power]] in the [[2011 Hong Kong local elections|2011 District Council election]] who opposed Democrats' compromise with the Beijing officials on the [[2010 Hong Kong electoral reform|2012 constitutional reform proposals]] and in the [[2015 Hong Kong local elections|2015 District Council election]] by [[Civic Passion]]'s [[Cheng Chung-tai]]. He kept the seat for 15 years but was defeated in 2015 by [[pro-Beijing camp|pro-Beijing]] lawyer [[Junius Ho]] in 2015 by a narrow margin of 277 votes.\n\n==Legislative Councillor==\nIn April 1990, Ho and other pro-democracy activists co-founded the [[United Democrats of Hong Kong]] (UDHK), the first major pro-democracy party in the city, in which he became the founding vice chairman. The party transformed into today's [[Democratic Party (Hong Kong)|Democratic Party]] in 1994 where he was the member of the party's first executive committee. In 1992, he ran for the [[1992 New Territories West by-election|by-election]] in [[New Territories West (constituency)#1991 Constituencies|New Territories West]] as his first attempt to the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong|Legislative Council]] after incumbent Democrat [[Ng Ming-yam]] died of cancer. He was defeated by conservative rural leader [[Tang Siu-tong]] by only four percent of the votes. He ran again in New Territories West in [[1995 Hong Kong legislative election|1995 Legislative Council election]], receiving 54 percent of the popular vote.\n\nHe stepped down from the colonial legislature on 30 June 1997 on the eve of the [[handover of Hong Kong]] after the Beijing government dismantled the \"through train\" agreement of allowing the 1995 elected legislature to transition beyond 1997. The Democratic Party boycotted the [[Provisional Legislative Council]] controlled by Beijing and refused to take part in it. In November 1997, Ho was nominated by the Democratic Party to run for a seat in the [[National People's Congress]], but excluded from competition when failed to obtain the minimum number of nominations from the 400-strong Beijing-appointed election conference.<ref name=\"Martin\"/>\n\nIn the [[1998 Hong Kong legislative election|first Legislative Council election]] of the SAR period in 1998, Ho won a seat in the New Territories West with his party colleague [[Lee Wing-tat]]. With his strong basis in his strategic district [[Tuen Mun]], he was re-elected in 2000 with one of the three Democratic Party tickets. [[Albert Chan]] who had strong basis in [[Tsuen Wan]] was also elected on the expense of Lee Wing-tat. Ho was re-elected in 2004. After the election, he unsuccessfully challenged [[Rita Fan]] in the [[President of the Legislative Council of Hong Kong|Legco presidential]] election.\n\n=== 2006 attack ===\nOn 20 August 2006, Ho was assaulted by three unidentified men using [[baseball bat]]s and a [[Club (weapon)|baton]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/index.cfm?id=1224922006 |title=Baseball bat attack on MP at democracy rally |accessdate=2006-08-21 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070313004148/http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/index.cfm?id=1224922006 |archivedate=13 March 2007 |df=dmy }}, ''[[The Scotsman]]'', 20 August 2006</ref> in a McDonald's restaurant in [[Central, Hong Kong]], after he had attended a protest against the government's plan to adopt a [[Goods and Services Tax (Hong Kong)|Goods and Services Tax]]. He suffered injuries to his head, arm and face, including a broken nose.<ref>\n[http://www.scmp.com/portal/site/SCMP/menuitem.2af62ecb329d3d7733492d9253a0a0a0/?vgnextoid=b5f6d67abe33d110VgnVCM100000360a0a0aRCRD&ss=Hong+Kong&s=News SCMP, ''South China Morning Post'' article, \"Assailant thumps lawmaker and shoves banana in his face\"]. Retrieved 26 October 2008.</ref> Democratic Party chairman Lee Wing-tat claimed that the attack was related to a lawsuit Albert Ho was working on, and had nothing to do with politics. Hong Kong Chief Executive [[Donald Tsang]] condemned the attack, declaring that the attackers would be pursued to the \"ends of the earth\". [[Secretary for Security]] [[Ambrose Lee]] also condemned it.\n\n===Democratic Party Chairman===\nBetween 2004 and 2006 he was the vice chairman of the [[Democratic Party (Hong Kong)|Democratic Party]]. In December 2006, he was elected as party chairman in the [[2006 Democratic Party (HK) leadership election|leadership election]], defeating [[Chan King-ming]] of the reformist faction. Under his spell, the party absorbed [[Emily Lau]]'s [[the Frontier (Hong Kong)|The Frontier]] in 2008.\n\nIn June 2010, he led the Democratic Party delegation to the [[Liaison Office of the Central People's Government in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region|Liaison Office]] to negotiate the [[2010 Hong Kong electoral reform|electoral reform package]] with the representatives of the Beijing government, for the first time since the 1989 Tiananmen massacre. The Beijing government eventually accepted the Democratic Party's modified proposal to allow five new directly elected [[District Council (Second)]] seats.<ref>Cheers and jeers for political reform vote, ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', Gary Cheung, Albert Wong and Fanny WY Fung, 25 June 2010</ref> The compromise sparked extreme discontent among the radical democrats and created a major unrest among the pan-democracy camp. He was challenged by radical democrat legislator [[Albert Chan]] in his [[Lok Tsui (constituency)|Lok Tsui constituency]] in the following [[2011 Hong Kong local elections|2011 District Council election]] and barely retained his seat.\n\nIn the [[2012 Hong Kong legislative election|2012 Legislative Council election]], Albert Ho ran in the newly created District Council (Second) constituency and was elected with 228,840 votes. However, his party continued being attacks from the radical democrats and received the worst results in history, retaining only six seats. Ho resigned as party chairman right after the election results came out and was taken over by Emily Lau as acting chairwoman.\n\n===2012 Chief Executive bid===\nAlbert Ho announced in [[Causeway Bay]], Hong Kong on 4 October 2011 that he would challenge the [[2012 Hong Kong Chief Executive election|2012 Chief Executive election]] which was elected by 1200-member [[Election Committee]] controlled by Beijing.<ref>{{in lang|zh-hk}}[http://orientaldaily.on.cc/cnt/news/20111005/00176_014.html \u4f55\u4fca\u4ec1\u64ec\u9078\u7279\u9996 \u641e\u5168\u6c11\u6295\u7968] ''Oriental Daily''. 5 October 2011.</ref> With the pan democrats securing an estimated 205 votes, Albert Ho took part in a pan-democrat primary election on 8 January 2012 against [[Association for Democracy and People's Livelihood]] lawmaker [[Frederick Fung]] and won.<ref>Lee, Diana. (13 December 2011). [http://www.thestandard.com.hk/news_detail.asp?we_cat=11&art_id=117940&sid=34758031&con_type=1&d_str=20111213&fc=1 Pan-democrat camp ready for next fight] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908231034/http://www.thestandard.com.hk/news_detail.asp?we_cat=11 |date=8 September 2015 }} ''The Standard''.</ref> Ho ran against the two pro-Beijing candidates, ex-convenor of the [[Executive Council of Hong Kong|Executive Council]] [[Leung Chun-ying]] and former [[Chief Secretary for Administration|Chief Secretary]] [[Henry Tang]]. Since being widely conceived of having no chance winning the Beijing-controlled election, Ho's popularity trailed behind Leung and Tang over the election. Out of the 1,132 EC votes, Albert Ho came third with only 76. Leung Chun-ying was declared duly elected by the Returning Officer.<ref name=kalman20120325latimes>Kaiman, Jonathan (25 March 2012). [https://www.webcitation.org/66QejlwF5?url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/world_now/2012/03/reporting-from-beijing-pro-beijing-candidate-leung-chun-ying-was-chosen-by-a-hong-kong-election-committee-as-the-territ.html \"Thousands protest pick for Hong Kong executive post\"]. ''Los Angeles Times'' Archived from [http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/world_now/2012/03/reporting-from-beijing-pro-beijing-candidate-leung-chun-ying-was-chosen-by-a-hong-kong-election-committee-as-the-territ.html the original] on 25 March 2012.</ref>\n\n===Snowden incident===\nIn 2013, Ho grabbed international headlines after it was revealed that he had assisted [[Edward Snowden]] during the latter's stay in Hong Kong.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lam|first=Lana|title=Hong Kong lawyer Albert Ho says 'middleman' urged Snowden to leave|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/article/1267373/exclusive-human-rights-lawyers-hong-kong-reveal-they-worked-closely|newspaper=South China Morning Post|date=24 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2014 Hong Kong protests===\nIn October 2014, during [[2014 Hong Kong protests|pro-democracy protests]] that began on 26 September, Albert Ho said he was prepared to take a bullet if demonstrations turned violent. He did not support violence in the cause of democracy, but was willing to make a \"sacrifice\" on behalf of young people \"because the future belongs to them.\"<ref>Ed Flanagan & Alastair Jamieson (2 October 2014). [http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/hong-kong-protests/hong-kongs-albert-ho-i-will-take-bullet-democracy-n216501 \"Hong Kong's Albert Ho: I Will Take A Bullet For Democracy \"]. NBC News.</ref>\n\n==Life after tenure as a member of the Legislative Council==\n=== 2019 Hong Kong anti-extradition bill protests ===\n[[File:Albert Ho (\u4f55\u4fca\u4ec1), solicitor and politician; Hong Kong anti-extradition bill protest; June 9, 2019.jpg|thumb|Albert Ho, current chairman of the Hong Kong Alliance in Support of Patriotic Democratic Movements in China, took part in the Hong Kong anti-extradition bill protests on 9 June 2019]]\n\nAlbert Ho took part in [[2019 Hong Kong anti-extradition bill protests|Hong Kong anti-extradition bill protest]] on 9 June 2019. Organizers of the demonstration said more than 1 million strong came out on Hong Kong streets, while the Hong Kong police called number of about 300.000. Controversial extradition bill was proposed by Hong Kong Government as if for extradition of a suspect in Taiwan. However, the Hong Kong government has extended the scope in this bill of relevant countries and regions for extradition, including mainland China. The protesters believe if Hong Kong people had been extradited to the mainland China, their judicial rights would not be guaranteed.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u6297\u8bae\u6e2f\u5e9c\u4fee\u8ba2\u9003\u72af\u6761\u4f8b \u9999\u6e2f\u7206\u53d1\u8fd1\u7a7a\u524d\u89c4\u6a21\u5927\u6e38\u884c |url=https://www.voachinese.com/a/hong-kong-extradition-protest/4951674.html |author=\u7533\u534e |author2=\u8c2d\u5609\u742a |date=9 June 2019 |website=Voice of America, Chinese |language=zh |accessdate=13 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Being attacked again ===\nAlbert Ho was attacked at around 7pm in Tin Hau on 19 September. As he exited Tin Hau MTR station to return home, a black-clad group reportedly followed him into a nearby street and beat him with rods.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/11/19/former-hong-kong-lawmaker-albert-ho-attacked/|title=Former Hong Kong lawmaker Albert Ho attacked|last=Cheng|first=Kris|date=2019-11-19|website=Hong Kong Free Press HKFP|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref> Ho criticized that it was organized crime, and urged that the police must investigate seriously.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hk01.com/\u653f\u60c5/400193/\u4f55\u4fca\u4ec1\u9047\u8972-\u6c11\u4e3b\u6d3e-\u5147\u5f92\u5c3e\u96a8\u81f3\u6a6b\u8857\u65bd\u8972-\u660e\u986f\u6709\u7d44\u7e54\u72af\u4e8b|title=\u3010\u4f55\u4fca\u4ec1\u9047\u8972\u3011\u6c11\u4e3b\u6d3e\uff1a\u5147\u5f92\u5c3e\u96a8\u81f3\u6a6b\u8857\u65bd\u8972 \u660e\u986f\u6709\u7d44\u7e54\u72af\u4e8b|last=\u912d\u6995\u7b1b|date=2019-11-19|website=\u9999\u6e2f01|language=zh-HK|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n\n===Arrest===\nOn 18 April 2020, Albert Ho was arrested as one of 15 Hong Kong high-profile democracy figures, on suspicion of organizing, publicizing or taking part in several unauthorized assemblies between August and October 2019 in the course of the [[2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests]]. Following protocol, the police statement did not disclose the names of the accused.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/18/world/asia/hong-kong-arrests.html |title = Amid Pandemic, Hong Kong Arrests Major Pro-Democracy Figures|first1=Elaine|last1=Yu|first2=Austin|last2=Ramzy|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date = 18 April 2020|access-date = 18 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://hongkongfp.com/2020/04/18/8-hong-kong-pro-democracy-figures-arrested-in-latest-police-round-up-party-says/ |title = Amid Pandemic, Hong Kong Arrests Major Pro-Democracy Figures|first=Rachel|last=Wong|newspaper=[[Hong Kong Free Press]]|date = 18 April 2020|access-date = 18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{commonscategory|Ho Chun Yan, Albert}}\n* [[List of graduates of University of Hong Kong]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-new|party}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Vice Chairperson of [[United Democrats of Hong Kong]]|years=1990\u20131994\n|with=[[Yeung Sum]]}}\n{{s-non|reason=Merged into [[Democratic Party (Hong Kong)|Democratic Party]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lau Chin-shek]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Vice Chairperson of [[Democratic Party (Hong Kong)|Democratic Party]]|years=1999\u20132000\n|with=[[Yeung Sum]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Law Chi-kwong]]<br />[[Lee Wing-tat]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Law Chi-kwong]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Vice Chairperson of [[Democratic Party (Hong Kong)|Democratic Party]]|years=2002\u20132006\n|with=[[Lee Wing-tat]] (2002\u20132004)\n|with2=[[Chan King-ming]] (2004\u20132006)}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Sin Chung-kai]]<br />[[Tik Chi-yuen]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lee Wing-tat]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chairperson of [[Democratic Party (Hong Kong)|Democratic Party]]|years=2006\u20132012}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Emily Lau]]}}\n{{s-par|hk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tang Siu-tong]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Legislative Council\n|district=[[New Territories West (constituency)#New Territories West|New Territories West]]\n|years=1995\u20131997}}\n{{s-non|reason=Replaced by [[Provisional Legislative Council]]}}\n{{s-new|parliament}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Legislative Council|district=[[New Territories West (constituency)|New Territories West]]|years=1998\u20132012}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Kwok Ka-ki]]}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Legislative Council|district=[[District Council (Second)]]|years=2012\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Roy Kwong]]}}\n{{s-off|hk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lo Chun-hung]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of [[Tuen Mun District Council]]\n|district=[[Lok Tsui (constituency)|Lok Tsui]]\n|years=2000\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Junius Ho]]}}\n{{s-npo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lee Cheuk-yan]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chairman of the [[Hong Kong Alliance in Support of Patriotic Democratic Movements in China|Alliance in Support of Patriotic Democratic Movements in China]]|years=2014\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Candidates in the Hong Kong Chief Executive election, 2012}}\n{{HK Democratic Party}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ho, Albert}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Members of the Regional Council of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Leaders of political parties]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Legislative Council of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:District councillors of Kowloon City District]]\n[[Category:District councillors of Tuen Mun District]]\n[[Category:Solicitors of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Charter 08 signatories]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party (Hong Kong) politicians]]\n[[Category:United Democrats of Hong Kong politicians]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong Affairs Society politicians]]\n[[Category:HK LegCo Members 1995\u20131997]]\n[[Category:HK LegCo Members 1998\u20132000]]\n[[Category:HK LegCo Members 2000\u20132004]]\n[[Category:HK LegCo Members 2004\u20132008]]\n[[Category:HK LegCo Members 2008\u20132012]]\n[[Category:HK LegCo Members 2012\u20132016]]\n[[Category:Members of the Election Committee of Hong Kong, 2017\u20132022]]\n", "name_user": "CRau080", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eArrest", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albert_Ho"}
{"title_page": "Tyson Fury", "text_new": "{{short description|British boxer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox boxer\n| name = Tyson Fury\n| image = Tyson Fury - 2016-04-30.jpg\n| caption = Fury in 2016\n| realname = Tyson Luke Fury\n| nickname = {{plainlist|\n*Gypsy King\n*The Furious One\n*2 Fast\n}}\n| weight = [[Heavyweight]]\n| height = 6 ft 9 in<ref name=stats2018>''[[Showtime Championship Boxing]]'' tale of the tape prior to the [[Deontay Wilder]] fight.</ref>\n| reach = 85 in<ref name=stats2018/>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1988|8|12}}\n| birth_place = [[Wythenshawe]], [[Manchester]], England\n| style = [[Orthodox stance|Orthodox]]\n| total = 31\n| wins = 30\n| KO = 21\n| losses = 0\n| draws = 1\n| no contests = \n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport | Men's [[amateur boxing]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{ENG}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[ABA Championships|English National Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold | 2008 [[London]] | [[Super-heavyweight]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[European Union Amateur Boxing Championships|EU Junior Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold | 2007 [[Warsaw]] | Super-heavyweight}}\n{{MedalCompetition | European Junior Championships}}\n{{MedalSilver | 2007 [[Sombor]] | Super-heavyweight}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{IRL}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Youth and Junior World Boxing Championships|World Junior Championships]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | 2006 [[Agadir]] | Super-heavyweight}}\n}}\n\n'''Tyson Luke Fury''' (born 12 August 1988) is a British [[professional boxer]] who is a two-time [[heavyweight]] world champion. He has held the [[World Boxing Council|WBC]], ''[[The Ring (magazine)|The Ring]]'' magazine, and [[lineal championship|lineal]] titles since defeating [[Deontay Wilder]] in February 2020; previously he held the [[unified champion|unified]] [[WBA (Super)]], [[IBF]], [[WBO]], [[International Boxing Organization|IBO]], ''The Ring'', and lineal titles after defeating [[Wladimir Klitschko]] in 2015. With his [[Deontay Wilder vs. Tyson Fury II|defeat of Wilder]], Fury became the third heavyweight, after [[Floyd Patterson]] and [[Muhammad Ali]], to hold ''The Ring'' magazine title twice, and the first heavyweight in history to have held the WBA (Super), WBC, IBF, WBO, and ''The Ring'' magazine titles. As of April 2020, Fury is ranked as the world's best active heavyweight by [[ESPN]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/21675272/divisional-rankings-tyson-fury-shakes-heavyweight-division-again|title=Divisional rankings: Fury shakes up heavyweight division ... again|last=|first=|date=|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref> the [[Transnational Boxing Rankings Board]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tbrb.org/all-rankings/|title=RANKINGS {{!}} Transnational Boxing Rankings Board|last=|first=|date=|website=|language=en-US|access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref> and [[BoxRec]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://boxrec.com/en/ratings?offset=0&sex=M&division=Heavyweight|title=BoxRec: Ratings|website=boxrec.com|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref> as well as the second-best active boxer, [[pound for pound]], by BoxRec,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://boxrec.com/en/ratings?r%5Bcountry%5D=&r%5Bdivision%5D=&r%5Bsex%5D=M&r%5Bstance%5D=&r%5Bstatus%5D=a&r_go=|title=BoxRec: Ratings|last=|first=|date=|website=boxrec.com|access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref> sixth by the Transnational Boxing Rankings Board,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tbrb.org/p4p/|title=P4P {{!}} Transnational Boxing Rankings Board|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref> and seventh by ESPN.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/28785006/pound-pound-rankings-tyson-fury-makes-debut|title=Pound-for-pound rankings: Tyson Fury makes debut|date=2020-02-27|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nAs an [[amateur boxing|amateur]], Fury represented both England and Ireland, as he was born in [[Manchester]] to an [[Irish Travellers|Irish Traveller]] family and traced his family lineage to relatives in [[Belfast]] and [[Galway]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Boxer Fury finds Irish roots |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/boxing/14904158 |work=BBC Sport |date=13 September 2011 |accessdate=12 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418082543/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/boxing/14904158 |archivedate=18 April 2015 }}</ref> He won the [[England Boxing|ABA]] [[super-heavyweight]] title in 2008 before turning professional later that year at 20 years of age. After winning the [[British Boxing Board of Control|English heavyweight title]] twice, he became the [[British Boxing Board of Control|British]] and [[Commonwealth Boxing Council|Commonwealth]] champion in 2011 by defeating the 14\u20130 [[Dereck Chisora]]. He then won the [[Boxing Union of Ireland|Irish]] and WBO Inter-Continental titles, before defeating Chisora again in a 2014 rematch for the [[European Boxing Union|European]] and WBO International heavyweight titles. This success, along with his 24\u20130 record, set up a match with the long-reigning world champion Klitschko in Germany, which Fury [[Wladimir Klitschko vs. Tyson Fury|won by unanimous decision]].\n\nFury was stripped of his IBF title 10 days after the Klitschko bout as he was unable to grant a fight with the IBF's [[mandatory challenger]], [[Vyacheslav Glazkov]], due to a rematch clause in his contract with Klitschko. The rematch did not materialise as Fury suffered from mental health issues leading to alcoholism, recreational drug use and extreme weight gain. He was charged with anti-doping violations. In 2016, he vacated the WBA, WBO, and IBO titles; ''The Ring'' stripped him of his last remaining title in early 2018. Later that year, after more than two years of inactivity, Fury challenged for the WBC heavyweight title against Wilder. The fight was [[Deontay Wilder vs. Tyson Fury|controversially scored as a draw]], with many believing Fury won.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/boxing/2018/12/02/deontay-wilder-tyson-fury-fight-controversial-draw-title-bout/2181952002/|title=Deontay Wilder, Tyson Fury fight to draw in controversial decision in WBC heavyweight title bout|first=Josh |last=Peter|date=15 December 2019|website=USA TODAY}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/boxing/tyson-fury-vs-deontay-wilder-result-draw-watch-video-scorecard-rematch-latest-news-next-joshua-belts-a8663241.html|title=Tyson Fury and Deontay Wilder battle to controversial draw|date=2 December 2018|website=The Independent}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.badlefthook.com/2018/12/2/18122038/wilder-vs-fury-pros-react-to-controversial-draw-decision|title=Wilder vs Fury: Pros react to controversial draw decision|first=Scott|last=Christ|date=2 December 2018|website=Bad Left Hook}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theweek.co.uk/boxing/98205/deontay-wilder-vs-tyson-fury-controversial-split-draw-how-boxers-media-reacted|title=Wilder vs. Fury ends in controversial split draw - how boxers and media reacted|website=The Week UK}}</ref> Fury's strong performance against Wilder (including recovering from a heavy [[knockdown (boxing)|knockdown]] in the final round) earned him [[The Ring magazine Comeback of the Year|Comeback of the Year]] from ''The Ring'' and numerous other awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worldboxingnews.net/2019/01/21/wbn-awards-2018-winners/|title=World Boxing News Awards 2018: The Winners revealed|date=21 January 2019|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nTyson Luke Fury<ref name=\"Paris Fury uploads photo of Tyson's passport\">{{cite tweet|user=parisfury1|author=Fury, Paris|number=260844544835330048|date=23 October 2012|title=@boycie85 just to show what u know! and anyone else inc Wikipedia who thinks its Luke}}</ref> was born on 12 August 1988 in the [[Wythenshawe]] area of [[Manchester]] to Irish parents Amber and [[John Fury]],<ref name=\"Rayner\" /> and was raised in a house in [[Styal]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Davies|first=Gareth A.|url=https://s.telegraph.co.uk/graphics/projects/tyson-fury-wladimir-klitschko-fight/index.html|title=Tyson Fury: 'It's me against the world'|date=2015-11-24|access-date=2020-04-18|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Fury was born three months [[Premature birth|premature]] and weighed {{convert|1|lb|g}}.<ref name=Starks>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/queensberry-rules-boxing-blog/2015/dec/02/tyson-fury-heavyweight-champion-wladimir-klitschko|title=Tyson Fury: a few facts about the new heavyweight champion of the world|last=Starks|first=Tim|date=2 December 2015|website=The Guardian|access-date=24 June 2018}}</ref> His father, John, named him Tyson after the then-undefeated undisputed heavyweight world champion [[Mike Tyson]].<ref name=\"Telegraph\" /> John said: \"The doctors told me there was not much chance of him living. I had lost two daughters in the same way who had been born prematurely.\" He decided on Tyson as he was a fighter and survived the premature birth.<ref name=Starks /> \n\nFury is of [[Irish Traveller]] descent.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tyson Fury: Fists of fury|first=Steve|last=Bunce| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/tyson-fury-fists-of-fury-6260261.html|accessdate=2 December 2012|newspaper=The Independent|date=11 November 2011}}</ref> His paternal grandfather was from [[Tuam]], which is also the birthplace of his father.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IwrO4OQE2gYC&pg=PA173&lpg=PA173&dq=%22gypsy+john+fury%22+tuam&source=bl&ots=BhIEYiAJjS&sig=pBCDjf5EGpTZOUgZUmm51ijmI7k&hl=en&sa=X&ei=9zYXVfzLApftaPGdgOgB&ved=0CBsQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=%22gypsy%20john%20fury%22%20tuam&f=false|title=Gypsy Empire|work=google.ie}}</ref> The Furys are ultimately of [[Gaels|Gaelic]] origin, deriving their present surname from \u00d3 Fiodhabhra.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.furey.name/history.htm|publisher=Clan Furey|title=The Furey/Fury family name History|date=12 December 2015|access-date=21 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151115211002/http://www.furey.name/history.htm|archive-date=15 November 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Fury's maternal grandmother is from [[County Tipperary]] and his mother was born in [[Belfast]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/people/the-fight-and-the-fury-1.1366134|title=The fight and the fury|date=20 April 2013|work=The Irish Times}}</ref><ref name=\"Irish debut\">[http://www.rte.ie/sport/boxing/2009/0917/furyt.html Tyson Fury added to Dunne card]{{dead link|date=November 2015}}, [[RT\u00c9 Sport]], Thursday, 17 September 2009 17:17</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/boxing/14904158|title=Boxer Fury finds Irish roots|date=13 September 2011|work=BBC Sport|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418082543/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/boxing/14904158|archivedate=18 April 2015|accessdate=12 February 2015}}</ref> Despite strongly identifying with his Irish heritage,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Tyson_Fury/status/344507509903597569|title=The greatest British Irish fighter who ever lived!king Tyson fury|last=FURY|first=TYSON|date=2013-06-11|website=@Tyson_Fury|language=en|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Tyson_Fury/status/636536515183706112|title=Irish blood, English heart this I'm made of, there is no1 on earth I'm afraid of,  especially not this Russian prick ,|last=FURY|first=TYSON|date=2015-08-26|website=@Tyson_Fury|language=en|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> Fury has had problems in gaining dual citizenship because his father's birth in County Galway was not recorded civilly in the 1960s, as Irish Travellers at the time only recorded births through baptism with the church rather than officially with the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://irishpost.co.uk/how-ireland-missed-out-on-its-first-official-world-heavyweight-champion-in-tyson-fury/|title=How Ireland missed out on its first official world heavyweight champion in Tyson Fury|website=The Irish Post|access-date=22 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nFury left school when he was 11, and joined his father and three brothers [[Asphalt concrete|tarmacking roads]]. His mother Amber had 14 pregnancies in total, but only four of the children survived. A daughter, Ramona, was born in December 1997 but died within days. This experience has stayed with Fury, who was just nine years old at the time. Fury began boxing at the age of 10.<ref name=\"Rayner\" /> His father acted as his trainer until 2011, when his father was jailed for gouging out the eye of another Traveller due to a long-standing feud;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/father-of-boxing-champion-tyson-fury-853780|title=Father of boxing champion Tyson Fury jailed for gouging a man's eye out after a 12 year feud over a bottle of beer|last=News|first=Manchester Evening|date=2011-02-14|website=men|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> Fury himself was raised to keep the fighting within the ring and has not had trouble with the law.<ref name=Rayner>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/boxing/tyson-fury/12033558/Profile-Tyson-Fury-lion-hearted-champion-with-a-talent-for-controversy.html|title=Tyson Fury: a lion-hearted champion with a talent for controversy|last=Rayner|first=Gordon|date=2015-12-07|access-date=2019-09-11|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> \n\nThe Fury family has a long history in boxing.<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite news|author=Staff|title=Tyson Fury profile|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/boxingandmma/3568972/Tyson-Fury-the-new-British-giant-on-the-heavyweight-block-Boxing-and-MMA.html|accessdate=20 April 2009|work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London, UK|date=6 December 2008}}</ref> Fury's father competed in the 1980s as \"Gypsy\" John Fury,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/boxing/11367625/Tyson-Fury-fired-up-by-the-return-of-his-father-from-prison.html|title=Tyson Fury fired up by the return of his father from prison|date=24 January 2015|work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London}}</ref> initially as a [[Bare-knuckle boxing|bare-knuckle]] and unlicensed boxer, and then as a professional boxer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/boxing/26153811|title=Tyson Fury: I'm not interested in being a role model|author=Ben Dirs|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref> John had a professional record of 8\u20134\u20131, with one of his losses being to future WBO heavyweight world champion [[Henry Akinwande]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boxrec.com/en/proboxer/27680|title=BoxRec: John Fury|website=boxrec.com|access-date=2019-10-11}}</ref> Tyson's half-brother [[Tommy Fury|Tommy]] made his professional debut on 22 December 2018 under the tutelage of two-weight world champion [[Ricky Hatton]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/46456676|title=Tommy Fury: Tyson my motivation, says brother before debut|date=5 December 2018|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> and he starred in the [[Love Island (2015 TV series, series 5)|2019 series]] of ''[[Love Island (2015 TV series)|Love Island]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://talksport.com/sport/boxing/628792/tommy-fury-exclusive-tyson-love-island-great-fighter/|title=Tommy Fury: I have made my own name... now I want to become a great fighter|last=Varney|first=Alex|date=2019-11-12|website=[[TalkSPORT]]|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref> Fury is also a cousin of several professional boxers, including heavyweights [[Hughie Fury]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/boxing/9916100/Tyson-Fury-and-cousin-Hughie-Fury-poised-to-become-the-new-Klitschkos.html|title=Tyson Fury and cousin Hughie Fury poised to become the 'new Klitschkos'|date=7 March 2013|work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London}}</ref> and [[Nathan Gorman (boxer)|Nathan Gorman]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://staffslive.co.uk/2018/11/nathan-gorman-backs-cousin-tyson-fury-to-topple-deontay-wilder/|title=Nathan Gorman backs cousin Tyson Fury to topple Deontay Wilder|date=2018-11-30|website=StaffsLive Journalism|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref> retired WBO [[middleweight]] world champion [[Andy Lee (boxer)|Andy Lee]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailystar.co.uk/sport/boxing/481075/Tyson-Fury-told-to-keep-his-mouth-shut-by-cousin-Andy-Lee-after-controversial-comments/|title=Redirect Notice|last=|first=|date=|website=www.google.com|access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref> and [[light heavyweight]] contender [[Hosea Burton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2016/12/11/tyson-fury-infuriated-he-is-made-pay-200-to-watch-cousin-fight-on-anthony-joshua-undercard|title=Redirect Notice|last=|first=|date=|website=www.google.com|access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref> Fury's distant relatives include the bare-knuckle boxers Uriah Burton and [[Bartley Gorman]], both considered \"[[King of the Gypsies]]\",<ref>The Independent, 30 November 2011</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/tyson-fury-reflections-of-a-gypsy-fighter-2377876.html|title=Tyson Fury: Reflections of a gypsy fighter|author=Alan Hubbard|date=29 October 2011|work=The Independent|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Duggan |first1=Keith |title=The fight and the fury |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/people/the-fight-and-the-fury-1.1366134 |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=20 April 2013}}</ref> hence Fury's own nickname of \"Gypsy King\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/boxing/wladimir-klitschko-vs-tyson-fury-6890067|title=Nine things you didn't know about Tyson Fury ahead of Wladimir Klitschko fight|last=Lewis|first=Matt|website=mirror|access-date=22 March 2016}}</ref> He has also styled himself as \"The Furious One\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxingnews24.com/2015/11/tyson-fury-the-furious-one/|title=Tyson Fury: The Furious One|website=Boxing News 24|access-date=22 March 2016}}</ref> and \"2 Fast\" Fury.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/tyson_fury/status/315551607855120385|title=Gypsy King on Twitter|website=Twitter|access-date=22 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Amateur boxing career==\nAs an amateur, Fury represented both England and Ireland. Fury represented Ireland three times at international level. He was based at of the Holy Family Boxing Club in [[Belfast]], [[Northern Ireland]], and later switched to the Smithboro Club in [[County Monaghan]] in the [[Republic of Ireland]].<ref name=\"inside\">{{cite web | author= | title=Tyson Fury looking for English and Irish title double | url=http://www.insideboxing.com/pressreleases/tyson_fury_looking_for_english_a.htm  | work= Inside Boxing | accessdate=20 April 2009}}{{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> In a double international match against an experienced [[Poles|Polish]] team in 2007, the Irish team lost 12\u20136 overall; Fury, however, was victorious in both his fights in [[Rzesz\u00f3w]] and [[Bia\u0142ystok]].<ref name=\"Bernard O'Neill\">{{cite web|author=Bernard O'Neill |title=Golden year for Irish boxing. He fought under Jimmy Egans Boxing, the club that made him to the standard he is. |url=http://www.irishnews.com/searchlog.asp?reason=denied_empty&script_name=/pageacc.asp&path_info=/pageacc.asp&tser1=ser&par=ben&sid=575740 |accessdate=20 April 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208125453/http://www.irishnews.com/searchlog.asp?reason=denied_empty&script_name=%2Fpageacc.asp&path_info=%2Fpageacc.asp&tser1=ser&par=ben&sid=575740 |archivedate=8 December 2015 }}</ref> In another Irish match against the US, Fury won his bout by knockout.<ref name=\"David Kelly\"/> He won bronze at the [[AIBA Youth World Boxing Championships]] in 2006.<ref name=\"boxrecfury\">{{cite web |url=http://boxrec.com/list_bouts.php?human_id=479205&cat=boxer |title=Tyson Fury \u2013 Boxer |publisher=Boxrec.com |date= |accessdate=13 November 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150616191458/http://boxrec.com/list_bouts.php?human_id=479205&cat=boxer |archive-date=16 June 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn England, whilst representing Jimmy Egan's Boxing Academy in Wythenshawe, Manchester, he participated in the [[Amateur Boxing Association of England|senior national championships]] in 2006 but was beaten by [[David Price (boxer)|David Price]] 22\u20138.<ref name=\"Boxing scene\">{{cite web | author=Mark Vester | title=\"Tyson Fury- \"I'd Smash David Price's Face in. | url=http://www.boxingscene.com/?m=show&id=19394 | accessdate=20 April 2009}}</ref> In May 2007, he won the EU Junior Championship, defeating Istvan Bernath in the final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://amateur-boxing.strefa.pl/Championships/EuropeanUnionj2007.html |title=EuropeanUnionJunior2007 |work=Amateur-boxing.strefa.pl |date=}}</ref> In July 2007 he won silver at the European Junior Championship, losing to [[Maxim Babanin]] in the final.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{cite news|last=Davies |first=Gareth A |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/boxing/11988862/Wladimir-Klitschko-v-Tyson-Fury-The-life-and-times-of-Tyson-Fury.html |title=Wladimir Klitschko v Tyson Fury: The life and times of Tyson Fury |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://amateur-boxing.strefa.pl/Championships/EuropeanJuniorChampionships2007.html |title=EuropeanJuniorChampionships2007 |publisher=Amateur-boxing.strefa.pl |date= |accessdate=2019-10-28}}</ref>\n\nAs a junior, Fury was ranked number three in the world behind the Russians Maxim Babanin and Andrey Volkov, but did not get the chance to represent Great Britain at the [[Boxing at the 2008 Summer Olympics|2008 Olympics]] because each country is restricted to one boxer per weight division and David Price was selected. Price came up through the amateur Olympic programme. Fury also unsuccessfully tried to qualify for Ireland.<ref>{{cite news|last=Davies |first=Gareth A |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/boxing/11988862/Wladimir-Klitschko-v-Tyson-Fury-The-life-and-times-of-Tyson-Fury.html |title=Wladimir Klitschko v Tyson Fury: The life and times of Tyson Fury |work=The Daily Telegraph |date= |accessdate=2018-11-30}}</ref> He was also forced to withdraw from the [[Irish Amateur Boxing Association|Irish national championships]] after officials from the Holy Trinity Boxing Club in West Belfast, the club of the then Irish amateur heavyweight champion, submitted a protest regarding his eligibility as he was not born in Ireland.<ref name=\"David Kelly\">{{cite web | first=David |last=Kelly | title=Tyson Fury- 'English' Tyson is causing a real fury in Dublin | url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/sport/other-sports/boxing-english-tyson-is-causing-a-real-fury-in-dublin-13373437.html | accessdate=20 April 2009 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080922141533/http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/sport/other-sports/boxing-english-tyson-is-causing-a-real-fury-in-dublin-13373437.html |work=Belfast Telegraph| archive-date=22 September 2008 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=MENFuryous>{{cite web|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/boxing/s/1055579_furyous_tyson_to_hit_back_|title=Fury-ous Tyson to hit back|author=Stuart Brennan|date=19 April 2010|work=men}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/sport/boxing/tyson-fury-fans-hoping-he-returns-to-belfast-to-show-off-world-title-belts-34244085.html|title=Tyson fury fans hoping he returns to Belfast to show off world title belts|first=Nevin|last=Farrell|website=Belfast Telegraph|date=29 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nFury won the [[England Boxing|ABA]] [[super-heavyweight]] title in 2008 by defeating Damien Campbell 19:1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://amateur-boxing.strefa.pl/Nationalchamps/England2008.html|title=England2008|website=amateur-boxing.strefa.pl|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref> He turned professional later that year.<ref name=\"Telegraph\" /> Feeling disillusioned with amateur boxing, he decided not to wait for the 2012 Olympics.<ref name=MENFuryous/> He finished with an amateur record of 31\u20134 (26 KOs).<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/>\n\n==Professional boxing career==\n===Early career===\n[[File:Tyson fury.jpg|thumb|266x266px|Fury after his professional debut on 6 December 2008]]\nFury made his professional debut at the age of 20 on 6 December 2008 in Nottingham, on the undercard of [[Carl Froch vs. Jean Pascal]] against Hungarian fighter Bela Gyongyosi (3-9-2), who Fury defeated via TKO in the first round with a combination to head and body.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.boxingnews24.com/2009/04/tyson-fury-the-short-story/|title=Tyson Fury: The Short Story \u22c6 Boxing News 24|date=2009-04-18|website=Boxing News 24|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-01}}</ref> He then had six more fights in the space of seven months, defeating [[Marcel Zeller]] (21-3), Daniil Peratyakto (15-20), [[Lee Swaby]] (23-22-2), Matthew Ellis (20-6-1), [[Scott Belshaw]] (10-1) and Aleksandrs Selezens (3-6) all via knockout within 4 rounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/tyson-fury-blows-aleksandrs-selezens-away-three--21096|title=Tyson Fury Blows Aleksandrs Selezens Away in Three|website=BoxingScene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2019-09-01}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 September 2009, Fury fought [[John McDermott (boxer)|John McDermott]] (25-5, 16 KOs) for the English heavyweight title, and won via a [[points decision]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/boxing/8252037.stm|title=Fury stuns McDermott in title win|last=|first=|date=12 September 2009|website=BBC Boxing|publisher=|access-date=7 January 2017}}</ref> Fury came in as a 1\u20136 favourite but produced a poor display, and the 98\u201392 decision by the referee Terry O'Connor was criticised as a \"travesty\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Kevin |last=Mitchell |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2009/sep/14/mcdermott-fury-english-heavyweight-boxing |title=John McDermott's defeat to Tyson Fury was a travesty of historic proportions |work=The Guardian |date=14 September 2009}}</ref> The decision led the British Boxing Board of Control to mandate three judges for all English titles, and the board ordered a rematch.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite news|last=Davies |first=Gareth A |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/boxing/7855554/Tyson-Fury-too-strong-for-John-McDermott-as-he-wins-heavyweight-clash-in-round-nine.html |title=Tyson Fury too strong for John McDermott as he wins heavyweight clash in round nine |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=2010-06-26}}</ref>\n\nFury scored two more victories against Tomas Mrazek (4-22-5) and Hans-Joerg Blasko (9-3) before facing McDermott in a rematch on 25 June 2010. Fury settled the controversy of the first fight, as he knocked down McDermott three times, first in the 8th round then twice in the 9th round to win by TKO. Fury won the English heavyweight title for a second time in the process.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> Another three wins followed: a points decisions over American fighters Rich Power (12-0) and Zack Page (21-32-2) in two 8-round matches, and a knockout of the Brazilian Marcelo Luis Nacimento (13-0) in the 5th round.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxing.com/hennessy_boxing_tyson_fury_vs_marcelo_luiz_nascimento.html|title=Hennessy Boxing: Tyson Fury Vs Marcelo Luiz Nascimento - Boxing.com|website=www.boxing.com|access-date=2019-09-01}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 July 2011, Fury faced undefeated heavyweight [[Dereck Chisora]] for the British and Commonwealth heavyweight titles at Wembley Arena in London. Although Chisora was aged 27 and Fury just 22 years old, both men went into the fight with a record of 14\u20130. Despite Fury's superior size and reach, Chisora was the favourite. After 12 hard-fought rounds Fury won via unanimous decision 117\u2013112, 117\u2013112, and 118\u2013111, with the fight shown live on free-to-air [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/14243725|title=Heavyweight Tyson Fury beats Dereck Chisora on points|last=|first=|date=23 July 2011|website=BBC Boxing|publisher=|access-date=7 January 2017}}</ref> Promoter [[Mick Hennessy]] said the fight peaked at around 3 million viewers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.badlefthook.com/2011/7/25/2292419/chisora-vs-fury-does-strong-ratings-on-channel-5+&cd=2&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=uk|title=Chisora vs Fury Does Strong Ratings on Channel 5|work=Bad Left Hook|access-date=3 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 September 2011, Fury fought 32-year-old fringe contender Nicolai Firtha (20\u20138\u20131, 8 KO) in a non-title bout at the [[King's Hall, Belfast|King's Hall]], Belfast. Firtha took the fight on two weeks' notice. The opening two rounds were dominated by Fury. In round 3, Firtha landed a big punch which looked to trouble Fury. Fury regained control of the fight by the next round and forced the referee to stop the fight at 2 minutes, 19 seconds on round 5. Fury admitted he got caught flush, \"He caught me with a good punch and I had to come back from it.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/14960740|title=Tyson Fury stops Nicolai Firtha in fifth round|date=17 September 2011|work=BBC Sport|access-date=22 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=\u0418\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0432\u0441\u044f\u0447\u0438\u043d\u0430|title=Tyson Fury 16th Fight Fury vs Nicolai Firtha|date=12 November 2015|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-lOa42Moft4|accessdate=22 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.badlefthook.com/2011/9/20/2437254/tyson-fury-vs-firtha-results-recap-knockout-early-stoppage+&cd=4&hl=en&ct=clnk&g|title=After the Fact Recap: Tyson Fury Stops Nicolai Firtha in Front of Raucous Belfast Fans|work=Bad Left Hook|access-date=22 September 2017}}</ref> The fight averaged 1.03 million viewers on Channel 5.<ref name=\"barb.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.barb.co.uk/viewing-data/weekly-top-30/|title=Weekly top 30 programmes {{!}} BARB|website=www.barb.co.uk|access-date=25 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nFury returned to the ring on 12 November at the [[EventCity|Event City]] in [[Trafford Park|Trafford Park, Manchester]] to defend his Commonwealth heavyweight title against undefeated Canadian heavyweight champion [[Neven Pajkic]]  (16-0, 5 KOs). Fury suffered an early scare after being knocked down in round 2 following a big right hand. Although Pajkic hobbled Fury again at the outset of round 3, Fury came back to knock down Pajkic twice during that round. The referee stopped the fight after the last knockdown, much to the protest of Pajkic, who declared himself ready to fight on. Many at ringside thought the stoppage premature.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/15709929|title=Tyson Fury stops Neven Pajkic to defend Commonwealth heavyweight title|date=12 November 2011|work=BBC Sport|access-date=22 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=HomeOfBritishBoxing|title=Tyson Fury vs Neven Pajkic Full Fight|date=13 November 2011|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ese1YPpw5mE|accessdate=22 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/boxing/8886867/Tyson-Fury-defends-Commonwealth-title-in-Manchester-against-Neven-Pajkic-despite-knockdown.html|title=Tyson Fury defends Commonwealth title in Manchester against Neven Pajkic, despite knockdown|last=Telegraph staff and agencies|date=13 November 2011|access-date=22 September 2017|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> The fight averaged 1.72 million viewers on Channel 5.<ref name=\"barb.co.uk\"/>\n\nFury vacated his British and Commonwealth belts in order to pursue a future world title match. Speaking to the media he spoke of his decision to vacate the belts, \"I vacated the British and Commonwealth titles, which some people say are more prestigious than the Irish title, but not to me. I vacated those belts for an Irish title shot because it meant more to me. All my people are from Ireland. I was born in Manchester but I am Irish.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.irish-boxing.com/2012/11/tyson-fury-i-fight-for-ireland-i-am-no-plastic-paddy/|title=Fury vacates Commonwealth and British titles \"I fight for Ireland\"|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}{{dead link|date=March 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>.  On 14 April 2012, Fury traveled to Belfast to fight at the Odyssey Arena for the vacant Irish heavyweight title. His opponent was veteran [[Martin Rogan]] (14\u20132, 7 KOs). Rogan had not fought in 18 months and had not beaten an opponent with a winning record since 2009.  At {{convert|245+3/4|lb|kg}}, Fury was fighting at the lightest weight of his professional career to date. Fury put Rogan on the canvas with a left hook in the third round. Rogan went down again in round 5 from a body shot. Rogan made it to his feet, but the bout was stopped at the request of his corner.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/17704857|title=Tyson Fury stops veteran Martin Rogan in Belfast bout|date=14 April 2012|work=BBC Sport|access-date=22 September 2017}}</ref> The fight averaged 1.33 million viewers on Channel 5.<ref name=\"barb.co.uk\"/>\n\nOn 7 July, Fury fought for the vacant [[World Boxing Organization|WBO]] Inter-Continental heavyweight title against American boxer [[Vinny Maddalone]] (35\u20137, 26 KOs) at the Hand Arena in [[Clevedon|Clevedon, Somerset]]. Fury weighed {{convert|245.5|lb|kg}}, marginally lighter than the Rogan fight. Maddalone entered with a record of 4\u20133 in his previous seven bouts. Fury improved his record to 19\u20130 with 14 stoppage wins, with a fifth-round technical knockout over Maddalone. Fury controlled the fight from the onset and stunned Maddalone with a combination in the opening round. Fury continued to land heavy punches and opened a cut under his opponent's left eye in the fourth. In round 5, with Maddalone taking punches, the referee stepped in and called an end to the bout with blood streaming out of the cut under the veteran's left eye. It was the fifth knockout loss of Maddalone's professional career. In the post-fight interviews, Fury said, \"I knew it was a matter of time. I actually called the referee over, he was taking some big shots. I'm still undefeated. I would like to say I'm ready for anyone in the world. Klitschkos, bring them on. Americans, bring them on. Bring on [[Tomasz Adamek]]. He's too small for me and I see an early win for me.\" Promoter [[Mick Hennessy]] also stated a world title fight was \"two or three fights away\", targeting Adamek next.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/18758257|title=Tyson Fury stops Vinny Maddalone to remain unbeaten|date=7 July 2012|work=BBC Sport|access-date=22 September 2017}}</ref> The fight averaged 1.05 million viewers on Channel 5.<ref name=\"barb.co.uk\"/>\n\n===Rise through the ranks===\nOn 12 November 2012, it was announced that Fury would fight American world title contender [[Kevin Johnson (boxer)|Kevin Johnson]] (28\u20133\u20131, 13 KOs) in a [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] title eliminator at the [[Odyssey (Belfast)|Odyssey Arena]] in Belfast on 1 December. Fury said, \"Johnson is just the kind of opponent that I want at this stage of my career. We needed a world class fighter and we have got one.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.proboxing-fans.com/tyson-fury-vs-kevin-johnson-wbc-title-eliminator-on-saturday_112712/|title=Tyson Fury vs. Kevin Johnson WBC title eliminator on Saturday|work=ProBoxing-Fans.com|access-date=21 September 2017}}</ref> Fury won via unanimous decision over Johnson. After 12 rounds, the judges scored it 119\u2013110, 119\u2013108, and 119\u2013108 in favour of Fury. Many media outlets including the BBC and ESPN dubbed the fight as a poor showing. Fury claimed he would score a good win, just as rival [[David Price (boxer)|David Price]] did when he stopped [[Matt Skelton]] a night earlier, but instead eased to a decision victory. Fury, with the win, was in line to challenge for the WBC title, held at the time by Vitali Klitschko.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.espn.co.uk/boxing/sport/story/181923.html|title=Fury booed as he outpoints Johnson|last=|first=|date=1 December 2012|website=Boxing Scene|publisher=|access-date=7 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.badlefthook.com/2012/12/1/3715768/fury-vs-johnson-results-wbc-eliminator-decision-scores-boxing-news|title=Tyson Fury wins WBC eliminator on wide decision|last=|first=|date=1 December 2012|website=|publisher=|access-date=7 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.espn.co.uk/boxing/sport/story/181923.html|title=Fury booed as he outpoints Johnson|work=ESPN.co.uk|access-date=21 September 2017}}</ref> The fight averaged 1.37 million viewers on Channel 5.<ref name=\"barb.co.uk\"/>\n\nOn 20 February 2013, it was reported that Fury would fight highly ranked American former cruiserweight world champion [[Steve Cunningham]] (25\u20135, 12 KOs) in his United States debut at [[Madison Square Garden Theater]] on 20 April. The bout was an IBF title eliminator to determine the number 2 world ranking, with the winner then needing to fight unbeaten Bulgarian heavyweight [[Kubrat Pulev]] for the mandatory position for a shot at the long reigning world champion [[Wladimir Klitschko]]. Cunningham came into the fight on the rebound from a controversial split decision loss to [[Tomasz Adamek]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fightsaga.com/news/item/2923-Tyson-Fury-vs-Steve-Cunningham-Confirmed-for-April-20|title=Tyson Fury vs Steve Cunningham Confirmed for April 20|last=Press Release|first=|access-date=21 September 2017}}</ref> At the weigh in, Cunningham was {{convert|44|lb|kg}} lighter, at {{convert|210|lb|kg}} to Fury's {{convert|254|lb|kg}}.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingnews24.com/2013/04/fury-with-41-pound-weight-advantage-over-cunningham/|title=Fury with {{convert|44|lb|kg}} weight advantage over Cunningham |date=19 April 2013|work=Boxing News 24|access-date=21 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nFury fought wildly in the first two rounds of the bout, and was floored by Cunningham in the 2nd round. However, Fury rebounded and handed Cunningham the first knockout defeat of his career with a right hand in the seventh round. Fury was also docked a point in round 5 following a headbutt.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/new-york/story/_/id/9194051/tyson-fury-stops-steve-cunningham-win-us-debut |title=Tyson Fury wins U.S. debut |date=20 April 2013 |accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/22235044|title=Tyson Fury knocks out Steve Cunningham in New York|last=|first=|date=20 April 2013|website=BBC Boxing|publisher=|access-date=7 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/queensberry-rules-boxing-blog/2013/apr/25/tyson-fury-us-debut|title=Tyson Fury makes a mess of his US debut against Steve Cunningham|last=Harrison|first=Andrew|date=25 April 2013|website=The Guardian|publisher=|access-date=7 January 2017}}</ref> A week after the fight, Cunningham spoke to ATG Radio, claiming that Fury used an illegal manoeuvre to knock him out, \"He held me with his forearm. He pushed me in the corner twice \u2013 which is illegal \u2013 and then he pushed me with his forearm, cocked my head to the left and threw a right hook.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.espn.co.uk/boxing/sport/story/204042.html|author=ESPN staff|title=Cunningham caught in F-word Fury|work=ESPN.co.uk|date=24 April 2013|access-date=21 September 2017}}</ref> The fight card aired on NBC in the late afternoon and averaged 1.2 million viewers, peaking at 1.7 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doghouseboxing.com/DHB/Paras-051313-New.htm|title=Main Events, NBC Pleased with Tyson Fury vs. Steve Cunningham TV Ratings|website=www.doghouseboxing.com|access-date=21 September 2017}}</ref> In the UK, the fight aired on Channel 5 and averaged 1.54 million viewers.<ref name=\"barb.co.uk\"/> The win over Cunningham gave Fury a world ranking of 7 according to [[BoxRec]], a number 2 ranking according to the [[International Boxing Federation|IBF]], 6th with the [[World Boxing Council|WBC]], and 5th with the [[World Boxing Organization|WBO]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fightnews.com/rankings-2 |title=Boxing Rankings &#124; WBC, WBA, WBO, IBF |publisher=Fightnews |date= |accessdate=11 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nFury was due to fight [[David Haye]] (26\u20132, 24 KOs) on 28 September 2013, in a fight which would have seen Fury fight on a pay-per-view platform for the first time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/23235561|title=David Haye v Tyson Fury: Fight on for 28 September in Manchester|date=9 July 2013|work=BBC Sport|access-date=21 September 2017}}</ref> However, Haye pulled out of the fight on 21 September, after sustaining a cut, which required six stitches, above the eye during training.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/boxing/10312568/David-Haye-believes-Tyson-Furys-superior-height-and-weight-will-count-for-nought-in-September-28-clash.html|title= David Haye believes Tyson Fury's superior height and weight will count for nought in September 28 clash|date=14 September 2013|work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/boxing/24185997 David Haye Postpones Tyson Fury Fight after Sustaining Cut] www.bbc.co.uk</ref> The fight was originally postponed to 8 February 2014. Haye pulled out of the fight a second time on 17 November, stating that he had a career-threatening shoulder injury which required surgery, and hinted at his retirement.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mike Costello |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/boxing/24981216 |title=David Haye advised to retire after major shoulder surgery |work=BBC Sport |date=17 November 2013 |accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref> Fury believed that Haye was making excuses because he did not want the fight, saying \"I'm absolutely furious but in all honesty this is exactly what I expected. Everyone knows I was very suspicious when he pulled out the first time and this confirms to me that he's always been afraid of me and never wanted this fight.\" Aside from training camp expenses, Haye also cost Fury his positions in the world rankings including an IBF final eliminator bout which would have made him mandatory for a shot at the world title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.espn.co.uk/boxing/sport/story/258495.html|title=Fury: 'Scared' Haye never wanted to face me|website=ESPN.co.uk|access-date=20 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 January 2014 it was announced that Fury would fight at the Copper Box Arena against Argentine veteran [[Gonzalo Basile|Gonzalo Omar Basile]] (61\u20138, 27KO) on 15 February.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/25883694|title=Tyson Fury to fight Gonzalo Omar Basile at Copper Box|date=2014|work=BBC Sport|access-date=7 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.espn.co.uk/boxing/sport/story/276749.html|title=Fury ready to face experienced Basile|work=ESPN.co.uk|access-date=7 October 2017}}</ref> On 5 February, Basile pulled out of the fight due to a lung infection. He was replaced by American journeyman [[Joey Abell]] (29\u20137, 28 KOs).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/tyson-fury-now-faces-joey-abell-replacing-ill-basile--74377|title=Tyson Fury Now Faces Joey Abell, Replacing Ill Basile - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|access-date=7 October 2017}}</ref> Fury won the fight via 4th-round TKO, which set up a rematch with Chisora in the summer. Ring rust showed in the opening two rounds with Abell connecting with left hands, which had Fury against the ropes. But Fury managed to compose himself and get behind the jab. In the third round, Fury floored Abell with a right hand. Abell beat the count but was floored again, this time being saved by the bell. Two more knockdowns followed in round 4 ending the fight.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.espn.co.uk/boxing/sport/story/283689.html|title=Fury and Chisora lay down markers for summer showdown|work=ESPN.co.uk|access-date=7 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.badlefthook.com/2014/2/15/5415106/fury-vs-abell-results-tyson-fury-stops-joey-abell-in-four-but-not|title=Fury vs Abell results: Tyson Fury stops Joey Abell in four, but not without struggles|first=Scott|last=Christ|work=Bad Left Hook|date=15 February 2014|access-date=7 October 2017}}</ref> After the fight, Fury took to the microphone, \"Tyson too fast Fury, that's the name, fighting's the game and these are bums compared to me. I want [[Wladimir Klitschko]], he's avoiding me, let's get it on Wlad.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/9169001/tyson-fury-halts-joey-abell-in-fourth-round-after-wild-heavyweight-brawl-in-london|title=Tyson Fury halts Joey Abell in fourth round after wild heavyweight brawl in London|work=Sky Sports|access-date=7 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===European heavyweight champion===\nFury was due to fight rival and heavyweight contender [[Dereck Chisora]] for the second time on 26 July 2014, for the European and once again the British heavyweight title.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/mar/17/fury-chisora-rematch-boxing-heavyweights-manchester|title=Dereck Chisora v Tyson Fury rematch announced for 26 July|date=17 March 2014|work=The Guardian|access-date=21 September 2017|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> On 21 July, Chisora was forced to pull out after sustaining a fractured hand in training. Belarusian [[Alexander Ustinov]] was lined up as Chisora's replacement in the bout scheduled to take place at the [[Manchester Arena]],<ref>\"[http://www1.skysports.com/boxing/news/12040/9391643/tyson-fury-to-take-on-alexander-ustinov-after-dereck-chisora-withdrawal Tyson Fury to take on Alexander Ustinov after Dereck Chisora withdrawal]\", Sky Sports, 23 July 2014. Retrieved 24 July 2014</ref> Fury pulled out of the fight after his uncle and former trainer Hughie Fury was taken seriously ill.<ref>Press Association (26 July 2014), \"[https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/jul/26/tyson-fury-withdraws-alexander-ustinov-fight Tyson Fury pulls out of Alexander Ustinov fight after uncle taken ill]\", ''The Guardian''. Retrieved 28 July 2014</ref> However, Fury and Chisora rescheduled the rematch for 29 November 2014 at [[ExCeL London]]. The bout was also a WBO title eliminator and shown live on [[BoxNation]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/28722704|title=Tyson Fury to face Dereck Chisora in London rematch|date=15 September 2014|work=BBC Sport|access-date=21 September 2017}}</ref> Fury was victorious again after dominating the fight up until Chisora's corner pulled him out at the end of the 10th round. Fury also used a southpaw stance for the majority of the fight, despite the traditional right-handed orthodox stance being his preference. Fury used his jab to trouble Chisora and stayed on the outside with his longer reach to dominate the fight. Chisora failed to land any telling punches, and due to Fury's awkward fighting style, ended up hitting him below the belt. Chisora was warned by referee Marcus McDonnell in the first round. After the fight, Fury said, \"Wladimir Klitschko, I'm coming for you, baby. I'm coming. No retreat, no surrender.\" Promoter [[Mick Hennessy]] said Fury would likely fight once more before challenging for the world title.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/30247385|title=Tyson Fury beats Dereck Chisora in world title eliminator|last=Excel|first=Ben Dirs BBC Sport at London's|website=BBC Sport|access-date=20 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/boxing/tyson-fury-vs-dereck-chisora-2-report-fury-the-winner-after-chisora-retires-following-10-rounds-of-9893301.html|title=Tyson Fury vs Dereck Chisora 2: Fury the winner after Chisora retires following 10 painful rounds|last=|first=|date=30 November 2014|website=|publisher=|access-date=7 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/11956360/tyson-fury-dominates-dereck-chisora-earn-world-title-shot|title=Fury dominates Chisora to earn world title shot|work=ESPN.com|access-date=21 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 December 2014, Sky Sports News announced that Fury would fight once more before challenging Klitschko for his world titles. His opponent was [[Christian Hammer]] (17\u20133, 10 KOs) and the fight took place on 28 February 2015 at the [[The O2 Arena|O2 Arena]] in London. Fury said he went for an opponent that would give him a challenge rather than an \"easier\" opponent, before challenging Klitschko.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12040/9620025/undefeated-heavyweight-tyson-fury-returns-to-the-ring-against-christian-hammer-in-the-new-year|title=Undefeated heavyweight Tyson Fury returns to the ring against Christian Hammer in the New Year|work=Sky Sports|access-date=21 September 2017}}</ref> Fury went on to win the fight when it came to a halt in the 8th round via [[Referee technical decision|RTD]]. Fury dominated the fight from the opening bell and dropped Hammer in round 5 following a short right hook. Following the fight, Fury called out Wladimir Klitschko again, stating he was ready for his world title shot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsmole.co.uk/boxing/result/result-fury-still-unbeaten-after-hammer-win_208404.html#$nykpaa&&hiXPBpaIEeWuEQp91fdxVw$|title=Result: Tyson Fury forces Christian Hammer to throw in the towel after eight rounds|work=Sports Mole|access-date=29 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208124737/http://www.sportsmole.co.uk/boxing/result/result-fury-still-unbeaten-after-hammer-win_208404.html#$nykpaa&&hiXPBpaIEeWuEQp91fdxVw$|archive-date=8 December 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/mar/01/tyson-fury-wladimir-klitschko-christian-hammer|title=Tyson Fury demands Wladimir Klitschko after beating Christian Hammer|last=Observer staff|date=28 February 2015|newspaper=The Guardian|issn=0261-3077|access-date=24 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2380617-tyson-fury-vs-christian-hammer-winner-recap-and-reaction|title=Fury Far Too Good for Hammer|last=Mazique|first=Brian|newspaper=Bleacher Report|date=28 February 2015|access-date=24 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Unified heavyweight world champion===\n{{Main|Wladimir Klitschko vs. Tyson Fury}}\nIn July 2015, it was confirmed that Fury would fight [[Wladimir Klitschko]] in a world heavyweight title showdown, for the [[World Boxing Association|WBA (Super)]], [[International Boxing Federation|IBF]], [[World Boxing Organization|WBO]], [[International Boxing Organization|IBO]], [[Lineal championship|Lineal]] and [[List of The Ring world champions|''The Ring'']] [[heavyweight]] titles. Initially scheduled for 24 October 2015, the fight was postponed to 28 November 2015 after Klitschko sustained a calf injury. For this match, Fury trained with the highest ranked heavyweight kickboxers in [[Glory (kickboxing)|GLORY]], [[Rico Verhoeven]] and [[Ben Adegbuyi|Benjamin Adegbuyi]].<ref>[http://www.fightsports.tv/story/30226184/ben-adegbuyi-talks-about-training-with-tyson-fury-ahead-of-glory-24 Ben Adegbuyi Talks About Training With Tyson Fury Ahead of GLORY 24]. Fightsports.tv (9 October 2015). Retrieved on 29 November 2015.</ref>\n\nThe fight took place at [[Esprit Arena]] in [[D\u00fcsseldorf]], Germany. Prior to the fight taking place on the night, there was much controversy, first starting with the gloves, then there was a complaint about the ring canvas. Klitchsko reportedly had his hands wrapped without a representative of Fury, so had to do them again. Fury won after twelve rounds by a unanimous decision. The judges scored the fight 115\u2013112, 115\u2013112, and 116\u2013111.<ref>Dirs, Ben (2015) \"[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/34956022 Tyson Fury beats Wladimir Klitschko to become world champion]\", [[BBC]], 29 November 2015. Retrieved 29 November 2015</ref> Klitschko and Fury showed little offence during the 12 rounds, but Fury was more active and did enough each round to take the decision. Klitschko landed 52 of 231 punches thrown (23%) and Fury landed 86 of 371 thrown (23%).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/14258171/tyson-fury-ends-wladimir-klitschko-heavyweight-reign|title=Scorecard: Fury ends Klitschko's heavyweight reign|date=2015-11-30|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nIn the post-fight interview, an emotional Fury said, \"This is a dream come true. We worked so hard for this. I've done it. It's hard to come to foreign countries and get decisions. It just means so much to me to come here and get the decision.\" He then took the microphone and thanked Klitschko, \"I'd like to say to Wladimir, you're a great champion. And thanks very much for having me. It was all fun and games during the buildup.\" Klitschko failed to throw his well-known right hand, mostly due to Fury's constant movement and mocking. He said, \"Tyson was the faster and better man tonight. I felt quite comfortable in the first six rounds, but I was astonished that Tyson was so fast in the second half as well. I couldn't throw my right hand because the advantage was the longer distance he had.\" Klitschko had a rematch clause in place.<ref>[http://www.totalsportek.com/boxing/wladimir-klitschko-vs-tyson-fury-fight-date/ Klitschko vs Tyson Fury Fight Rescheduled 28 November 2015]. Totalsportek.com (5 October 2015). Retrieved 28 November 2015.</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/14244433/tyson-fury-wins-unanimous-decision-wladimir-klitschko-become-world-heavyweight-champion|title=Fury ends Klitschko reign as heavyweight champ|work=ESPN.com|access-date=21 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 December 2015, the IBF stripped Fury of its title, as the contract for the fight against Klitschko included a rematch clause, precluding Fury from facing the IBF's mandatory challenger [[Vyacheslav Glazkov]]. Fury had held the IBF belt for only 10 days.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tyson Fury: World heavyweight champion stripped of IBF title|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/35047606|publisher=BBC News|date=8 December 2015|accessdate=9 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com/boxing/story/ibf-strips-heavyweight-title-belt-from-tyson-fury-120915|title=IBF confirms its heavyweight belt stripped from Tyson Fury over giving Klitschko rematch|date=9 December 2015|website=FOX Sports}}</ref>\n\n===Relinquishing world titles===\n{{See also|Wladimir Klitschko vs. Tyson Fury#Cancelled rematch}}\nFollowing months of negotiation, the rematch with Klitschko was announced on 8 April 2016, this time with the fight scheduled to take place in Fury's hometown of [[Manchester]] at the [[Manchester Arena]] on 9 July 2016. Despite agreeing terms for the rematch, Fury said he had \"no motivation\" and had gained an extreme amount of weight after the first fight, as he weighed over {{convert|330|lb|kg}} by April 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/36038621 |title=Tyson Fury: World heavyweight champion suffering 'racial abuse' |work=BBC Sport |date=2016-04-13}}</ref> On 24 June 2016, it was announced that this fight would be postponed to a later date due to Fury sustaining a sprained ankle in training.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/36624767 |title=Tyson Fury postpones Wladimir Klitschko rematch due to injury |work=BBC Sport |date=24 June 2016 |accessdate=30 November 2018}}</ref> On the same day, Fury and his cousin, [[Hughie Fury]], were charged by [[UK Anti-Doping]] \"with presence of a prohibited substance\", namely [[nandrolone]], from a sample taken 16 months previously in February 2015. Tyson and Hughie said that they \"strenuously deny\" the charge.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/36970816 |title=Tyson Fury: World heavyweight champion faces UK Anti-Doping charge |work=BBC Sport |date=4 August 2016 |accessdate=30 November 2018}}</ref> On 23 September, Fury again postponed the fight after being declared \"medically unfit\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/37456191 |title=Wladimir Klitschko v Tyson Fury postponed: World heavyweight rematch on hold |work=BBC Sport |date=23 September 2016 |accessdate=30 November 2018}}</ref> ESPN reported that Fury had failed a drug test for [[cocaine]] a day before the second postponement. Fury cited problems with [[Major depressive disorder|depression]] after the positive test for cocaine.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://metro.co.uk/2016/09/30/tyson-fury-tests-positive-for-cocaine-day-before-he-pulls-out-of-wladimir-klitschko-rematch-for-second-time-6163129/|title=Tyson Fury set to stripped of world titles after testing positive for cocaine|date=30 September 2016|website=Metro|access-date=30 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nFury's mental health deteriorated after winning the world titles. On 4 October 2016, in an interview with ''Rolling Stone'', Fury said \u201cI\u2019m going through a lot of personal demons, trying to shake them off, this has got nothing to do with my fighting \u2013 what I\u2019m going through right now is my personal life. I've not been in a gym for months. I've been going through depression. I just don't want to live anymore, if you know what I\u2019m saying. I've had total enough of it. Never mind cocaine. I just didn't care. I don't want to live anymore. So cocaine is a little minor thing compared to not wanting to live anymore. I am seeing help, but they can't do nothing for me. What I've got is incurable. I don't want to live. All the money in the world, fame and glory, means nothing if you're not happy. I'm seeing psychiatrists. They say I've got a version of [[Bipolar disorder|bipolar]]. I'm a manic depressive. I don't even want to wake up. I hope I die every day. And that's a bad thing to say when I've got three children and a lovely wife isn't it? But I don't want to live anymore. And if I could take me own life \u2013 and I wasn't a Christian \u2013 I'd take it in a second. I just hope someone kills me before I kill me self. I'll have to spend eternity in hell. I\u2019ve been out drinking, Monday to Friday to Sunday, and taking cocaine. I can\u2019t deal with it and the only thing that helps me is when I get drunk out of me mind.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-sports/world-heavyweight-champion-tyson-fury-ive-done-lots-of-cocaine-119571/|title=World Heavyweight Champion Tyson Fury: 'I've Done Lots of Cocaine'|last1=Bonner|first1=Stayton|last2=Bonner|first2=Stayton|date=4 October 2016|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/44340029|title=Tyson Fury on depression, drugs, drinking and his comeback fight|first=Matt|last=Davis|date=4 June 2018|publisher=BBC Sport|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 October 2016, pending investigation on an anti-doping case about his cocaine use, nandrolone findings, and being deemed medically unfit to fight, Fury decided to vacate the [[WBA (Unified)]], WBO, IBO heavyweight titles. He said \"I won the titles in the ring and I believe that they should be lost in the ring, but I'm unable to defend at this time and I have taken the hard and emotional decision to now officially vacate my treasured world titles and wish the next in-line contenders all the very best as I now enter another big challenge in my life which I know, like against Klitschko, I will conquer.\"<ref name=\"GiveMeSport\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.givemesport.com/891813-tyson-fury-releases-statement-after-vacating-world-titles?autoplay=on|title=Tyson Fury writes emotional 127-word statement after vacating world titles|date=13 October 2016|newspaper=GiveMeSport|access-date=13 October 2016}}</ref> Fury's promoter Mick Hennessy added: \"Tyson will still be the lineal world heavyweight champion in everyone's eyes. He beat the most dominant champion in the modern era of boxing on an amazing night in Germany to earn that accolade and that will never change. Whilst it's heartbreaking to see Tyson vacate the world titles that he worked so long and hard for all his life, what's paramount now is that he receives the medical treatment along with the love of his family and friends and the support of the boxing world to make a full recovery.\"<ref name=\"GiveMeSport\" /> Fury's decision was based on not having to put himself under constant media pressure, allowing him time to recover and receive professional medical help for his mental health problems, and spend time with his family. On 13 October, the [[British Boxing Board of Control]] decided to suspend Fury's boxing licence.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/boxing/tyson-fury-relinquishes-world-titles-12018162?|title=Tyson Fury relinquishes his world heavyweight titles|last=Keay|first=Sheldan|date=13 October 2016|newspaper=men|access-date=13 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/37641280|title=Tyson Fury: British Boxing Board of Control suspends fighter|date=13 October 2016|newspaper=BBC Sport|access-date=13 October 2016}}</ref> On 1 February 2018, Fury was stripped of his last remaining title, ''The Ring'' magazine's heavyweight championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11231863/tyson-fury-stripped-of-the-ring-title|title=Tyson Fury stripped of THE RING title|last=Dielhenn|first=James|date=1 February 2018|work=Sky Sports|accessdate=30 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Issues with UKAD and BBBofC===\nIn December 2016, Fury's uncle Peter announced that Fury would be returning around spring in 2017 and would aim for a fight against WBC champion [[Deontay Wilder]]. On 23 December, Fury tweeted that he was back in training ahead of a ring return around April or May 2017. His tweet read, \"I've had a nightmare 2016, done a lot of stuff I'm not proud of, but my promise to you is I'll return in 2017.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/peter-fury-tyson-fury-return-april-may-we-want-deontay-wilder--112047|title=P. Fury: Tyson Will Return in April/May, We Want Deontay Wilder |first=Edward|last=Chaykovsky|website=Boxing Scene|date=26 December 2016|access-date=24 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/boxing/tyson-fury-vows-return-boxing-12369259|title=Tyson Fury vows to return to the boxing ring in 2017|last=Keay|first=Sheldan|date=24 December 2016|newspaper=Manchester Evening News|access-date=24 December 2016}}</ref> On 6 March 2017, Fury tweeted that his return fight would take place on 13 May 2017 and he was speaking to promoter [[Frank Warren (promoter)|Frank Warren]] about possible opponents. Warren had become Fury's promoter after Fury dropped his long-time promoter Mick Hennessy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/granada/update/2017-03-06/tyson-fury-says-hell-be-back-fighting-on-may-13/|title=Tyson Fury says he'll be back fighting on May 13|work=ITV News|date=6 March 2017|access-date=7 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/39186463|title=Tyson Fury: Former heavyweight champion suggests May comeback|date=6 March 2017|work=BBC Sport|access-date=7 March 2017}}</ref> The date set for the return would mean Fury would be fighting on the undercard of [[Josh Warrington]] defending his WBC International featherweight title against [[Kiko Mart\u00ednez|Kiko Martinez]] at the [[First Direct Arena]] in Leeds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/tyson-fury-announces-ring-return-set-13-comeback--114305|title=Tyson Fury Announces Ring Return, Set For May 13 Comeback \u2013 ''Boxing News''|website=www.boxingscene.com|access-date=7 March 2017}}</ref> Hours after Fury announced a comeback date, the [[British Boxing Board of Control]] (BBBofC) publicly announced that Fury was still suspended and would not be fighting in May. This was confirmed by their general secretary Robert Smith. He also mentioned that there had been no contact from Fury or his representatives since the ban started in October 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://talksport.com/boxing/british-boxing-board-control-tyson-fury-will-not-be-making-boxing-return-may-he-hasnt|title=British Boxing Board of Control: Tyson Fury will NOT be making boxing return in May \u2013 'He hasn\u2019t contacted us. He\u2019s still suspended'|date=7 March 2017|work=talkSPORT|access-date=8 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/british-board-robert-smith-tyson-fury-not-position-box--114337|first=Elliot|last=Foster|title=British Board's Robert Smith: Tyson Fury Not In Position To Box! |website= Boxing Scene|date=7 March 2017|access-date=8 March 2017}}</ref> Warren told [[Reuters]] on 7 March, \"I want to see him back in the ring as soon as possible but before that happens he's got a couple of issues to sort out.\" Warren said that along with the dispute with the BBBofC there would need to be a court hearing with [[UK Anti-Doping]] (UKAD).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/frank-warren-on-tyson-fury-return-hearing-set-early--114343|title=Frank Warren on Tyson Fury's Return, Hearing Set For Early May \u2013 ''Boxing News''|website=www.boxingscene.com|access-date=8 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/tyson-fury-set-8-ukad-hearing-over-ped-violation-claim--114544|title=Tyson Fury Set For May 8 UKAD Hearing Over PED Violation Claim \u2013 ''Boxing News''|website=www.boxingscene.com|access-date=14 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nRobert Smith, general secretary of the BBBofC, said in May 2017 that Fury's case was \"complex\" and it had been adjourned.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.badlefthook.com/2017/5/13/15636466/tyson-furys-anti-doping-hearing-on-hold|title=Tyson Fury's anti-doping hearing on hold|date=13 May 2017|website=Bad Left Hook|access-date=15 May 2017}}</ref> In September 2017, Fury challenged UKAD to give him a reply, and either ban him or reinstate his boxing licence. He believed he was being treated unfairly as it had taken over a year for them to reply, stating that usually the problem would be dealt with within a matter of months. Fury tweeted, \"How long must I be held up and kept out of action? It's been 15 months since I've been under investigation, you're keeping an innocent man from fulfilling his destiny and from providing for his family.\" UKAD stated there was no particular timescale involved,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/tyson-fury-pleads-with-ukad-render-decision-on-his-career--120610|title=Tyson Fury Pleads With UKAD To Render Decision on His Career |work=Boxing Scene|author=Boxing Clever|date=18 September 2017|access-date=19 September 2017}}</ref> but denied claims that they were prolonging the hearing. Instead they said they were trying to resolve the matter as soon as possible.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11045009/ukad-responds-to-tyson-fury-criticism-over-adjourned-hearing|title=UKAD responds to Tyson Fury criticism over adjourned hearing|first=Richard|last=Damerell|work=Sky Sports|date=20 September 2017|access-date=21 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tyson Fury at Place Bell, Laval Quebec, Canada - Dec 16 2017.jpg|thumb|Fury at [[Place Bell (Laval, Quebec)|Place Bell]], Laval Quebec, Canada in 2017]]\n\nOn 8 November 2017, [[BBC Sport]] reported that a National Anti-Doping Panel hearing was due to take place in December. Due to the legal battle between Fury and UKAD, it was believed that UKAD could potentially become [[Insolvency|insolvent]] or would need a government bail out. UKAD reportedly have an annual budget of \u00a38 million, and the fact that Fury had not fought for two years would have caused potential loss of earnings, possibly over \u00a310 million. UKAD asked the government if they could underwrite the case.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/41899478|title=Tyson Fury legal fight 'could bankrupt' UK Anti-Doping|date=8 November 2017|work=BBC Sport|access-date=8 November 2017}}</ref> On 23 November, according to Robert Smith of the BBBofC, a hearing was set for a date in December 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11139829/tyson-fury-will-resume-his-uk-anti-doping-hearing-next-month|title=Tyson Fury will resume his UK Anti-Doping hearing next month|work=Sky Sports|access-date=23 November 2017}}</ref> On 25 November 2017, Fury announced his comeback after signing with managerial group [[MTK Global]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/21549876/tyson-fury-signs-management-company-mtk-global|title=Management company MTK Global signs Fury|date=2017-11-25|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-01}}</ref> A hearing start date of 11 December was set, with a potential outcome being Fury facing a four-year ban.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/tyson-fury-ukad-hearing-starts-monday-facing-4-year-ban--123174|title=Tyson Fury UKAD Hearing Starts Monday, Facing 4 Year Ban|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=8 December 2017}}</ref> Fury did not attend the hearing and had reporters waiting outside the location for six hours before leaving.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/tyson-fury-no-shows-ukad-hearing-creating-further-delay--123324|title=Tyson Fury No-Shows UKAD Hearing, Creating Further Delay|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=11 December 2017}}</ref> Mick Hennessy later stated that Fury was not required at the hearing.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11167835/tyson-fury-was-not-required-to-attend-london-hearing-uk-anti-doping-have-confirmed|title=Tyson Fury was not required to attend London hearing, UK Anti-Doping have confirmed|work=Sky Sports|access-date=12 December 2017}}</ref> On 7 February 2018, UKAD revealed they spent \u00a3585,659 on the Fury case. \u00a3576,587 was paid to London law firm [[Bird & Bird]], barrister fees came to \u00a31,130 and around \u00a38,000 was paid for laboratory work. UKAD believed they could regain \u00a3250,000 through legal insurance.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/22353569/tyson-hughie-fury-legal-battle-cost-uk-anti-doping-577000|title=Fury legal battle cost UKAD \u00a3577,000|work=ESPN.com|access-date=7 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/42965999|title=Tyson & Hughie Fury: Ukad spent \u00a3577,000 on legal fees|date=7 February 2018|work=BBC Sport|access-date=7 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/ukad-spent-600k-pursue-doping-case-against-tyson-fury--125030|title=UKAD Spent 600K To Pursue Doping Case Against Tyson Fury|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=7 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 December, UKAD announced they had agreed with the Furys and the BBBoC to resolve the charges. \"Taking into account the delays in results management that meant charges were not brought in respect of the nandrolone findings until June 2016, and the provisional suspensions that Tyson and Hughie Fury have already effectively served, the two year period of ineligibility is backdated to 13 December 2015, and therefore expires at midnight on 12 December 2017.\"<ref name=\"skysports1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11168985/tyson-fury-licence-will-be-considered-in-january-after-ukad-ruling|title=Tyson Fury licence 'will be considered' in January after UKAD ruling|work=Sky Sports|access-date=13 December 2017}}</ref> Tyson's February 2015 win over Christian Hammer was disqualified but his Klitschko triumph was not. Tyson blamed the elevated nandrolone levels on eating uncastrated [[wild boar]] and declared his and Hughie's innocence, \"Hughie and I have maintained our innocence from day one and we're now happy that it has finally been settled with UKAD and that we can move forward knowing that we'll not be labelled drug cheats.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/boxing/2017/12/12/tyson-fury-cleared-resume-boxing-career-accepting-backdated/ |title=Tyson Fury cleared to set up Anthony Joshua fight after accepting backdated two-year drugs ban |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=2017-12-12}}</ref> The BBBofC said they would consider the renewal of Fury's boxing licence in January 2018.<ref name=\"skysports1\"/> In relation to the news, Fury wrote on Twitter, \"Guess who's back?\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/21748106/tyson-fury-free-box-again-accepting-backdated-ban|title=Fury free to box again|work=ESPN.com|access-date=12 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11168009/tyson-fury-accepts-backdated-ukad-ban|title=Tyson Fury accepts backdated UKAD ban; still requires boxing licence|work=Sky Sports|access-date=12 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/tyson-fury-free-box-ukad-ruling--123353|title=Tyson Fury Free To Box After UKAD Ruling|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=12 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Comeback trail===\nOn 10 January 2018, Fury announced he would be re-applying for his boxing licence through the BBBofC.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11202175/tyson-fury-to-apply-for-licence-from-british-boxing-board-of-control|title=Tyson Fury to apply for licence from British Boxing Board of Control|work=Sky Sports|access-date=10 January 2018}}</ref> An interview took place between Fury and BBBofC on 19 January, where the latter agreed to re-instate Fury as long as he sent them up-to-date medical records after visiting a psychologist.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/42744703|title=Tyson Fury: British Boxing Board of Control agrees to lift suspension|date=2018|work=BBC Sport|access-date=19 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11213451/tyson-furys-suspension-set-to-be-lifted-subject-to-medical-clearance|title=Tyson Fury's suspension set to be lifted subject to medical clearance|work=Sky Sports|access-date=19 January 2018}}</ref>  Fury said a motivation on his return was [[Deontay Wilder]]. \"He said I couldn't do it, he said definitely not Tyson Fury. He's done.\"<ref>\n{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/43910687|title=Deontay Wilder criticism has motivated me to return to boxing|first=Luke |last=Reddy|work=BBC Sport|date=26 April 2018}}</ref> At a press conference in London on 12 April 2018, Fury announced he had signed a multi-fight deal with Frank Warren's Queensberry Promotions. He stated that he intended to fight at least three times before 2019, starting on 9 June at the Manchester Arena.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/23127482/frank-warren-signs-tyson-fury-comeback-set-manchester-arena-june-9|title=Fury signs with Warren, to fight again June 9|work=ESPN.com|access-date=13 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11327482/tyson-fury-will-fight-on-june-9-after-confirming-comeback|title=Tyson Fury confirms comeback fight - and sends warning to Anthony Joshua|work=Sky Sports|access-date=13 April 2018}}</ref> After weeks of speculation, it was confirmed the fight would be shown exclusively on BT Sport.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://sport.bt.com/boxing/tyson-furys-comeback-will-be-shown-exclusively-live-on-bt-sport-as-the-partnership-with-frank-warren-and-queensberry-promotions-is-extended-S11364267644341|title=Tyson Fury\u2019s comeback will be shown exclusively live on BT Sport|work=BT.com|access-date=2 May 2018}}</ref> On 20 May, 39-year-old Albanian [[Sefer Seferi]] (23\u20131, 21 KOs) was announced as Fury's opponent in a 10-round bout. Seferi was a career cruiserweight, having fought once at heavyweight, when he lost to [[Manuel Charr]] in 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11379680/tyson-fury-to-face-sefer-seferi-in-heavyweight-comeback-fight|title=Tyson Fury to face Sefer Seferi in heavyweight comeback fight|work=Sky Sports|access-date=21 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/44190446|title=Tyson Fury will fight Sefer Seferi when he makes his boxing comeback on 9 June|date=20 May 2018|work=BBC Sport|access-date=21 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/23553756/tyson-fury-make-comeback-heavyweight-sefer-seferi|title=Fury comeback starts against Seferi June 9|work=ESPN.com|access-date=21 May 2018}}</ref> Fury weighed {{convert|276|lb|kg}} at the weigh-in, {{convert|66|lb|kg}} heavier than Seferi. Fury had lost {{convert|112|lb|kg}} for the fight, having experienced extreme weight gain due to his mental health problems. Fury won the fight after Seferi quit on his stool after round 4.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11400146/tyson-fury-beat-sefer-seferi-in-his-return-to-heavyweight-boxing|title=Tyson Fury beat Sefer Seferi in his return to heavyweight boxing|work=Sky Sports|access-date=22 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://sport.bt.com/boxing/tyson-fury-result-gypsy-king-beats-sefer-seferi-in-comeback-fight-S11364277098865|title=Tyson Fury fight result: Gypsy King beats Sefer Seferi in comeback bout|work=BT.com|access-date=22 June 2018}}</ref> The opening couple of rounds had little to no action as Fury was showboating, which referee Phil Edwards warned him for in round 2. A brawl also broke out in the crowd during the fight, but order was restored before the fight came to an end. Fury began to unload heavy shots in round 4 and it appeared many of the shots landed and hurt Seferi, hence he retired on his stool.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/tyson-fury-finally-returns-seferi-results--128948|title=Tyson Fury Finally Returns, Looks Rusty in Stopping Seferi|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=22 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/44426519|title=Tyson Fury: Briton beats Sefer Seferi in comeback fight|date=9 June 2018|work=BBC Sport|access-date=22 June 2018}}</ref> After the fight, Warren confirmed Fury would next return on the [[Carl Frampton]] undercard on 18 August at [[Windsor Park]] in [[Belfast]]. It was revealed the fight, which aired exclusively on [[BT Sport 1]], peaked at 814,000 live viewers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.frankwarren.com/fury-return-peaks-at-814000-live-tv-viewers/|title=FURY RETURN PEAKS AT 814,000 LIVE TV VIEWERS - Frank Warren|date=16 June 2018|work=Frank Warren|access-date=22 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 July 2018, it was announced that Fury would fight former two-time world title challenger [[Francesco Pianeta]] (35\u20134\u20131, 21 KOs) on 18 August.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingnewsonline.net/tyson-fury-next-opponent-revealed/|title=Tyson Fury next opponent REVEALED - Boxing News|date=12 July 2018|work=Boxing News|access-date=12 July 2018}}</ref> Fury weighed in at {{convert|258|lb|kg}}, {{convert|18|lb|kg}} lighter than he weighed against Seferi. Pianeta came in at {{convert|254.7|lb|kg}}.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.irish-boxing.com/naked-carl-frampton-deontay-wilder-invasion-steve-collins-misses-weight/|title=WINDSOR WEIGH-IN: Naked Carl Frampton - Deontay Wilder invasion - Steve Collins misses weight -|date=17 August 2018|access-date=17 August 2018}}</ref> On 30 July, it was reported that there was ongoing negotiations for a fight to take place in either November or December 2018 between Fury and Wilder (40\u20130, 39 KOs).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/fury-confirms-negotiations-with-wilder-december-fight--130442|title=Fury Confirms Negotiations With Wilder For December Fight|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=31 August 2018}}</ref> On 31 July, Fury stated the fight against Wilder was 99% a done deal, with only a location and date to be confirmed. Fury also had to come through in his bout against Pianeta.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/tyson-fury-far-im-concerned-wilder-fight-99-done--130484|title=Tyson Fury: As Far as I'm Concerned - Wilder Fight is 99% Done!|author=Boxing Clever|work=BoxingScene.com|date=31 July 2018|access-date=31 August 2018}}</ref> Wilder was scheduled to be in Belfast to further promote the fight.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-set-belfast-ringside-berth--130848|title=Deontay Wilder Set For Belfast Ringside Berth|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=31 August 2018}}</ref> Fury went the full 10 rounds, defeating Pianeta via a points decision. Referee Steve Gray scored the fight 100\u201390 in favour of Fury.<ref>Taylor, Declan (2018) \"[https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/boxing/tyson-fury-vs-deontay-wilder-confirmed-win-vs-francesco-pianeta-carl-frampton-josh-warrington-luke-a8497826.html Tyson Fury vs Deontay Wilder confirmed after defeat of Francesco Pianeta as Carl Frampton beats Luke Jackson]\", ''[[The Independent]]'', 19 August 2018. Retrieved 19 August 2018</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/tyson-fury-outboxes-francesco-pianeta-results--131013|title=Tyson Fury Outboxes Francesco Pianeta, Eyes Wilder Next|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=31 August 2018}}</ref> Fury later revealed he had no intention of trying to end the fight early. He said, \"I think it was a calculated boxing performance. I got 10 rounds with a very tough man under my belt. I was working on my jab, slipping his punches. I thought that was a step up with the opponent and display. I needed the rounds, and I had plenty left in the tank.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/24410610/tyson-fury-defeats-francesco-pianeta-sets-heavyweight-showdown-deontay-wilder|title=Fury wins to set up showdown against Wilder|work=ESPN.com|access-date=31 August 2018}}</ref> According to CompuBox, Fury landed 107 of 620 punches thrown (17%). This included 100 power punches landed of 226 thrown (44%). Pianeta landed only 37 of his 228 punches thrown (16%).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/tyson-fury-vs-francesco-pianeta-compubox-punch-stats--131040|title=Tyson Fury vs. Francesco Pianeta - CompuBox Punch Stats|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=31 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring the post-fight interviews, promoter Warren confirmed the Fury vs. Wilder fight was on. The fight would take place in either Las Vegas or New York in November 2018. The fight would be aired on PPV in the United States on [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] and in the UK on [[BT Sport Box Office|BT Sports Box Office]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://sport.bt.com/boxing/tyson-fury-v-deontay-wilder-mega-fight-to-be-shown-exclusively-live-on-bt-sport-S11364289577993|title=Fury v Wilder mega-fight to be shown exclusively live on BT Sport|work=BT.com|access-date=31 August 2018}}</ref> Talking about how the fight came together, Fury said, \"We have two men who will fight anyone. This man has been trying to make a fight with another chump. They called, I answered. I said: 'Send me the contract.' They sent it. I said 'yes'.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/45236702|title=Tyson Fury and Deontay Wilder face off in ring after Briton beats Francesco Pianeta|date=18 August 2018|work=BBC Sport|access-date=31 August 2018}}</ref> Warren later told BBC Radio 5 live, \"[It's a] 50\u201350 [purse split], quick and smooth negotiations. He was the world heavyweight champion. He's undefeated. [Wilder and his team] understand that. All of the terms are agreed.\" By the end of August, contracts for the fight to take place had been signed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-vs-tyson-fury-50-50-deal-says-frank-warren--131059|title=Deontay Wilder vs. Tyson Fury is a 50\u201350 Deal, Says Frank Warren|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=31 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===WBC heavyweight championship===\n{{Main|Deontay Wilder vs. Tyson Fury}}\nOn 22 September, both Fury and Wilder confirmed they had signed the contract and the fight would take place on 1 December 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://sport.bt.com/boxing/tyson-fury-and-deontay-wilder-agree-december-1-date-for-fight-S11364297208878|title=Tyson Fury and Deontay Wilder agree December 1 date for fight|work=BT.com|access-date=22 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/45611289|title=Deontay Wilder v Tyson Fury: Fight confirmed for 1 December|date=22 September 2018|work=BBC Sport|access-date=22 September 2018}}</ref> According to the [[California State Athletic Commission]], Wilder would earn a guaranteed base purse of $4 million and Fury would take home a guaranteed purse of $3 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/espn/now?nowId=21-41046609-4|title=Per the California State Athletic Commission, purses for Saturday\u2019s Wilder-Fury card: Deontay Wilder $4 million, Tyson Fury $3 million |date=2018-12-01|website=ESPN.com|access-date=2018-12-01}}</ref> Despite Frank Warren's original claim that the revenue would be split 50\u201350, it was revealed that Wilder could make $14 million (\u00a311 million) and Fury would earn around $10.25 million (\u00a38 million). Both boxers would see this increase to their base purses after receiving their percentages from pay-per-view revenue.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.express.co.uk/sport/boxing/1051813/Fury-vs-Wilder-Prize-Money-Deontay-Wilder-and-Deontay-Wilder-Purses-Revealed|title=Fury vs Wilder prize money: Deontay Wilder and Tyson Fury\u2019s purses revealed|last=Malata|first=Chisanga|date=2018-11-29|work=Express.co.uk|access-date=2018-11-29}}</ref> The weigh-in took place on November 30, outside the [[Los Angeles Convention Center]]. Fury stepped on the scale first and weighed in at {{convert|256+1/2|lb|kg}}. This was only {{convert|2|lb|kg}} lighter than his weigh-in against Francisco Pianeta in August 2018, but he looked leaner. Wilder was next to step on and came in at {{convert|212+1/2|lb|kg}}, his lowest since his debut in 2008 when he weighed {{convert|207+1/4|lb|kg}}. For his last bout, Wilder weighed {{convert|214|lb|kg}}, however, it was cited that Wilder suffered from an illness during his training camp.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/wilder-weighs-even-lower-ortiz-fight-fury-256-5-weights--134196|title=Wilder Weighs In Even Lower Than For Ortiz Fight; Fury 256.5|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-12-01|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nIn front of a crowd of 17,698 at the Staples Center, Wilder and Fury fought a 12-round split decision draw, meaning Wilder retained his WBC title. Mexican judge Alejandro Rochin scored the fight 115\u2013111 for Wilder, Canadian judge Robert Tapper had it 114\u2013112 for Fury and British judge Phil Edwards scored it a 113\u2013113 draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-vs-tyson-fury-official-scorecards-photo--134242|title=Deontay Wilder vs. Tyson Fury \u2013 Official Scorecards \u2013 Photo|website=BoxingScene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2018-12-24}}</ref> The crowd booed at the decision with many believing Fury did enough to dethrone Wilder. Fury, using his unorthodox stance, spent much of the fight using upper and lower-body movement to avoid Wilder big shots and stay out of range. There was not much action in round 1 as both boxers used the round to feel each other out. Wilder tried to trap Fury into the corner, but Fury made Wilder miss most of his big swings. In round 4, Wilder bloodied Fury's nose with his stiff jabs, but was unable to follow up on the attacks. In round 6, Fury switched to southpaw stance and had success backing Wilder against the ropes and at the same time stayed cautious of Wilder's power. In round 7, after trading jabs, which saw Fury come out on top, Fury landed a counter right hand, then quickly tied Wilder up before he could throw anything back. Round 8 saw back and forth action with both trying to land. Wilder threw a lot of power shots which Fury mostly evaded. In round 9, Wilder finally dropped Fury with a short left hook followed by an overhand right. Fury beat referee Jack Reiss\u2019 count and survived the round. Having expended a lot of energy trying to finish Fury in round 9, Wilder looked fatigued in round 10. This came to as an advantage for Fury as he landed two right hands. Fury also took advantage in round 11, landing enough shots and avoided anything Wilder could throw. In round 12, Wilder landed a right-left combination which put Fury down hard on his back. The crowd, commentary team and Wilder believed the fight was over. Reiss looked at Fury on the canvas and began giving him a count. To everyone's surprise, Fury beat the count. Reiss made Fury walk towards him and called for the action to continue. Wilder, fatigued again, was unable to land another power shot and Fury landed some right hands to finish the round and the fight on his feet. Both boxers embraced in a hug after the final bell sounded.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-tyson-fury-controversial-draw-results--134241|title=Deontay Wilder, Tyson Fury Ends in Controversial Draw|website=BoxingScene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2018-12-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/46416721|title=Wilder v Fury: Stunning draw in WBC world heavyweight title fight|last=|first=|date=|website=BBC Boxing|access-date=2008-12-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11569434/tyson-fury-forced-to-settle-for-a-draw-with-deontay-wilder|title=Tyson Fury forced to settle for a draw with Deontay Wilder|website=Sky Sports|language=en|access-date=2018-12-24}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[CompuBox]] statistics, Wilder landed 71 punches of 430 thrown (17%), and Fury landed 84 of his 327 thrown (26%). Wilder was much less accurate in this fight than he usually had been in previous fights. Fury out-landed Wilder in 9 out of the 12 rounds. Both Wilder and Fury only landed double digits in 4 separate rounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-vs-tyson-fury-compubox-punch-stats--134262|title=Deontay Wilder vs. Tyson Fury \u2013 CompuBox Punch Stats|last=|first=|date=|website=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-12-24}}</ref> After the fight, both men gave in-ring interviews. Wilder stated, \"I think with the two knockdowns, I definitely won the fight. We poured our hearts out tonight. We're both warriors. I rushed my punches. I didn't sit still. I was too hesitant. I started overthrowing the right hand, and I just couldn't adjust. I was rushing my punches. That's something I usually don't do.\" Fury said, \"We're on away soil. I got knocked down twice, but I still believe I won that fight. I'm being a total professional here. God bless America. The 'Gypsy King' has returned. That man is a fearsome puncher, and I was able to avoid that. The world knows I won the fight. I hope I did you all proud after nearly three years out of the ring. I showed good heart to get up. I came here tonight, and I fought my heart out.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/25429168|title=Wilder-Fury ends in a draw; both calls for rematch|date=2018-12-02|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2018-12-24}}</ref> Wilder and Fury both claimed to be the best heavyweights in the world and both called out unified world champion [[Anthony Joshua]]. Fury shouted, \u201cChicken! Chicken! Joshua, where are you?\u201d Wilder then agreed to state the two best heavyweights got into the ring and fought.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/wilder-fury-agree-were-best-division-joshua-chicken--134253|title=Wilder, Fury Agree: We're Best in Division, Joshua is a Chicken|first=Duncan|last=Robinson|website=BoxingScene.com|language=en-us|date=2 December 2018|access-date=2018-12-24}}</ref>\n\nThe event was both a critical and a commercial success. The fight sold approximately 325,000 [[pay-per-view]] buys on Showtime in the United States, grossing around $24 million, making it the most lucrative heavyweight fight in the country since [[John Ruiz vs. Roy Jones Jr.|2003]].<ref name=\"espn\">{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/25519401/deontay-wilder-tyson-fury-fight-generates-325000-pay-per-view-buys|title=Sources: Wilder-Fury generates 325K PPV buys|date=December 12, 2018|work=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/wilder-fury-fight-max-out-325000-ppv-buys--134375|title=Wilder-Fury Fight Should Max Out At 325,000 PPV Buys|website=BoxingScene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2018-12-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.worldboxingnews.net/2018/12/05/deontay-wilder-tyson-fury-ppv-success/|title=Deontay Wilder v Tyson Fury hailed a heavyweight Pay-Per-View success|date=December 5, 2018|work=World Boxing News}}</ref> Showtime's delayed broadcast a week later drew an average 488,000 viewers and peaked at 590,000 viewers.<ref name=\"espn\" /> Despite the commercial success of the fight, promoter [[Bob Arum]] believes it was meagre in comparison to the bout's potential. Arum said Fury vs. Wilder II could surpass [[Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs. Manny Pacquiao]], which grossed over $600 million, saying: \"They were the little guys, here we have the biggest men in the sport.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Gareth A Davies |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/boxing/2019/06/16/tyson-fury-eyes-richest-fight-boxing-history-against-deontay/ |title=Tyson Fury eyes 'richest fight in boxing history' against Deontay Wilder after ruthless stoppage of Tom Schwarz |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=2019-06-16}}</ref>\n\n===ESPN deal===\nAfter the fight with Wilder, Fury secured a five-fight contract with [[ESPN]] and [[Top Rank]] worth \u00a380 million ($100 million). He made his return to the ring at the [[MGM Grand Garden Arena]] in [[Las Vegas]] against the WBO Inter-Continental heavyweight champion [[Tom Schwarz]] (24\u20130, 16 KOs) on 15 June 2019. This was Fury's first fight in Las Vegas.<ref name=\"telegraph1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/boxing/2019/06/16/tyson-fury-vs-tom-schwarz-live-round-round-fight-updates-las/ |title=Tyson Fury makes light work of Tom Schwarz with commanding second-round stoppage in Las Vegas |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=2019-06-16}}</ref> Fury weighed {{convert|263|lb|kg}}, compared to Schwarz's {{convert|235+1/2|lb|kg}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.badlefthook.com/2019/6/14/18679847/fury-vs-schwarz-weigh-in-results-tyson-263-tom-235-staredown-video-hart-barrera-mikaela-mayer |title=Weigh-in results and video: Tyson Fury 263, Tom Schwarz 235\u00bd |work=Bad Left Hook |date=2019-06-14}}</ref> He was in complete control of the fight, peppering the undefeated Schwarz in round one before finishing him in the second round by TKO, to take Schwarz's WBO Inter-Continental title. During the fight, Fury [[Rope-a-dope|purposely backed up against the ropes and let Schwarz unload]], using head movement to evade the strikes and generating applause from the 9,000 people in attendance.<ref name=\"telegraph1\"/>\n\nFury fought again in Las Vegas against former WBA Continental heavyweight champion [[Otto Wallin]] (20\u20130, 13 KOs) on 14 September, at the [[T-Mobile Arena]]. Promoter Frank Warren said: \"It is another undefeated boxer he is facing and a contest where a victory will set up the Deontay Wilder rematch.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Gareth A Davies |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/boxing/2019/08/13/tyson-fury-confirms-setember-bout-against-otto-wallin-las-vegas/ |title=Tyson Fury confirms Setember &#91;sic&#93; bout against Otto Wallin in Las Vegas |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=2019-08-13}}</ref> Fury scaled at {{convert|254.4|lb|kg}}, his lightest since facing Klitschko in 2015, when he weighed {{convert|247|lb|kg}}. The Swedish southpaw Wallin came in at exactly {{convert|236|lb|kg}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://talksport.com/sport/boxing/601232/tyson-fury-otto-wallin-fight-mexican-theme-las-vegas-weigh-in/ |title=Tyson Fury slims down for Otto Wallin fight and continues Mexican theme at Las Vegas weigh-in |work=Talksport.com |date=2019-09-14}}</ref> Fury won by unanimous decision 116\u2013112, 117\u2013111, and 118\u2013110. Fury suffered a serious cut above his right eye in the third round from a short left hook, as well as a cut over his right eyelid from an accidental clash of heads in the fifth which affected his vision for the rest of the fight and prompted a ringside doctor to be consulted in the sixth. After an examination, Fury said he was able to continue and the doctor agreed. In the second half of the fight, Fury repeatedly hit Wallin with solid shots. Wallin came back in the twelfth with his best punch of the fight, a clean left hand which momentarily troubled Fury. After tying Wallin up in a clinch, Fury saw out the round, receiving the decision victory and the WBC Mayan belt, a commemorative title awarded to the winner of a high-profile fight held during [[Public holidays in Mexico|Mexican national holidays]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/boxing/tyson-fury-fight-result-otto-wallin-highlights-eye-cut-blood-deontay-wilder-next-news-a9105836.html|title=What we learned from Tyson Fury's win vs Otto Wallin|date=2019-09-15|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref> According to CompuBox, Fury landed 179 of 651 total punches (27%) while Wallin connected with 127 of 334 total punches (38%). Of these total punches, Fury landed 127 power punches to Wallin's 84.<ref>{{cite web|last=Idec |first=Keith |url=https://www.boxingscene.com/tyson-fury-cut-decision-otto-wallin-results--142565 |title=Tyson Fury Overcomes Horrible Cut To Decision Otto Wallin |work=Boxingscene.com |date=2019-09-15}}</ref> In his in-ring interview, Fury praised the performance of Wallin, who was a more than 10\u20131 underdog, and expressed condolences as Wallin's father had recently died. Fury then called out Wilder for a rematch in February 2020.<ref>{{cite news|author=Declan Taylor |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/boxing/2019/09/15/tyson-fury-v-otto-wallin-fight-live-latest-round-updates/ |title=Tyson Fury defeats Otto Wallin on points in bloody Las Vegas battle |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=2019-09-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/sep/15/tyson-fury-otto-wallin-fight-report |title=Tyson Fury survives Otto Wallin scare to stay on course for Wilder rematch |first=Bryan Armen|last=Graham|work=The Guardian |date=15 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Wilder rematch===\n{{Main|Deontay Wilder vs. Tyson Fury II}}\n\nOn 27 November 2019, ESPN announced that Fury would face Deontay Wilder on 22 February 2020, in a rematch of their bout in 2018, which resulted in a controversial draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmamania.com/2019/11/27/20986522/deontay-wilder-tyson-fury-championship-rematch-set-feb-22-las-vegas-boxing|title=Deontay Wilder vs Tyson Fury championship rematch set for Feb. 22 in Las Vegas |author=Adam Guillen Jr.|publisher=mmamania.com|date=November 27, 2019}}</ref> In the build-up to the rematch, Fury split with trainer Ben Davison, who had coached Fury since late 2017 and helped him lose the large amount of weight he had gained during his hiatus and restore him to fighting condition. Davison was nominated for 2018 Trainer of the Year due to his role in Fury's successful return to the ring. The split was described as amicable and Davison wished Fury good luck in the rematch against Wilder. Fury then announced he had partnered with Javan \"SugarHill\" Steward, nephew of Hall-of-Fame trainer [[Emanuel Steward]], and that he would return to [[Kronk Gym]], where he briefly trained in 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ringtv.com/587131-tyson-fury-and-trainer-ben-davison-split-amicably-fury-now-working-with-sugar-hill/|title=Tyson Fury and trainer Ben Davison split amicably, Fury now working with Sugar Hill|date=2019-12-15|website=The Ring|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref> The rematch was officially announced on 27 December 2019, and the venue was set as the [[MGM Grand Garden Arena]] in Las Vegas.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/boxing/2019/12/27/tyson-fury-rematch-deontay-wilder-confirmed-february-22-las/|title=Tyson Fury rematch with Deontay Wilder confirmed for February 22 in Las Vegas|last=Davies|first=Gareth A.|date=2019-12-27|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-12-29|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> The fight contract included a clause in which the loser can invoke a trilogy fight if he chooses.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/boxing/2019/12/28/tyson-fury-deontay-wilder-agree-trilogy-fights-ahead-las-vegas/|title=Tyson Fury and Deontay Wilder agree to trilogy of fights ahead of Las Vegas rematch|last=Hayward|first=Paul|date=2019-12-28|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-12-29|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> \n\nFury weighed in at {{convert|273|lb|kg}}, the third heaviest weight of his professional career and {{convert|17|lb|kg}} heavier than his weight for the first Wilder bout. He stated in the lead-up to the fight that he wanted extra size and power to look for a knockout. Wilder weighed in at {{convert|231|lb|kg}}, the heaviest of his career.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/28752902/deontay-wilder-weighs-231-heaviest-career-tyson-fury-273-pounds-pure-british-beef|title=Wilder up to 231 lbs.; Fury looking for KO at 273|date=2020-02-22|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref> Fury started the fight by taking the centre of the ring and establishing his jab. He looked for some big shots, while evading Wilder's swings. In the third round, Fury floored Wilder with a strong right hand to the temple. Wilder beat the count and survived the round but was visibly disoriented, as blood began to stream from his left ear. Wilder fell to the canvas twice more, but they were ruled as slips by the referee [[Kenny Bayless]], before Fury knocked Wilder down again in the fifth round with a quick combination punctuated by a left hook to the body. Wilder made it to his feet again, but was unable to muster much in the way of a counterattack and he was now bleeding from the mouth as well as the ear. The fight was stopped midway through the seventh round after a flurry of hard-hitting shots from Fury caused Wilder's corner to throw in the towel to save him from further punishment.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hayward|first=Paul|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/boxing/2020/02/23/tyson-fury-beats-deontay-wilder-unbeaten-champion-reduced-tatters/|title=Tyson Fury beats Deontay Wilder: 'an unbeaten champion reduced to tatters' - Paul Hayward's verdict|date=2020-02-23|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2020-02-23|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> At the time of stoppage, Fury was ahead on all three judges' scorecards 59\u201352, 58\u201353, and 59\u201352, with the irregular scores due to Bayless deducting a point from Fury in the fifth for holding.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/%20/deontay-wilder-30-days-exercise-clause-fury-trilogy--147028|title=Deontay Wilder Has 30 Days To Exercise Clause For Fury Trilogy|website=BoxingScene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref>\n\nAccording to CompuBox, Fury landed 82 of his 267 total punches (31%), including 58 out of 160 power punches (36%). Wilder landed 34 of his 141 total punches (24%), including 18 out of 55 power punches (33%).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/%20/tyson-fury-deontay-wilder-rematch-compubox-punch-stats--147018|title=Tyson Fury-Deontay Wilder Rematch - CompuBox Punch Stats|website=BoxingScene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> Fury received widespread praise for his performance, with many believing that it established one of the best boxing comeback stories ever seen, and some stating that the victory placed him as one of the greatest heavyweight boxers in history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/boxing/2020/02/24/tyson-furys-fairy-tale-rise-top-one-lifes-amazing-stories/|title=Tyson Fury\u2019s fairy-tale rise to top is one of life\u2019s amazing stories {{!}} The Telegraph|website=Telegraph|language=en|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref> It made him the first man to defeat two champions who had 10 or more defences of their world championship (Klitschko with 18 defences, and Wilder with 10 defences).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/14258171/tyson-fury-ends-wladimir-klitschko-heavyweight-reign|title=Scorecard: Fury ends Klitschko's heavyweight reign|date=2015-11-30|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/tyson-fury-wbc-heavyweight-title-defeat-deontay-wilder-1488615|title=Tyson Fury stops Deontay Wilder in seven rounds to claim WBC heavyweight title|last=EST|first=Dan Cancian On 2/23/20 at 3:55 AM|date=2020-02-23|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> Fury also became the third heavyweight, after [[Muhammad Ali]] and [[Floyd Patterson]], to hold ''The Ring'' magazine title twice, and the first heavyweight in history to have held the WBA (Super), WBC, IBF, WBO, and ''The Ring'' magazine titles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweek.co.uk/boxing/105825/gypsy-king-takes-wbc-crown-tyson-fury-stops-deontay-wilder|title=Gypsy King takes the WBC crown: Tyson Fury stops Deontay Wilder in the seventh round in Las Vegas|website=The Week UK|language=en|date=22 February 2020|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> With a gate of $16,916,440, the fight broke the gate record for a heavyweight bout in Nevada set by [[Evander Holyfield vs. Lennox Lewis II]] in November 1999.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/28760535/deontay-wilder-tyson-fury-ii-gate-breaks-nevada-heavyweight-record|title=Wilder-Fury gate sets Nevada heavyweight mark|date=2020-02-23|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/boxing/51602615 |title =Tyson Fury beats Deontay Wilder in world title fight in Las Vegas|date=23 February 2020|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\n===WWE (2019)===\nFury made an appearance in an [[Angle (professional wrestling)|angle]] on [[WWE]]'s debut of [[WWE SmackDown|''SmackDown'']] on [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] on 4 October 2019. He stared down [[Braun Strowman]] during his match, and Strowman later threw one of his opponents, [[Dolph Ziggler]], at Fury. After the match, Fury jumped the barricade, but was stopped by security. The WWE announced that Fury would be given an [[Promos (professional wrestling)|open mic]] for the following episode of [[WWE Raw|''Raw'']]. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://pwinsider.com/article/130170/tyson-fury-heading-to-monday-night-raw.html?p=1 |title=Tyson Fury Heading To Monday Night Raw |work=PWInsider.com |first= Mike |last=Johnson|date=5 October 2019}}</ref> Fury appeared in the last segment of the 7 October 2019 episode of ''Raw'' and demanded an apology from Strowman as the two traded insults. They then had a \"brawl\" which was separated by some of Strowman's fellow professional wrestlers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-results/wwe-raw-live-results-hell-cell-fallout-tyson-fury-appears-294271 |title=WWE Raw live results: Hell in a Cell fallout, Tyson Fury appears |work=F4wonline.com |date=2019-10-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/boxing/49970087|title=Tyson Fury v Braun Strowman: Heavyweight boxer clashes with WWE wrestler|publisher=BBC Sport|date=October 8, 2019|access-date=October 9, 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 October 2019, it was confirmed that Fury and Strowman would have a match at [[Crown Jewel (2019)|WWE Crown Jewel]],<ref name=\"LesnarVelasquezStrowmanFury\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2019/10/11/wwe-adds-two-big-matches-to-crown-jewel-in-saudi-arabia-on-oct-31-lesnar-vs-velasquez-and-strowman-vs-tyson-fury/|title=WWE adds two big matches to Crown Jewel in Saudi Arabia on Oct. 31 \u2013 Lesnar vs. Velasquez and Strowman vs. Tyson Fury|date=October 11, 2019|last=Keller|first=Wade|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=October 11, 2019}}</ref> with the contract having been signed on the 15 October episode of [[WWE Raw|Monday Night Raw]]. Fury defeated Strowman by Countout at Crown Jewel.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alfredkonuwa/2019/10/31/wwe-crown-jewel-2019-results-braun-strowman-loses-another-big-match-after-tyson-furys-countout-win/|title=WWE Crown Jewel 2019 Results: Braun Strowman Loses Another Big Match After Tyson Fury\u2019s Countout Win|last=Konuwa|first=Alfred|website=Forbes|language=en|date=31 October 2019|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref> Fury reportedly earned \u00a311.9 million ($15 million) for his participation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/10/15/tyson-fury-bank-11-9m-wwe-debut-match-braun-strowman-10920274/|title=Tyson Fury to pocket \u00a311.9m for WWE debut match against Braun Strowman|date=2019-10-15|website=Metro|language=en|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref>\n\n==Other ventures==\nIn September 2019, [[Penguin Random House]] imprint Century secured the publishing rights to Fury's autobiography, titled ''[[Behind the Mask: My Autobiography]]''. It was released on 14 November 2019 and reached the number-one bestseller position on Amazon with 24 hours of its release.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.secondsout.com/news/news/tyson-fury-behind-the-mask-autobiography-best-seller-praised-by-frank-warren-predicts-unified-title-win-2959498|title=Tyson Fury Behind The Mask autobiography best seller praised by Frank Warren, predicts unified title win|website=SecondsOut Boxing News|language=En|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Pullman |first=Philip |url=https://www.thebookseller.com/news/century-clinches-tyson-fury-s-warts-and-all-autobiography-1080966 |title=Century clinches Tyson Fury's \"warts and all\" autobiography |work=The Bookseller |date=2019-09-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/entertainment/tyson-fury-unveils-publication-date-for-warts-and-all-autobiography-38485832.html|title=Tyson Fury unveils publication date for \u2018warts and all\u2019 autobiography|website=Independent.ie|language=en|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref> \n\nFury appeared in a four-part [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]] documentary named ''Meet the Furys'', which followed the Fury family while Tyson was preparing to fight in Las Vegas for the first time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/presscentre/press-releases/itv-announces-brand-new-factual-series-meet-furys|title=ITV announces brand new factual series Meet The Furys|website=Press Centre|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> ITV later commissioned another documentary about Fury, titled ''Tyson Fury: The Gypsy King'', which showed Fury and his family during the build-up to the Wilder rematch.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/presscentre/ep1week7/tyson-fury-gypsy-king|title=Tyson Fury: The Gypsy King|website=itv.com|language=En|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\nKnown for his habit of impromptu singing, Fury regularly gained media attention for singing songs in the boxing ring after matches and during promotional events.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dailystar.co.uk/sport/boxing/tyson-furys-secret-singing-career-20908957|title=Watch Tyson Fury's secret singing career - Gypsy King sings Elvis Presley in throwback|last=Miles|first=Joe|date=23 November 2019|work=[[Daily Star (United Kingdom)|The Daily Star]]|accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref> In 2019, Fury appeared as a guest vocalist on British singer-songwriter [[Robbie Williams]]' studio album ''[[The Christmas Present]]'', for the song \"Bad Sharon\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/boxing/tyson-fury-robbie-williams-favourites-20650634|title=Tyson Fury and Robbie Williams favourites to land Christmas No.1|website=[[Daily Mirror]]|last=Jones|first=Rich|date=18 October 2019|accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nFury has expressed an interest in competing in [[mixed martial arts]]. In November 2019, he had a training session with [[Darren Till]], who said there is a 70% chance that Fury will compete in MMA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://talksport.com/sport/mma/635321/tyson-fury-darren-till-former-heavyweight-champion-ufc/|title=UFC star tells Tyson Fury to start training for a fight in MMA|last=161385360554578|date=2019-11-27|website=talkSPORT|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmamania.com/2019/11/24/20981298/darren-till-talks-tyson-fury-70-chance-he-fights-in-mma|title=Darren Till talks Tyson Fury: 70% chance he fights in MMA|last=Harkness|first=Ryan|date=2019-11-24|website=MMAmania.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref> Fury also mentioned that [[Conor McGregor]] has offered to train him should he crossover to MMA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/28087333/tyson-fury-conor-mcgregor-offered-train-mma|title=Fury: McGregor has offered to train me in MMA|date=2019-11-15|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref>\n\n==Public image==\nAfter Fury became world champion in 2015, the British media began to scrutinise what he had said in the past. He received criticism for having said that he would \"hang\" his sister if she was [[promiscuous]], as well as comments made in an interview before the Klitschko fight in which he denounced abortion, paedophilia, and homosexuality, saying that the legalisation of these behaviours would bring forth a Biblical reckoning.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/dec/07/tyson-fury-outrage-homosexuality-women-religion-divisive-sporting-star |title=Tyson Fury: the boxer who picked a fight with the world |first=Barney|last= Ronay|work=The Guardian |date=2018-05-25}}</ref>  \n\nFury was nominated for the 2015 [[BBC Sports Personality of the Year Award]] but around 140,000 people signed a petition claiming that his equation of homosexuality with paedophilia should disqualify him. When asked about the petition by a BBC journalist, Fury quoted religious phrases, including \"believe in the Lord Jesus Christ and you will be saved,\" along with John 3:16: \"For God so loved the world, He gave His only begotten Son, whoever believes in Him shall have eternal life and shall not perish.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-35055146/tyson-fury-responds-to-sports-personality-of-the-year-criticism|title=Tyson Fury responds to Sports Personality of the Year criticism|date=2015-12-09|website=bbc.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref> Fury ultimately came fourth in the SPOTY award and said at the ceremony, \"I've said a lot of stuff in the past and none of it is with intentions to hurt anybody. I apologise to anyone that's been hurt by it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.com/sport/boxing/35147170|title= Tyson Fury apologies for comments that 'hurt anybody'|date=20 December 2015|accessdate=21 December 2015|author= |work=BBC Sports}}</ref> He also was criticised for comments on [[bestiality]], transgender people, and \"Jewish people who own all the banks, all the papers, all the TV stations\" in a May 2016 interview.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/boxing/2016/05/13/tyson-fury-launches-into-foul-mouthed-anti-semitic-video-rant-an/ |title=Tyson Fury launches into foul-mouthed anti-Semitic video rant and offers views on rape and bestiality |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=2016-05-13}}</ref> The interview was later deleted and Fury apologised: \"I said some things which may have hurt some people, which as a Christian man is not something I would ever want to do. Though it is not an excuse, sometimes the heightened media scrutiny has caused me to act out in public and then my words can get taken out of context. I mean no harm or disrespect to anyone and I know more is expected of me as an ambassador of British boxing and I promise in future to hold myself up to the highest possible standard.\"<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.com/sport/boxing/36308091|title= Tyson Fury: World heavyweight champion sorry for video comments|accessdate=17 May 2016|author= |publisher= BBC, 16 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Antisemitism2\">{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.com/sport/boxing/36291579|title= Tyson Fury: Heavyweight champion should be barred \u2013 Campaign Against Antisemitism|accessdate=14 May 2016|author= |publisher= BBC|date=13 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nFury was formerly known for his attention-grabbing antics, such as arriving at a press conference in a [[Lamborghini]] and wearing a [[Batman]] costume. After his hiatus, he has said that he does not want to \"play a character anymore\". He stated in November 2017, \"I feel I have a story to tell, a massive one. The stuff I've been through, depression, mental health problems. It can help and inspire others. From 18 stone to 27. From a clean living man to drugs and alcohol and back to the heavyweight world champion again. I hope the legacy and story I leave behind will help others in the future of what to do and not to do.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/boxing/42154202 |title=Tyson Fury says he wants to become a people's champion if he returns to boxing |work=BBC Sport |date=2017-11-28}}</ref> Although Fury has vowed to reign in his entertaining behaviour, he is still known for his vibrant personality, with promoter Bob Arum stating that he \"hasn't seen a fighter with that much charisma since Muhammad Ali\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/sport/other-sport/bob-arum-on-tyson-fury-i-haven-t-seen-a-fighter-with-that-much-charisma-since-muhammad-ali-1.875013|title=Bob Arum on Tyson Fury: I haven\u2019t seen a fighter with that much charisma since Muhammad Ali|date=2019-06-16|website=thenational|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref> Since his return to the ring and his strong performance against Wilder, Fury has been dubbed \"The People's Champion\" due to his open and honest discussion about his mental health struggles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2018/dec/03/boxing-peoples-champion-tyson-fury-memories-muhammad-ali |title='People's champion' Tyson Fury evokes memories of Muhammad Ali era |work=The Guardian |date=3 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Kevin|last=Mitchell|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/boxing/anthony-joshua-tyson-fury-next-fight-deontay-wilder-rematch-frank-warren-a8711981.html |title='People's Champion' Tyson Fury a bigger attraction than Anthony Joshua, claims Frank Warren |work=The Independent |date=2019-01-04}}</ref> He is currently an Ambassador for the former British world champion [[Frank Bruno]]'s mental health charity, The Frank Bruno Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefrankbrunofoundation.co.uk/|title=The Frank Bruno Foundation - Building Healthy Bodies and Healthy Minds|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFury met his wife Paris (n\u00e9e Mullroy) when she was 15 and he was 17.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/article/tyson-fury-interview-2019 |title=Tyson Fury interview 2019 |work=Gq-magazine.co.uk |date=}}</ref><ref name=Rayner /> Like Fury, Paris is a practising [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] and was raised in a Gypsy family. They began dating the year after they met, and married in 2008 at St. Peter in Chains Catholic Church in [[Doncaster|Doncaster, South Yorkshire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doncasterfreepress.co.uk/news/boxer-tyson-fury-and-doncaster-wife-paris-announce-arrival-of-fifth-child-42454 |title=Boxer Tyson Fury and Doncaster wife Paris announce arrival of fifth child |work=Doncaster Free Press |date=2019-02-28}}</ref> The couple have five children together: three sons named Prince Tyson Fury II, Prince Adonis Amaziah, and Prince John James; and two daughters named Venezuela, and Valencia Amber.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://heavy.com/sports/2015/07/paris-fury-tyson-furys-wife-pictures-sexy-photos-hot/|title=Paris Fury, Tyson Fury's Wife: The Pictures you Need to See|first=Guy|last=Docetoni|work=Heavy.com|date=1 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=How old is Tyson Fury\u2019s wife Paris Fury and how many children do they have|url= https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/05/old-tyson-furys-wife-paris-fury-many-children-12355714/|newspaper=The Metro|first=Rachael|last=Martin|date=5 March 2020}}</ref> Paris suffered a [[miscarriage]] before Fury's cancelled bout with Ustinov in 2014,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Davies|first=Gareth A.|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/boxing/11012239/Tyson-Furys-wife-suffered-miscarriage-before-postponed-bout-says-his-uncle.html|title=Tyson Fury's wife suffered miscarriage before postponed bout, says his uncle|date=2014-08-04|access-date=2020-02-25|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> and also lost another child on the day of Fury's comeback fight against Seferi in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/article/tyson-fury-interview-2019|title=A world exclusive interview with Tyson Fury|website=British GQ|language=en-GB|first=Henry |last=Mance|date=16 April 2019|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> \n\nFury and his family reside in [[Morecambe|Morecambe, Lancashire]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lancasterguardian.co.uk/news/people/morecambe-boxing-champ-tyson-fury-to-feature-in-four-part-itv-documentary-called-meet-the-furys-1-9956639 |title=Morecambe boxing champ Tyson Fury to feature in four-part ITV documentary called Meet the Furys |work=Lancaster Guardian |date=2019-08-26}}</ref> In September 2015, he expressed an interest in running as an independent candidate to be the [[Member of Parliament#United Kingdom|UK Member of Parliament]] for [[Morecambe and Lunesdale (UK Parliament constituency)|Morecambe and Lunesdale]], opining that the government was overly focused on providing services for immigrants and not enough on homeless people and those with drug and alcohol problems. He also suggested that Britain should [[Brexit|leave the European Union]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-34400386|title=Boxer Tyson Fury's political fight to be Morecambe MP|date=30 September 2015|accessdate=2 December 2015|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> Fury donated his \u00a37 million purse from his first match against Wilder to charities to build homes for homeless alcohol and drug addicts in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://talksport.com/sport/boxing/491322/tyson-fury-news-gypsy-king-worth-deontay-wilder-purse-charity-rematch/amp/|title=Tyson Fury donated \u00a37million Deontay Wilder purse from first fight to charity, with rematch breaking ticket money records|work=TalkSport|last1=Coleman|first1=Joe|date=24 February 2020|accessdate=25 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, Fury spoke about the racial abuse he receives as a Gypsy world champion, because \"no one wants to see a Gypsy do well\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/36038621|title=Tyson Fury: World heavyweight champion suffering 'racial abuse'|date=13 April 2016|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref> He stated, \"I am a Gypsy and that's it. I will always be a Gypsy, I'll never change. I will always be fat and white and that's it. I am the champion yet I am thought of as a bum.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/15418309/tyson-fury-plans-quit-uk-wladimir-klitschko-fight-relocate-us|author=PA Sport|title=Fury to leave UK for U.S. after Klitschko fight|website=ESPN.com|access-date=28 April 2016}}</ref> Since his return from his hiatus, Fury has stated that he now feels more accepted in Britain. A large crowd attended the book signing for his autobiography ''Behind the Mask'' in 2019; Fury said he felt \"like crying to be honest about the love I'm being shown here. It's amazing.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailystar.co.uk/sport/boxing/tyson-fury-feels-like-crying-20882152|title=Tyson Fury \u2018feels like crying\u2019 after being overwhelmed by fans at book launch|last=Gibbs|first=Dan|date=2019-11-14|website=Dailystar.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n==Professional boxing record==\n{{BoxingRecordSummary\n|draws=1\n|nc=\n|ko-wins=21\n|ko-losses=\n|dec-wins=9\n|dec-losses=\n|dq-wins=\n|dq-losses=\n}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:95%\"\n|-\n!{{abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Result\n!Record\n!Opponent\n!Type\n!Round, time\n!Date\n!Location\n!Notes\n|-\n|31\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|30\u20130\u20131\n|align=left|{{flagicon|US}} [[Deontay Wilder]]\n|TKO\n|7 (12), {{small|1:39}}\n|[[Deontay Wilder vs. Tyson Fury II|22 Feb 2020]]\n|align=left|{{small|{{flagicon|US}} MGM Grand Garden Arena, Paradise, Nevada, US}}\n|align=left|{{small|Won WBC, vacant ''The Ring'', and lineal heavyweight titles}}\n|-\n|30\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|29\u20130\u20131\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|SWE}} [[Otto Wallin]]\n|UD\n|12\n|14 Sep 2019\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|[[T-Mobile Arena]], Paradise, Nevada, US}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|-\n|29\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|28\u20130\u20131\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|GER}} [[Tom Schwarz]]\n|TKO\n|2 (12), {{small|2:54}}\n|15 Jun 2019\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|[[MGM Grand Garden Arena]], [[Paradise, Nevada| Paradise]], [[Nevada]], US}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|Won WBO Inter-Continental heavyweight title}}\n|-\n|28\n|{{draw}}Draw\n|{{nowrap|27\u20130\u20131}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Deontay Wilder]]\n|{{abbr|SD|Split draw}}\n|12\n|[[Deontay Wilder vs. Tyson Fury|1 Dec 2018]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|[[Staples Center]], [[Los An