{"title_page": "20th Television", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Twentieth Television, Inc.\n| logo = 20th_Television_logo.png\n| image = \n| type = Division\n| owner = [[The Walt Disney Company]]\n| parent = [[20th Century Fox Television]]<br>([[Walt Disney Television]])\n| divisions = {{Plainlist|\n* Lincolnwood Drive Inc.\n* 20th Century Fox Television Distribution\n* [[National Geographic Society#Films and television|NGC Studios]] (73%)\n}}\n| founded = {{start date and age|1989}}\n| hq_location_city = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n| hq_location_country = U.S.\n| industry = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Television syndication]]\n* Advertising sales\n}}\n| website = {{URL|20thtv.com/}}\n}}     \n\n'''Twentieth Television, Inc.''' (stylized as '''20th Television''') is an [[United States|American]] television syndication studio and the syndication arm of [[20th Century Fox Television]], which itself is a subsidiary of [[The Walt Disney Company]].\n\n==History==\n20th Television was formed in 1989 by Fox, Inc. (the [[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]] unit that oversaw 20th Century Fox at that time) in order to separate 20th Century Fox's television productions (which were previously handled by its [[20th Century Fox Television]] division) from the movie studio in order to increase the latter's output.<ref name=ap-20thtelevision>{{cite news|last=Horn|first=John|title=20th Century Fox Restructures Film, Television Units|url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1989/20th-Century-Fox-Restructures-Film-Television-Units/id-c84852dbf431b84aa16465a1c851bdb3|accessdate=December 27, 2012|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|date=July 12, 1989}}</ref> During this time, 20th Television and 20th Century Fox served as two of Fox's four main units, along with the [[Fox Broadcasting Company]] and [[Fox Television Stations]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/07/13/business/a-revamping-of-fox-film-puts-emphasis-on-movies.html|title=A Revamping of Fox Film Puts Emphasis on Movies|last=Harmetz|first=Aljean|date=1989-07-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-30|last2=Special to The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Following a 1994 restructuring of Fox's television production companies, 20th Television was refocused on syndication and \"non-traditional programs\"; its network television division was moved back to 20th Century Fox and retook the 20th Century Fox Television name.<ref name=lat-tcftvrestored>{{cite news|title=2 Named to Executive Posts in Fox TV Restructuring|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1994-12-05/business/fi-5172_1_twentieth-century-fox-television|accessdate=December 27, 2012|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=December 5, 1994}}</ref>\n\n20th Television distributes almost all programming from the television production unit and its subsidiaries and the motion picture studio's output (and their own subdivisions); since sister company 20th Century Fox Television produces most of the Fox network programming, 20th Television can also be considered the network's syndication arm.  It owns programming from other production companies and studios they have acquired, including [[MTM Enterprises]], most by [[Metromedia|Metromedia Producers Corporation]], and most by [[New World Pictures|New World Entertainment]] (including those by [[Four Star Television]] and Genesis Entertainment).\n\nThe company also syndicates and/or co-syndicates product from partners such as [[Regency Television]] and [[Debmar-Mercury]] (until April 2019).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvnewscheck.com/article/2007/01/11/9528/feud-dead-zone-both-clear-85-of-country|title='Feud', 'Dead Zone' Both Clear 85% of Country|work=TV News Check|date=January 11, 2007|accessdate=March 13, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117957191/|title='Dead Zone' headed to syndication|last=Guider|first=Elizabeth|work=Variety|date=January 11, 2007|accessdate=January 29, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAs part of the restructuring that stemmed from News Corporation spinning off its entertainment assets into 21st Century Fox, it was announced on July 8, 2013, that 20th Television will operate under the management of 20th Century Fox Television; it was previously under [[Fox Television Stations]]. As a result, the former company's president will now report to the latter's chairmen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/07/21st-century-fox-realigns-tv-syndication-distribution-biz-under-20th-century-fox-tv/|title=21st Century Fox Realigns TV Syndication, Distribution Biz Under 20th Century Fox TV|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=July 8, 2013|accessdate=January 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[20th Century Fox Television]]\n* [[Fox 21 Television Studios]]\n* [[Disney\u2013ABC Home Entertainment and Television Distribution]]\n* [[ABC Studios]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Imdb company|0161074}}\n{{Walt Disney Television |state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:Television syndication distributors]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 1989]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox Television]]\n[[Category:Disney production studios]]\n[[Category:Disney acquisitions]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name                = Twentieth Television, Inc.\n| logo                = 20th_Television_logo.png\n| former_name         =\n| type                = Division of [[20th Century Fox Television]]\n| owner               = <!-- Per [[Template:Infobox company]], it states: \"If the company is majority-owned by a single entity and as such is a subsidiary or division, omit the owner field and use the parent field instead.\" -->\n| parent              = [[20th Century Fox Television]]\n| divisions           = \n| subsid              = \n| founded             = {{start date and age|1989}}\n| hq_location_city    = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n| hq_location_country = U.S.A\n| industry            = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Television syndication]]\n* Advertising sales\n}}\n| website             = {{URL|20thtv.com/}}\n| Formerly            = \n}}     \n\n'''Twentieth Television, Inc.''' (stylized as '''20th Television''') is an [[United States|American]] television syndication studio and the syndication arm of [[20th Century Fox Television]], [[Fox 21 Television Studios]], and [[FX Productions]], with 20th Century Fox Television being a subsidiary of [[Walt Disney Television]].\n\n==History==\n20th Television was formed in 1989 by Fox, Inc. (the [[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]] unit that oversaw 20th Century Fox at that time) in order to separate 20th Century Fox's television productions (which were previously handled by its [[20th Century Fox Television]] division) from the movie studio in order to increase the latter's output.<ref name=ap-20thtelevision>{{cite news|last=Horn|first=John|title=20th Century Fox Restructures Film, Television Units|url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1989/20th-Century-Fox-Restructures-Film-Television-Units/id-c84852dbf431b84aa16465a1c851bdb3|accessdate=December 27, 2012|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|date=July 12, 1989}}</ref> During this time, 20th Television and 20th Century Fox served as two of Fox's four main units, along with the [[Fox Broadcasting Company]] and [[Fox Television Stations]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/07/13/business/a-revamping-of-fox-film-puts-emphasis-on-movies.html|title=A Revamping of Fox Film Puts Emphasis on Movies|last=Harmetz|first=Aljean|date=1989-07-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-30|last2=Special to The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Following a 1994 restructuring of Fox's television production companies, 20th Television was refocused on syndication and \"non-traditional programs\"; its network television division was moved back to 20th Century Studios and retook the 20th Century Fox Television name.<ref name=lat-tcftvrestored>{{cite news|title=2 Named to Executive Posts in Fox TV Restructuring|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1994-12-05/business/fi-5172_1_twentieth-century-fox-television|accessdate=December 27, 2012|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=December 5, 1994}}</ref>\n\n20th Television distributes almost all programming and documentaries from the television production unit including [[Foxstar Productions]] and its subsidiaries and the motion picture studio's output (and their own subdivisions). It owns programming from other production companies and studios they have acquired, including [[MTM Enterprises]], most by [[Metromedia Producers Corporation]], and most by [[New World Entertainment]] (including those by [[Four Star Television]] and [[Genesis Entertainment]]). \n\nThe company also syndicates and/or co-syndicates product from partners such as [[Regency Television]] and [[Debmar-Mercury]] (until April 2019).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvnewscheck.com/article/2007/01/11/9528/feud-dead-zone-both-clear-85-of-country|title='Feud', 'Dead Zone' Both Clear 85% of Country|work=TV News Check|date=January 11, 2007|accessdate=March 13, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117957191/|title='Dead Zone' headed to syndication|last=Guider|first=Elizabeth|work=Variety|date=January 11, 2007|accessdate=January 29, 2013}}</ref> The Lincolnwood Drive subsidiary of 20th Television has been used to produce the syndicated court series ''[[Divorce Court]]'' since the 2014-15 season, mainly for tax reasons.\n\nIn 1992, Greg Meidel became president of 20th Television, serving until 1995. Meidel was president of [[MyNetworkTV]] when he add 20th Television's same position to his responsibility in 2009.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Andreeva |first1=Nellie |title=Greg Meidel Joins Judge Judy Sheindlin's Company Queen Bee Productions |url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/greg-meidel-joins-judge-judy-sheindlin-company-queen-bee-productions-1202624094/ |accessdate=June 7, 2019 |work=Deadline |date=May 30, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs part of the restructuring that stemmed from News Corporation spinning off its entertainment assets into [[21st Century Fox]], it was announced on July 8, 2013, that 20th Television will operate under the management of 20th Century Fox Television; it was previously under Fox Television Stations. As a result, the former company's president will now report to the latter's chairmen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/07/21st-century-fox-realigns-tv-syndication-distribution-biz-under-20th-century-fox-tv/|title=21st Century Fox Realigns TV Syndication, Distribution Biz Under 20th Century Fox TV|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=July 8, 2013|accessdate=January 21, 2018}}</ref> [[Acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney|After the acquisition of 21st Century Fox]] by [[The Walt Disney Company]] on March 20, 2019, president Greg Meidel was laid off.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Andreeva |first1=Nellie |title=Fox Television President Greg Meidel Out As Disney-Fox Layoffs Continue |url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/fox-television-president-greg-meidel-out-disney-fox-layoffs-1202580382/ |accessdate=June 7, 2019 |work=Deadline |date=March 21, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn January 17, 2020, it was announced that the \"Fox\" name would be dropped from several of the Fox assets acquired by Disney. However, the renaming of 20th Century Fox Television, 20th Television, and Fox 21 Television Studios, as well as [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment]] and [[Fox Networks Group]] International, was not made clear.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/disney-dropping-fox-20th-century-studios-1203470349/|title=Disney Drops Fox Name, Will Rebrand as 20th Century Studios, Searchlight Pictures|first=Adam B.|last=Vary|work=Variety|date=January 17, 2020|accessdate=January 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[20th Century Fox Television]]\n* [[Fox 21 Television Studios]]\n* [[Disney\u2013ABC Home Entertainment and Television Distribution]]\n* [[ABC Studios]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Imdb company|0161074}}\n{{Walt Disney Television |state=expanded}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Television syndication distributors]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 1989]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox Television]]\n[[Category:Disney production studios]]\n[[Category:Disney acquisitions]]\n", "name_user": "102.176.94.64", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(edit summary removed)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/20th_Television"}
{"title_page": "Southmead", "text_new": "\n\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country = England\n|official_name= Southmead\n|coordinates = {{coord|51.5039|-2.6028|display=inline,title}}\n|map_type= nomap\n|static_image_name= Bristol southmead.png\n|static_image_caption= Boundaries of the city council ward\n|static_image_alt= Southmead ward north of the city centre\n|civil_parish=\n| population = 11,956\n| population_ref =(2011.Ward)<ref>{{cite web | title=Southmead | work=2011 Census Ward Information Sheet | url=http://www.bristol.gov.uk/WardFinder/pdfs/southmead-wis.pdf | accessdate=26 February 2015}}</ref>\n|unitary_england= [[Bristol]]\n|lieutenancy_england= Bristol\n|region= South West England\n|constituency_westminster= [[Bristol North West (UK Parliament constituency)|Bristol North West]]\n|post_town= BRISTOL\n|postcode_area= BS\n|postcode_district= BS10\n|dial_code= 0117\n|os_grid_reference= ST582785\n}}\n\n'''Southmead''' is a northern suburb and [[wards of the United Kingdom|council ward]] of [[Bristol]], in the south-west of England. The town of [[Filton]] (in [[South Gloucestershire]]), and the Bristol suburbs of [[Monks Park]], [[Horfield]], [[Henleaze]] and [[Westbury on Trym]] lie on its boundaries.\n\nThe [[River Trym]] rises in Southmead and flows south-west through Badock's Wood, a [[Local Nature Reserve]]. There is a [[round barrow]] near the northern end of the wood.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fobw.co.uk/documents/29.html |title=History |publisher=Fobw.co.uk |date= |accessdate=4 March 2013}}</ref> A [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]], known as the The [[Pen Park Hole]] <ref>{{Citation|title=Pen Park Hole|date=2020-03-16|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Pen_Park_Hole&oldid=945820444|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>, is also located within Southmead on 'Pen Park Road'. \n\n==History==\nSouthmead was a manor of the parish of Westbury on Trym. The manor house, mentioned in a document of 1319, was near the south end of what is now Southmead Road.<ref>''The Henleaze Book'', p.14</ref> Most of the estate of {{convert|313|acre|km2}} was sold in the late 19th century. By 1888 Southmead was a small hamlet on Southmead Road.<ref>{{cite news|title=It's where community spirit thrives|url=http://www.bristolpost.co.uk/s-community-spirit-thrives/story-16528444-detail/story.html|accessdate=28 November 2015|work=Bristol Post|date=13 July 2012}}</ref> [[Southmead Hospital]], formerly the Barton Regis Workhouse, was opened there in 1924.\n\nLarge-scale development of the area started in 1931, when the Bristol Corporation built 1,500 houses to the north of Southmead Road, partly to house families cleared from the [[slum]]s of central Bristol, and partly to address the housing shortage at the time. A further 1,100 houses were built after the Second World War. Since the Second World War, a reference has often been made by the local community, to the 'pre-war estate' of Southmead and the 'post-war estate', with locals also referring to them as \"The old estate\" and \"The new estate\".\n[[File:Tilling Road - geograph.org.uk - 255288.jpg|right|thumb|Southmead housing developments|281x281px]]\n==Southmead today==\n[[File:A pedestrian entrance to Southmead Hospital, Bristol (geograph 3314481).jpg|thumb|right|Pedestrian entrance to Southmead Hospital|277x277px]]\nThe centre of Southmead is along Greystoke Avenue, a wide road with grassy areas some distance to the North of the original hamlet on Southmead Road. The area to the South and West, falls within Westbury-on-Trym and Henleaze ward since the last boundary review and further to the May 2016 elections. Parts of Southmead to the south-east of Southmead Road, including the hospital, are in Horfield ward.<ref>Southmead Ward Map https://www.bristol.gov.uk/documents/20182/34844/Southmead+Ward+May+2016/28a2356c-7ab4-4911-a706-bd5ad897852c. Publisher=Bristol City Council. Year=2016. Accessed 12 February 2017</ref> \n==Social issues==\nEfforts have been made to improve the area's social problems and implement environmental improvements, many of which have been successful. Social policies have led to a more mixed housing offer and to some extent gentrification, with improved infrastructure and local services. The right to buy has led to an increased transfer of housing provision from tenanted to owner-occupation. Major employment hubs at Filton, MOD Abbey Wood and the increase of services at Southmead Hospital have brought increased affluence and opportunity to the area. A greater selection of shops and facilities have come to the area, allowing those on limited incomes to access food more cheaply and readily. Whilst Southmead as an area looks and feels as though it is improving, it still experiences deprivation. The central part of Southmead still sits within the most 10% deprived areas of England, and the South West of the Ward since 2015 now falls within the bottom 10-20% most deprived areas.<ref>https://www.bristol.gov.uk/documents/20182/32951/Deprivation+in+Bristol+2015/429b2004-eeff-44c5-8044-9e7dcd002faf. 'Deprivation in Bristol 2015'. Bristol City Council. Accessed 12 February 2017</ref> Ongoing social policies and economic impacts are taking time to incrementally improve the area.\n\nResidents have good geographical access.<ref>See Map 15, which show that Southmead does not fall under low geographical barriers indices - https://www.bristol.gov.uk/documents/20182/32951/Deprivation+in+Bristol+2015/429b2004-eeff-44c5-8044-9e7dcd002faf. 'Deprivation in Bristol 2015'. Bristol City Council. Accessed 12 February 2017</ref> There has however been a transfer of public services away from physical resources to more central, virtual and internet based services. For example, the Southmead Police Station is due to close, with a more regional hub at Patchway. Council tenant services are to be reduced at Southmead House off Greystoke Avenue. Bus services, whilst sometimes locally critiqued, are accessible and more frequent as compared to some other areas of the City. A frequent service connects residents to the Gloucester Road area, City Centre and Cribbs Causeway for shopping. The nearest station is however 2\u20133 miles away at Filton Abbey Wood.\n[[File:Glencoyne Square - Southmead - geograph.org.uk - 5921.jpg|thumb|Glencoyne Square|276x276px]]\nThere is provision of health services with a doctor's surgery on Ullswater Road and a modern new facility at the Greenway Centre. A regional hospital, and A&E facility can be found at Southmead Hospital. The Lannercost provides facilities for those with physical and learning impairments. There are a selection of care homes and sheltered accommodation about the ward area. Despite access to health facilities Southmead still has poor health outcomes; with life expectancy at 77 years, some 5 yrs lower than neighbouring Henleaze but not quite as bad as some areas such as the Bedminster at 76.4 years.<ref>See http://ias.bristol.gov.uk/IAS/dataviews/tabular?viewId=708&geoId=590&subsetId=. Bristol JSNA - Life Expectancy and Mortality. GeoWise Ltd 2015. Accessed date 12 February 2017</ref>  \n\nThe area is well served with a range of local parks and sporting facilities. There is a private member's sports club at David Lloyd near Badock's Wood. There are sports pitches at Greenway Centre to the South East, and at Charlton Mead to the East of the area. Filton Golf Course abuts Southmead to the North East. There is an MUGA and Adventure Playground off Doncaster Road. There are also play areas off of Glencoyne Square, Charlton Mead and off Greystoke Avenue. To the South of Southmead, only a mile away, is Horfield Sports Centre with public access to 3G pitches, gym, sports Hall and a swimming pool.<ref>See Southmead Community Plan for overview of community facilities. http://www.southmeadcommunityplan.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Southmead-Com-Buildings-July-Final-Report.pdf. Author - Vivid Regeneration LLP. Dated 2014. Accessed date 12 February 2017</ref> \n\nThere is ready access to children's provision through a selection of primary schools at Baddocks Wood, Little Mead and Fonthill. Baddocks Wood Children Centre complements Early Year's provision to the South of the area. Young people are however said to be more socially deprived and not as likely to go to university as others in the country which is reflective of the national socio-economic imbalances within the UK's education system.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2009/feb/03/university-access-social-exclusion | work=The Guardian | location=London | title=Universities don't like common people, do they? | first=Jessica | last=Shepherd | date=3 February 2009 | accessdate=23 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Social cohesion==\nSouthmead has historically had adverse press due to community safety and cohesion. Following the [[1980 St. Pauls riot]], Southmead experienced two nights of rioting.<ref>{{cite web|last=Serpico|first=John|url=http://www.brh.org.uk/articles/southmead.html|title=The Southmead Riots|publisher=Bristol Radical History Group|accessdate=27 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Ball |first1=Roger |title=Violent urban disturbance in England 1980-81 |url=http://eprints.uwe.ac.uk/17958/19/Master%20Document%204%201_electronic_copyright.pdf |publisher=University of the West of England |accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 October 2009, a BBC ''[[Panorama (TV series)|Panorama]]'' report, investigating the extent of [[Racism in the United Kingdom|racism in modern Britain]], featured two undercover journalists who posed as Muslims on the Southmead estate. The journalists were subject to 50 incidents of racist abuse from local residents in two months.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/panorama/hi/front_page/newsid_8303000/8303229.stm |title=BBC \u2013 Panorama \u2013 Reduced to a four-letter word |publisher=BBC News |date=19 October 2009 |accessdate=4 March 2013}}</ref> The couple were verbally and physically attacked during their time in the area of Southmead where they were residing, being told to go back to Iraq. The word \"Jew\" was also used as an insult against the man and a brick was thrown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b00nfr2h/Panorama_Undercover_Hate_on_the_Doorstep |title=BBC One \u2013 Panorama, Undercover \u2013 Hate on the Doorstep |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=25 October 2009 |accessdate=4 March 2013}}</ref> The day after the programme was broadcast, a 22-year-old man and an 11-year-old boy were arrested on suspicion of [[Assault#Aggravated assaults|racially aggravated assault]].<ref>\n{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/bristol/8316799.stm | work=BBC News | title=Two held after TV racism expose | date=20 October 2009 | accessdate=23 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nAs with any area there have been mixed experiences by residents and visitors. A visitor to the area, unhappy with the lack of bus service provision in the Crow Lane area, once commented that \"the police are doing [[bugger all]] about this, all this [[Aggression|aggro]] that's going on\" <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DeIradYX3jw |title=999 Call - Very sore feet |publisher=YouTube |date=2008-07-11 |accessdate=2014-02-04}}</ref>. The area is said by locals to be \"a great place [with] ... a strong sense of community spirit, lots of community activity and lots of optimism for the future.<ref name=communityplan>[http://www.southmeadcommunityplan.co.uk/about-southmead-community-plan/ Southmead Community Plan]. Southmead Development Trust, 2017. Accessed 12 February 2017.</ref> The local neighbourhood plan says \"our vision is that Southmead is known as a great place for everyone to live, a strong community where residents work together, inspire each other and people of all ages have the skills and confidence to achieve their full potential\".<ref name=communityplan /> This plan was the outcome of significant community consultation and planning. Two of the nine strands of the community plan target community safety and strengthening the community (including inclusion and cohesion). The Southmead Development Trust (SDT) co-ordinates and oversees the plan.\n[[File:Southmead Hospital, Bristol- north end of Brunel building (geograph 6010500).jpg|thumb|272x272px|Southmead Hospital]]\n[[File:Southmead youth centre.jpg|right|thumb|Southmead Youth Centre|271x271px]]\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{commons category|Southmead (ward)}}\n{{Districts of Bristol}}\n\n[[Category:Areas of Bristol]]\n[[Category:Wards of Bristol]]\n", "text_old": "{{copyedit|date=April 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country = England\n|official_name= Southmead\n|coordinates = {{coord|51.5039|-2.6028|display=inline,title}}\n|map_type= nomap\n|static_image_name= Bristol southmead.png\n|static_image_caption= Boundaries of the city council ward\n|static_image_alt= Southmead ward north of the city centre\n|civil_parish=\n| population = 11,956\n| population_ref =(2011.Ward)<ref>{{cite web | title=Southmead | work=2011 Census Ward Information Sheet | url=http://www.bristol.gov.uk/WardFinder/pdfs/southmead-wis.pdf | accessdate=26 February 2015}}</ref>\n|unitary_england= [[Bristol]]\n|lieutenancy_england= Bristol\n|region= South West England\n|constituency_westminster= [[Bristol North West (UK Parliament constituency)|Bristol North West]]\n|post_town= BRISTOL\n|postcode_area= BS\n|postcode_district= BS10\n|dial_code= 0117\n|os_grid_reference= ST582785\n}}\n\n'''Southmead''' is a northern suburb and [[wards of the United Kingdom|council ward]] of [[Bristol]], in the south-west of England. The town of [[Filton]] (in [[South Gloucestershire]]), and the Bristol suburbs of [[Monks Park]], [[Horfield]], [[Henleaze]] and [[Westbury on Trym]] lie on its boundaries.\n\nThe [[River Trym]] rises in Southmead and flows south-west through Badock's Wood, a [[Local Nature Reserve]]. There is a [[round barrow]] near the northern end of the wood.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fobw.co.uk/documents/29.html |title=History |publisher=Fobw.co.uk |date= |accessdate=4 March 2013}}</ref> A [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]], known as the The [[Pen Park Hole]] <ref>{{Citation|title=Pen Park Hole|date=2020-03-16|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Pen_Park_Hole&oldid=945820444|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>, is also within Southmead on 'Pen Park Road'. \n\n==History==\nSouthmead was a manor of the parish of Westbury on Trym. The manor house, mentioned in a document of 1319, was near the south end of what is now Southmead Road.<ref>''The Henleaze Book'', p.14</ref> Most of the estate of {{convert|313|acre|km2}} was sold in the late 19th century. By 1888 Southmead was a small hamlet on Southmead Road.<ref>{{cite news|title=It's where community spirit thrives|url=http://www.bristolpost.co.uk/s-community-spirit-thrives/story-16528444-detail/story.html|accessdate=28 November 2015|work=Bristol Post|date=13 July 2012}}</ref> [[Southmead Hospital]], formerly the Barton Regis Workhouse, was opened there in 1924.\n\nLarge-scale development of the area started in 1931, when the Bristol Corporation built 1,500 houses to the north of Southmead Road, partly to house families cleared from the [[slum]]s of central Bristol, and partly to address the housing shortage at the time. A further 1,100 houses were built after the Second World War. Since then, reference{{by whom|date=April 2020}} has often been made to the 'pre-war estate' of Southmead and the 'post-war estate', with locals referring to them as \"The old estate\" and \"The new estate\".{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n[[File:Tilling Road - geograph.org.uk - 255288.jpg|right|thumb|Southmead housing developments]]\n==Southmead today==\n[[File:A pedestrian entrance to Southmead Hospital, Bristol (geograph 3314481).jpg|thumb|right|Pedestrian entrance to Southmead Hospital]]\nThe centre of Southmead is along Greystoke Avenue, a wide road with grassy areas some distance to the North of the original hamlet on Southmead Road. The area to the South and West, falls within Westbury-on-Trym and Henleaze ward since the last boundary review and further to the May 2016 elections. Parts of Southmead to the south-east of Southmead Road, including the hospital, are in Horfield ward.<ref>Southmead Ward Map https://www.bristol.gov.uk/documents/20182/34844/Southmead+Ward+May+2016/28a2356c-7ab4-4911-a706-bd5ad897852c. Publisher=Bristol City Council. Year=2016. Accessed 12 February 2017</ref> \n==Social issues==\nEfforts have been made to improve the area's social problems and implement environmental improvements, many of which have been successful. Social policies have led to a more mixed housing offer and to some extent gentrification, with improved infrastructure and local services. The right to buy has led to an increased transfer of housing provision from tenanted to owner-occupation. Major employment hubs at Filton, MOD Abbey Wood and the increase of services at Southmead Hospital have brought increased affluence and opportunity to the area. A greater selection of shops and facilities have come to the area, allowing those on limited incomes to access food more cheaply and readily. Whilst Southmead as an area looks and feels as though it is improving, it still experiences deprivation. The central part of Southmead still sits within the most 10% deprived areas of England, and the South West of the Ward since 2015 now falls within the bottom 10-20% most deprived areas.<ref>https://www.bristol.gov.uk/documents/20182/32951/Deprivation+in+Bristol+2015/429b2004-eeff-44c5-8044-9e7dcd002faf. 'Deprivation in Bristol 2015'. Bristol City Council. Accessed 12 February 2017</ref> Ongoing social policies and economic impacts are taking time to incrementally improve the area.\n\nResidents have good geographical access.<ref>See Map 15, which show that Southmead does not fall under low geographical barriers indices - https://www.bristol.gov.uk/documents/20182/32951/Deprivation+in+Bristol+2015/429b2004-eeff-44c5-8044-9e7dcd002faf. 'Deprivation in Bristol 2015'. Bristol City Council. Accessed 12 February 2017</ref> There has however been a transfer of public services away from physical resources to more central, virtual and internet based services. For example, the Southmead Police Station is due to close, with a more regional hub at Patchway. Council tenant services are to be reduced at Southmead House off Greystoke Avenue. Bus services, whilst sometimes locally critiqued, are accessible and more frequent as compared to some other areas of the City. A frequent service connects residents to the Gloucester Road area, City Centre and Cribbs Causeway for shopping. The nearest station is however 2\u20133 miles away at Filton Abbey Wood.\n[[File:Glencoyne Square - Southmead - geograph.org.uk - 5921.jpg|thumb|Glencoyne Square]]\nThere is provision of health services with a doctor's surgery on Ullswater Road and a modern new facility at the Greenway Centre. A regional hospital, and A&E facility can be found at Southmead Hospital. The Lannercost provides facilities for those with physical and learning impairments. There are a selection of care homes and sheltered accommodation about the ward area. Despite access to health facilities Southmead still has poor health outcomes; with life expectancy at 77 years, some 5 yrs lower than neighbouring Henleaze but not quite as bad as some areas such as the Bedminster at 76.4 years.<ref>See http://ias.bristol.gov.uk/IAS/dataviews/tabular?viewId=708&geoId=590&subsetId=. Bristol JSNA - Life Expectancy and Mortality. GeoWise Ltd 2015. Accessed date 12 February 2017</ref>  \n\nThe area is well served with a range of local parks and sporting facilities. There is a private member's sports club at David Lloyd near Badock's Wood. There are sports pitches at Greenway Centre to the South East, and at Charlton Mead to the East of the area. Filton Golf Course abuts Southmead to the North East. There is an MUGA and Adventure Playground off Doncaster Road. There are also play areas off of Glencoyne Square, Charlton Mead and off Greystoke Avenue. To the South of Southmead, only a mile away, is Horfield Sports Centre with public access to 3G pitches, gym, sports Hall and a swimming pool.<ref>See Southmead Community Plan for overview of community facilities. http://www.southmeadcommunityplan.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Southmead-Com-Buildings-July-Final-Report.pdf. Author - Vivid Regeneration LLP. Dated 2014. Accessed date 12 February 2017</ref> \n\nThere is ready access to children's provision through a selection of primary schools at Baddocks Wood, Little Mead and Fonthill. Baddocks Wood Children Centre complements Early Year's provision to the South of the area. Young people are however said to be more socially deprived and not as likely to go to university as others in the country which is reflective of the national socio-economic imbalances within the UK's education system.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2009/feb/03/university-access-social-exclusion | work=The Guardian | location=London | title=Universities don't like common people, do they? | first=Jessica | last=Shepherd | date=3 February 2009 | accessdate=23 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Social cohesion==\n[[File:Southmead youth centre.jpg|right|thumb|Southmead Youth Centre]]\nSouthmead has historically had adverse press due to community safety and cohesion. Following the [[1980 St. Pauls riot]], Southmead experienced two nights of rioting.<ref>{{cite web|last=Serpico|first=John|url=http://www.brh.org.uk/articles/southmead.html|title=The Southmead Riots|publisher=Bristol Radical History Group|accessdate=27 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Ball |first1=Roger |title=Violent urban disturbance in England 1980-81 |url=http://eprints.uwe.ac.uk/17958/19/Master%20Document%204%201_electronic_copyright.pdf |publisher=University of the West of England |accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 October 2009, a BBC ''[[Panorama (TV series)|Panorama]]'' report, investigating the extent of [[Racism in the United Kingdom|racism in modern Britain]], featured two undercover journalists who posed as Muslims on the Southmead estate. The journalists were subject to 50 incidents of racist abuse from local residents in two months.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/panorama/hi/front_page/newsid_8303000/8303229.stm |title=BBC \u2013 Panorama \u2013 Reduced to a four-letter word |publisher=BBC News |date=19 October 2009 |accessdate=4 March 2013}}</ref> The couple were verbally and physically attacked during their time in the area of Southmead where they were residing, being told to go back to Iraq. The word \"Jew\" was also used as an insult against the man and a brick was thrown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b00nfr2h/Panorama_Undercover_Hate_on_the_Doorstep |title=BBC One \u2013 Panorama, Undercover \u2013 Hate on the Doorstep |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=25 October 2009 |accessdate=4 March 2013}}</ref> The day after the programme was broadcast, a 22-year-old man and an 11-year-old boy were arrested on suspicion of [[Assault#Aggravated assaults|racially aggravated assault]].<ref>\n{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/bristol/8316799.stm | work=BBC News | title=Two held after TV racism expose | date=20 October 2009 | accessdate=23 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nAs with any area there have been mixed experiences by residents and visitors. A visitor to the area, unhappy with the lack of bus service provision in the Crow Lane area, once commented that \"the police are doing [[bugger all]] about this, all this [[Aggression|aggro]] that's going on\" <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DeIradYX3jw |title=999 Call - Very sore feet |publisher=YouTube |date=2008-07-11 |accessdate=2014-02-04}}</ref>. The area is said by locals to be \"a great place [with] ... a strong sense of community spirit, lots of community activity and lots of optimism for the future.<ref name=communityplan>[http://www.southmeadcommunityplan.co.uk/about-southmead-community-plan/ Southmead Community Plan]. Southmead Development Trust, 2017. Accessed 12 February 2017.</ref> The local neighbourhood plan says \"our vision is that Southmead is known as a great place for everyone to live, a strong community where residents work together, inspire each other and people of all ages have the skills and confidence to achieve their full potential\".<ref name=communityplan /> This plan was the outcome of significant community consultation and planning. Two of the nine strands of the community plan target community safety and strengthening the community (including inclusion and cohesion). The Southmead Development Trust (SDT) co-ordinates and oversees the plan.\n{{clear right}}\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{commons category|Southmead (ward)}}\n{{Districts of Bristol}}\n\n[[Category:Areas of Bristol]]\n[[Category:Wards of Bristol]]\n", "name_user": "Regenerate Cities", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Southmead"}
{"title_page": "20th Century Fox Television", "text_new": "{{short description|TV production company}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Twentieth Century Fox Television, Inc.\n| logo = 20th_Century_Fox_Television_logo.png\n| former_name = TCF Television Productions, Inc. (1949-1958)\n| type = [[Division (business)|Division]]\n| key_people = Carolyn Cassidy, President, Creative Affairs<br>Howard Kurtzman, President, Business Affairs\n| industry = [[Television production]]\n| products = [[Television programs]]\n| owner = <!-- Per [[Template:Infobox company]], it states: \"If the company is majority-owned by a single entity and as such is a subsidiary or division, omit the owner field and use the parent field instead.\" -->\n| parent = Disney Television Studios<br><small>([[Walt Disney Television]])</small>\n| divisions = {{Unbulleted list|[[20th Television]]|[[Fox Television Animation]]}}\n| founded = {{start date and age|1949}}\n| hq_location_city = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n| hq_location_country = United States\n}}\n'''Twentieth Century Fox Television''' (or '''TCF TV''' or '''TCFTV''', stylized as '''20th Century Fox Television''') is a television-production studio for [[20th Century Fox]], owned by [[Walt Disney Television]], a division of [[The Walt Disney Company]].<ref name=\"dl\">{{cite news |last1=Andreeva |first1=Nellie |title=Disney Unveils Top TV Executive Structure Post Fox Acquisition: Peter Rice, Dana Walden, John Landgraf, Gary Knell Joining |url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/disney-top-tv-executive-structure-fox-acquisition-peter-rice-dana-walden-john-landgraf-1202473566/ |accessdate=October 9, 2018 |work=Deadline |date=October 8, 2018}}</ref> [[20th Television]] is the syndication and distribution arm of 20th Century Fox Television.<ref>{{cite news|title=21st Century Fox Realigns TV Syndication, Distribution Biz Underdog/ 20th Century Fox TV|work=[[Foxmovies.com]]|date=July 8, 2013|publisher=Penske Media Corporation}}</ref>\n\n20th Century Fox Television was part of [[Acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney|Disney's 2019 acquisition]] of the majority [[21st Century Fox]] assets.<ref name=\"FoxDisneyPressRelease\">{{cite press release|url=https://thewaltdisneycompany.com/walt-disney-company-acquire-twenty-first-century-fox-inc-spinoff-certain-businesses-52-4-billion-stock-2/|title=The Walt Disney Company To Acquire Twenty-First Century Fox, Inc., After Spinoff Of Certain Businesses, For $52.4 Billion In Stock|work=[[The Walt Disney Company]]|date=December 14, 2017|accessdate=December 14, 2017}}</ref> Disney's acquisition of 21st Century Fox was completed on March 20, 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thewaltdisneycompany.com/disney-and-21st-century-fox-announce-per-share-value-in-connection-with-71-billion-acquisition/|title=Disney and 21st Century Fox Announce per Share Value in Connection with $71 Billion Acquisition|last=|first=|date=March 20, 2019|work=The Walt Disney Company|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nNotable shows produced by 20th Century Fox Television include: [[Batman (TV series)|''Batman'']], ''[[M*A*S*H (TV series)|M*A*S*H]]'', ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'', ''[[How I Met Your Mother]]'', ''[[Bones (TV series)|Bones]]'', ''[[Empire (2015 TV series)|Empire]]'', ''[[Family Guy]]'', ''[[24 (TV series)|24]]'', ''[[Modern Family]]'', ''[[This Is Us (TV series)|This Is Us]]'', ''[[American Dad!]]'', ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]'', ''[[Futurama]]'', ''[[King of the Hill]]'', ''[[New Girl (TV series)|New Girl]]'', ''[[American Horror Story]]'' and most notably ''[[The X-Files]]'' and ''[[The Simpsons]]''.\n\n==Overview and history==\n20th Century Fox Television was formed in 1949 as other studios were branching out into television production as well.  At that time, the company was known as TCF Television Productions, Inc. until 1958. Decades later, TCFTV folded the operations of TV production companies it has acquired: [[Metromedia|Metromedia Producers Corporation]] in 1986, [[New World Pictures|New World Entertainment]] in 1997, and [[MTM Enterprises]] in 1998, and is the current distributor (via its distribution division, [[20th Television]]) for most of the shows originally produced by these companies.\n\nFrom 1986-2019, 20th Century Fox Television served as the Fox [[television network]]'s official production arm (with [[Fox 21 Television Studios|Fox Television Studios]] being viewed as the network's unofficial television production division), producing the bulk of [[television series]] airing on the [[television network]]. TCFTV produced the first two series that aired on Fox's sister network, [[MyNetworkTV]]: the telenovelas ''[[Desire (TV series)|Desire]]'' and ''[[Fashion House]]''.\n\nIn 1989, 20th Century Fox Television's functions were taken over by Twentieth Television Corporation, a separate entity from 20th Century Fox Film Corporation. Both companies were subsidiaries of News Corporation unit Fox Inc.; the move was made to separate the television productions from the movie studio in order to increase the latter's output.<ref name=ap-20thtelevision>{{cite news|last=Horn|first=John|title=20th Century Fox Restructures Film, Television Units|url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1989/20th-Century-Fox-Restructures-Film-Television-Units/id-c84852dbf431b84aa16465a1c851bdb3|accessdate=December 27, 2012|newspaper=[[Associated Press]]|date=July 12, 1989}}</ref> Following a 1994 restructuring of Fox's television production companies, 20th Television was refocused on syndication and \"non-traditional programs\", while network television programming once more came under the 20th Century Fox Television banner and returned to being a division of the movie studio.<ref name=lat-tcftvrestored>{{cite news|title=2 Named to Executive Posts in Fox TV Restructuring|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1994-12-05/business/fi-5172_1_twentieth-century-fox-television|accessdate=December 27, 2012|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=December 5, 1994}}</ref> In 1997, [[MTM Enterprises]] became part of 20th Century Fox Television, and thus remains an in-name only division of TCFTV. In 2012, 20th Century Fox Television was reorganized as a separate unit of News Corporation; 20th Century Fox Television chairs [[Dana Walden]] and Gary Newman now report to [[Chase Carey]], COO of 21st Century Fox.<ref>{{cite web|title=SHOCKER! FOX SHAKEUP: Tom Rothman Exiting 20th Film Group; Jim Gianopulos Becomes Sole Chairman/CEO; 20th TV\u2019s Dana Walden & Gary Newman Now Report To News Corp #2 Chase Carey|url=http://www.deadline.com/2012/09/tom-rothman-departing-fox-filmed-entertainment/|accessdate= May 16, 2013|date=September 14, 2012|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|last=Finke|first=Nikki|author2=Mike Fleming, Jr.}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, it was announced that the operations of the [[Fox Broadcasting Company]] and 20th Century Fox Television would merge into a new unit, the Fox Television Group, which was overseen by Walden and Newman.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/15/business/media/dana-walden-and-gary-newman-to-lead-new-fox-television-group.html|title=21st Century Fox Melds Its Television Broadcasting and Studio Units|last=Steel|first=Emily|date=2014-07-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-04-17|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The Fox network was not included in Disney's acquisition of 21st Century Fox and was one of several assets later spun off to [[Fox Corporation]].  In early 2015, Mythology Entertainment signed a first look deal with the company and fellow company [[Fox 21 Television Studios]] while announcing its TV division head.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Reilly |first1=Travis |title=Mythology Entertainment Signs First Look Deal With Fox TV |url=https://www.thewrap.com/mythology-entertainment-signs-first-look-deal-with-fox-tv/ |accessdate=July 14, 2019 |work=The Wrap |date=March 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, the Disney acquisition of 21st Century Fox was finalized.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/lachlan-murdoch-takes-control-of-fox-corp-but-how-will-he-deal-with-president-trump/2019/03/20/abbb43d6-40ee-11e9-a0d3-1210e58a94cf_story.html |title=Lachlan Murdoch takes control of Fox Corp. But how will he deal with President Trump? |publisher=The Washington Post |date= |accessdate=2019-03-28}}</ref> As a result of the acquisition, Newman departed and Walden was made head of Disney programming.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/new-fox-charlie-collier-gary-newman-exit-1202474293/|title=AMC\u2019s Charlie Collier To Lead Fox Broadcasting Network, Gary Newman To Depart|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=19 October 2018|website=Deadline|publisher=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/dana-walden-talks-disney-tv-strategy-netflix-growing-pains-1165232|title=Dana Walden Goes It Alone: Disney TV Strategy, Netflix \"Growing Pains\" and Why \"Volume Is the Enemy\"|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> Jonnie Davis and Howard Kurtzman, who previously held high ranking positions with the Fox Television Group,<ref>https://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/scully-signs-overall-deal-with-20th-century-fox serve</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/01/twentieth-tv-promotes-business-execs-howard-kurtzman-mark-pearson-673201/|title=20th Century Fox Television Ups Howard Kurtzman & Mark Pearson|date=29 January 2014|website=Deadline|publisher=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> became the co-heads of 20th Century Fox Television.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/disney-fox-tv-layoffs-dana-walden-rallies-staff-memo-1196575|title=Ahead of Disney-Fox TV Layoffs, Dana Walden Rallies Staff in Memo|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> In July 2019, Disney promoted Davis to the position of President of [[ABC Studios]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-abc-studios-patrick-moran-jonnie-davis-20190710-story.html|title=Jonnie Davis becomes president of ABC Studios, replacing Disney veteran Patrick Moran|last=James|first=Meg|website=latimes.com|access-date=2019-07-11}}</ref> Carolyn Cassidy succeeded Davis as President of Creative Affairs at 20th Century Fox Television, running the studio jointly with Kurtzman.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/disney-tv-studios-jonnie-davis-carolyn-cassidy-1203263378/|title=Jonnie Davis to Head ABC Studios, Patrick Moran Out, as Disney TV Studios Restructures|last=Low|first=Elaine|last2=|first2=|date=2019-07-10|website=Variety|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-07-11}}</ref>\n\n==List of programs produced by 20th Century Fox Television==\n{{Main|List of 20th Century Fox television programs}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[20th Television]]\n* [[Foxstar Productions]]\n* [[Fox 21 Television Studios]]\n* [[20th Century Fox]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb company|0056447|20th Century Fox Television}}\n*{{IMDb company|0159275|Fox Television Animation}}\n*{{IMDb company|0164607|Twentieth Century Fox Television}}\n\n{{Fox Entertainment Group}}\n{{Authority control}}\n__NOTOC__\n\n[[Category:1949 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox Television]]\n[[Category:Disney production studios]]\n[[Category:Disney acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies based in California]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies established in 1949]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 1949]]\n[[Category:Peabody Award winners]]\n[[Category:Television production companies of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|TV production company}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Twentieth Century Fox Television, Inc.\n| logo                = 20th_Century_Fox_Television_logo.png\n| former_name         = TCF Television Productions, Inc. (1949-1958)\n| type                = [[Division (business)|Division]]\n| key_people          = Carolyn Cassidy, President, Creative Affairs<br>Howard Kurtzman, President, Business Affairs\n| industry            = [[Television production]]\n| products            = [[Television programs]]\n| owner               = <!-- Per [[Template:Infobox company]], it states: \"If the company is majority-owned by a single entity and as such is a subsidiary or division, omit the owner field and use the parent field instead.\" -->\n| parent              = Disney Television Studios</small>\n| divisions           = [[20th Television]]\n| founded             = {{start date and age|1949}}\n| hq_location_city    = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n| hq_location_country = [[United States]]\n}}\n'''Twentieth Century Fox Television''' (abbreviated as '''TCFTV''' and stylized as '''20th Century Fox Television''') is an American television-production studio owned by [[Walt Disney Television]], a unit of the Disney Media Networks division of [[The Walt Disney Company]].<ref name=\"dl\">{{cite news |last1=Andreeva |first1=Nellie |title=Disney Unveils Top TV Executive Structure Post Fox Acquisition: Peter Rice, Dana Walden, John Landgraf, Gary Knell Joining |url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/disney-top-tv-executive-structure-fox-acquisition-peter-rice-dana-walden-john-landgraf-1202473566/ |accessdate=October 9, 2018 |work=Deadline |date=October 8, 2018}}</ref> [[20th Television]] is the syndication and distribution arm of 20th Century Fox Television.<ref>{{cite news|title=21st Century Fox Realigns TV Syndication, Distribution Biz Underdog/ 20th Century Fox TV|work=[[Foxmovies.com]]|date=July 8, 2013|publisher=Penske Media Corporation}}</ref>\n\n20th Century Fox Television was part of [[Acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney|The Walt Disney Company's acquisition]] of the majority of [[21st Century Fox]]'s assets.<ref name=\"FoxDisneyPressRelease\">{{cite press release|url=https://thewaltdisneycompany.com/walt-disney-company-acquire-twenty-first-century-fox-inc-spinoff-certain-businesses-52-4-billion-stock-2/|title=The Walt Disney Company To Acquire Twenty-First Century Fox, Inc., After Spinoff Of Certain Businesses, For $52.4 Billion In Stock|work=[[The Walt Disney Company]]|date=December 14, 2017|accessdate=December 14, 2017}}</ref> Disney's acquisition of 21st Century Fox was completed on March 20, 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thewaltdisneycompany.com/disney-and-21st-century-fox-announce-per-share-value-in-connection-with-71-billion-acquisition/|title=Disney and 21st Century Fox Announce per Share Value in Connection with $71 Billion Acquisition|last=|first=|date=March 20, 2019|work=The Walt Disney Company|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nNotable shows produced by 20th Century Fox Television owned by [[The Walt Disney Company]] include [[Batman (TV series)|''Batman'']], ''[[M*A*S*H (TV series)|M*A*S*H]]'', ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'', ''[[How I Met Your Mother]]'', ''[[Bones (TV series)|Bones]]'', ''[[Bob's Burgers]]'', ''[[Empire (2015 TV series)|Empire]]'', ''[[Family Guy]]'', ''[[24 (TV series)|24]]'', ''[[Modern Family]]'', ''[[This Is Us (TV series)|This Is Us]]'', ''[[American Dad!]]'', ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]'', ''[[Futurama]]'', ''[[King of the Hill]]'', ''[[New Girl (TV series)|New Girl]]'', ''[[American Horror Story]]'' and most notably ''[[The X-Files]]'' and ''[[The Simpsons]]''.\n\n==Overview and history==\n20th Century Fox Television was formed in 1949 as other studios were branching out into television production as well.  At that time, the company was known as TCF Television Productions, Inc. until 1958. Decades later, TCFTV folded the operations of TV production companies it has acquired: [[Metromedia|Metromedia Producers Corporation]] in 1986, [[New World Pictures|New World Entertainment]] in 1997, and [[MTM Enterprises]] in 1998, and is the current distributor (via its distribution division, [[20th Television]]) for most of the shows originally produced by these companies.\n\nFrom 1986-2019, 20th Century Fox Television served as the Fox [[television network]]'s official production arm (with [[Fox 21 Television Studios|Fox Television Studios]] being viewed as the network's unofficial television production division), producing the bulk of [[television series]] airing on the [[television network]]. TCFTV produced the first two series that aired on Fox's sister network, [[MyNetworkTV]]: the telenovelas ''[[Desire (TV series)|Desire]]'' and ''[[Fashion House]]''.\n\nIn 1989, 20th Century Fox Television's functions were taken over by Twentieth Television Corporation, a separate entity from 20th Century Fox Film Corporation. Both companies were subsidiaries of News Corporation unit Fox Inc.; the move was made to separate the television productions from the movie studio in order to increase the latter's output.<ref name=ap-20thtelevision>{{cite news|last=Horn|first=John|title=20th Century Fox Restructures Film, Television Units|url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1989/20th-Century-Fox-Restructures-Film-Television-Units/id-c84852dbf431b84aa16465a1c851bdb3|accessdate=December 27, 2012|newspaper=[[Associated Press]]|date=July 12, 1989}}</ref> Following a 1994 restructuring of Fox's television production companies, 20th Television was refocused on syndication and \"non-traditional programs\", while network television programming once more came under the 20th Century Fox Television banner and returned to being a division of the movie studio.<ref name=lat-tcftvrestored>{{cite news|title=2 Named to Executive Posts in Fox TV Restructuring|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1994-12-05/business/fi-5172_1_twentieth-century-fox-television|accessdate=December 27, 2012|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=December 5, 1994}}</ref> In 1997, [[MTM Enterprises]] became part of 20th Century Fox Television, and thus remains an in-name only division of TCFTV. In 2012, 20th Century Fox Television was reorganized as a separate unit of News Corporation; 20th Century Fox Television chairs [[Dana Walden]] and Gary Newman now report to [[Chase Carey]], COO of 21st Century Fox.<ref>{{cite web|title=SHOCKER! FOX SHAKEUP: Tom Rothman Exiting 20th Film Group; Jim Gianopulos Becomes Sole Chairman/CEO; 20th TV\u2019s Dana Walden & Gary Newman Now Report To News Corp #2 Chase Carey|url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/09/tom-rothman-departing-fox-filmed-entertainment/|accessdate= May 16, 2013|date=September 14, 2012|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|last=Finke|first=Nikki|author2=Mike Fleming, Jr.}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, it was announced that the operations of the [[Fox Broadcasting Company]] and 20th Century Fox Television would merge into a new unit, the Fox Television Group, which was overseen by Walden and Newman.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/15/business/media/dana-walden-and-gary-newman-to-lead-new-fox-television-group.html|title=21st Century Fox Melds Its Television Broadcasting and Studio Units|last=Steel|first=Emily|date=2014-07-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-04-17|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In early 2015, Mythology Entertainment signed a first look deal with the company and fellow company [[Fox 21 Television Studios]] while announcing its TV division head.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Reilly |first1=Travis |title=Mythology Entertainment Signs First Look Deal With Fox TV |url=https://www.thewrap.com/mythology-entertainment-signs-first-look-deal-with-fox-tv/ |accessdate=July 14, 2019 |work=The Wrap |date=March 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, the Disney acquisition of 21st Century Fox was finalized.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/lachlan-murdoch-takes-control-of-fox-corp-but-how-will-he-deal-with-president-trump/2019/03/20/abbb43d6-40ee-11e9-a0d3-1210e58a94cf_story.html |title=Lachlan Murdoch takes control of Fox Corp. But how will he deal with President Trump? |publisher=The Washington Post |date= |accessdate=2019-03-28}}</ref> As a result of the acquisition, Newman departed and Walden was made head of Disney programming.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/new-fox-charlie-collier-gary-newman-exit-1202474293/|title=AMC\u2019s Charlie Collier To Lead Fox Broadcasting Network, Gary Newman To Depart |last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=19 October 2018|website=Deadline|publisher=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/dana-walden-talks-disney-tv-strategy-netflix-growing-pains-1165232|title=Dana Walden Goes It Alone: Disney TV Strategy, Netflix \"Growing Pains\" and Why \"Volume Is the Enemy\"|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> Jonnie Davis and Howard Kurtzman, who previously held high ranking positions with the Fox Television Group,<ref>https://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/scully-signs-overall-deal-with-20th-century-fox serve</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/01/twentieth-tv-promotes-business-execs-howard-kurtzman-mark-pearson-673201/|title=20th Century Fox Television Ups Howard Kurtzman & Mark Pearson|date=29 January 2014|website=Deadline|publisher=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> became the co-heads of 20th Century Fox Television.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/disney-fox-tv-layoffs-dana-walden-rallies-staff-memo-1196575|title=Ahead of Disney-Fox TV Layoffs, Dana Walden Rallies Staff in Memo|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> In July 2019, Disney promoted Davis to the position of President of [[ABC Studios]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-abc-studios-patrick-moran-jonnie-davis-20190710-story.html|title=Jonnie Davis becomes president of ABC Studios, replacing Disney veteran Patrick Moran|last=James|first=Meg|website=latimes.com|access-date=2019-07-11}}</ref> Carolyn Cassidy succeeded Davis as President of Creative Affairs at 20th Century Fox Television, running the studio jointly with Kurtzman.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/disney-tv-studios-jonnie-davis-carolyn-cassidy-1203263378/|title=Jonnie Davis to Head ABC Studios, Patrick Moran Out, as Disney TV Studios Restructures |last=Low |first=Elaine |date=2019-07-10 |website=Variety|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-07-11}}</ref>  In January 2020, Kurtzman announced that he would retire by June 2020. [[CBS Television Studios]] executive Dan Kupetz has been named the new executive vice president of business affairs and operations and will be joining 20th TV in March 2020. He is reporting to Cassidy, who assumes solo leadership and work closely with Kurtzman until he departs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/howard-kurtzman-sets-retirement-as-carolyn-cassidy-named-lone-20th-tv-president-1267583 |title=Howard Kurtzman Sets Retirement as Carolyn Cassidy Named Lone 20th TV President |last=Goldberg |first=Lesley |date=January 7, 2020 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=16 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/dan-kupetz-head-business-affairs-at-disneys-20th-tv-1268698 |title=Dan Kupetz to Head Business Affairs at Disney's 20th TV |last=Porter |first=Rick |date=January 13, 2020 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=17 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe company signed in 2019 a four-year overall deal with [[Elizabeth Meriwether|Liz Meriwether]], co-creator of ''[[Bless This Mess (TV series)|Bless This Mess]]''. Thus was followed by a production deal with [[Lake Bell|Lake Bell Productions]] in February 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Thorne |first1=Will |last2=Thorne |first2=Will |title=Lake Bell Inks Pod Deal With 20th Century Fox TV |url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/lake-bell-20th-century-fox-tv-pod-deal-1203512831/ |accessdate=February 24, 2020 |work=Variety |date=February 24, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==List of programs produced by 20th Century Fox Television==\n{{Main|List of 20th Century Fox television programs}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[20th Television]]\n* [[Fox Television Stations Productions]]\n* [[Foxstar Productions]]\n* [[Fox 21 Television Studios]]\n* [[FX Productions]]\n* [[Fox Television Animation]]\n* [[20th Century Studios]]\n* [[Searchlight Pictures]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb company|0056447|20th Century Fox Television}}\n*{{IMDb company|0159275|Fox Television Animation}}\n*{{IMDb company|0164607|Twentieth Century Fox Television}}\n\n{{Walt Disney Television|state=expanded}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n__NOTOC__\n\n[[Category:1949 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox Television]]\n[[Category:Disney production studios]]\n[[Category:Disney acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies based in California]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies established in 1949]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 1949]]\n[[Category:Peabody Award winners]]\n[[Category:Television production companies of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "102.176.94.64", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(edit summary removed)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/20th_Century_Fox_Television"}
{"title_page": "Vinnie Vincent", "text_new": "{{short description|American musician}}\n\n[http://noisecreep.com/kiss-guitarist-vinnie-vincent-wont-face-animal-cruelty-charg/]{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2011}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Vinnie Vincent\n| image            = Vinnie Vincent Invasion - Vinnie Vincent.png\n| caption          = Vinnie Vincent C. 1985\n| image_size       = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1952|8|6}}\n| birth_place      = [[Bridgeport, Connecticut]], United States\n| birth_name       = Vincent John Cusano\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| alias            = \"The Ankh Warrior\"\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Glam metal]]\n* [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]]\n* [[hard rock]]\n}}\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n* Musician\n* songwriter\n}}\n| instrument       = {{flatlist|\n* Guitar\n* vocals\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n* [[Vinnie Vincent Invasion]]\n* [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]]\n* [[Dan Hartman]]\n* Treasure\n* [[Laura Nyro]]\n* Warrior\n* Heat\n}}\n| years_active     = {{flatlist|\n* 1970\u20131997\n* 2017-2019\n}}\n}}\n'''Vincent John Cusano''' (born August 6, 1952), better known by his [[stage name]] '''Vinnie Vincent''', is an American guitarist and [[songwriter]]. He is a former member of the rock band [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]] from 1982 until mid-1984 during the band's transition out of their 1973\u20131983 makeup period. Vincent was the last member to wear a unique makeup/costume configuration, as the character of '''The Ankh Warrior''' (a design created by [[Paul Stanley]]), until he and the band were first shown without the makeup during an interview on MTV in September 1983.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/news/23139/greatest-replacement-guitarists-in-rock/|title=Ranking Rock\u2019s 10 Greatest Replacement Guitarists|publisher=VH1.com|accessdate=May 26, 2016}}</ref> He also was the leader of his own band, [[Vinnie Vincent Invasion]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bridgeport.ct.schoolwebpages.com/education/components/scrapbook/default.php?sectiondetailid=30126|title=Central High School Biography of Vinnie Vincent|accessdate=November 3, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.msn.com/music/artist-biography/vinnie-vincent/|title=Vinnie Vincent:Biography|publisher=MSN.Com|accessdate=November 3, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714220445/http://music.msn.com/music/artist-biography/vinnie-vincent/|archive-date=July 14, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nVincent John Cusano was born in Bridgeport, Connecticut, the son of Theresa \"Terri\" (Ferraro) and Alfonso Cusano, musicians. Both of his parents were of Italian descent.<ref name=\"vinnie-vincent\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vinnie-vincent.com/biography/index.html|title=VINNIE-VINCENT.COM \u2013 A Vinnie Biography, Part 1: The Wilderness|publisher=vinnie-vincent.com|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref> He picked up the guitar at an early age and was inspired by [[Bluegrass music|bluegrass]] and [[rock and roll]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Prato |first=Greg |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/vinnie-vincent-invasion-p5765/ |title=Vinnie Vincent |publisher=AllMusic |accessdate=April 1, 2012}}</ref> Cusano's first introduction to working with internationally renowned artists was working with Felix Cavaliere (mostly widely known from \"The Rascals\" and their hit \"Good Lovin\" prior) as part of the band \"Treasure\".  This resulted in an album of the same name being released on Epic Records in 1977. It was recorded in New York City at Sound Ideas recording studios <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.discogs.com/Treasure-Treasure/release/3332637 |title=Treasure \u2013 Treasure (Vinyl, LP, Album) {{!}} Discogs |access-date=April 20, 2017}}</ref>  In 1980, Vincent moved to [[Los Angeles, California]] where he became a staff songwriter for the television series ''[[Happy Days]]'' and ''[[Joanie Loves Chachi]]''. Many of the series songs were written on Vincent's [[acoustic guitar]] while sitting at the Cunninghams' kitchen table on the ''Happy Days'' set, during off-time from the show's rehearsal schedule. Vincent has said the times of working at the Paramount lot were genuinely \"happy days\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kissfaq.com/members/bio_vinnie.html |title=Vinnie Vincent Biography |publisher=KissFAQ |accessdate=July 9, 2008 |date=September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080924134948/http://www.kissfaq.com/members/bio_vinnie.html |archive-date=September 24, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> According to the site \"Kiss Related Recordings\", Vincent has played with [[Dan Hartman]] as well as the bands Hunter, Warrior, Hitchhikers and Heat going as far back as 1970.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\n==Career==\n===Kiss===\n[[File:KISS ankh warrior face.svg|thumb|left|120px|\"The Ankh Warrior\"]]\nAfter being introduced to the band by songwriter [[Adam Mitchell (songwriter)|Adam Mitchell]],<ref name=\"kissasylum\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kissasylum.com/vault/issue9.html|title=KISS Asylum: KISS Thought Vault: Issue #9|publisher=kissasylum.com|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref> Vincent was brought in as the replacement for guitarist [[Ace Frehley]]. Vincent's personality meshed well with [[Gene Simmons]] and [[Paul Stanley]], thus enabling him to play lead guitar on six of the nine tracks on the ''[[Creatures of the Night]]'' album as well as co-writing three. After a disappointing Creatures of the Night/Tenth Anniversary tour, that finished on a high at what ended up being the \"last\" makeup show (and Kiss' largest crowd attendance) at Maracan\u00e3 Stadium, Rio de Janeiro, Brasil, Vincent returned to the studio with Kiss to record the ''[[Lick It Up]]'' album. His work was productive, yielding eight co-writes out of the ten songs on the album (a record for any member until [[Bruce Kulick]]'s nine on ''[[Carnival of Souls: The Final Sessions|Carnival of Souls]]'' and Stanley's ten on ''[[Monster (Kiss album)|Monster]]'').{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nThough contributing to ''Creatures of the Night'' as a session player before being named as Frehley's replacement in December 1982, Vincent, for all the public knew, was the official guitarist in Kiss and played all the lead guitar tracks on ''Lick it Up''. In what was a frequent occurrence for former guitarist Frehley, a \"ghost player\" was asked to play on the album, with [[Rick Derringer]] recording the solo on the opening track.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\n[[File:Exciter with Vincent solo.ogg|thumb|\"Exciter\" by Kiss with Vinnie Vincent solo.| right]]\n\nThough the band seemed to have renewed vigor on stage, all was not well. Vincent's refusal to sign the employment contract strained the relationship with Simmons/Stanley. Due partly to disputes over what his role in the band was and his pay would be (some reports indicated that Vincent had asked for, and was flatly denied, a percentage of the band's gross profits), and despite the exhortations of both Simmons and Stanley, all through his tenure with the band Vincent refused to sign any contract, making his employment unofficial. This ultimately led to Vincent leaving the band after the North American leg of the \"Lick It Up\" tour.<ref name=\"DS 1997\">Black Diamond: The Unauthorized Biography of KISS | Dale Sherman | 1997</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Lick It Up Tour]] ended in March 1984, Vincent was terminated from the band, and replaced by [[Mark St. John]].<ref name=\"DS 1997\"/> Despite parting on bad terms, Vincent was later utilized by Kiss as a songwriter on the 1992 album ''[[Revenge (Kiss album)|Revenge]]'', contributing to the songs \"[[Unholy (song)|Unholy]]\", \"Heart Of Chrome\" and \"I Just Wanna\". Vincent again fell out of favor with Simmons and Stanley, as they claimed that Vincent again began \"making all kinds of crazy demands and pulling the same kind of crazy stuff all over again\".<ref name=\"DS 1997\"/>\n\n===Vinnie Vincent Invasion===\nFollowing his departure from Kiss in mid-1984, Vincent used his money that he made from his tenure in the band to take a long vacation and traveled the world for a full year visiting places like [[Tahiti]], [[Philippines]], [[Mozambique]], [[India]] and [[European Union|Europe]], including a visit to the small town [[Mora Municipality, Sweden|Mora]] in [[Dalarna]], [[Sweden]].<ref name=\"forumbilder\">{{cite web|url=http://forumbilder.se/images/8317200911401762e1.jpg|title=Image: 8317200911401762e1.jpg, (570 \u00d7 784 px)|publisher=forumbilder.se|accessdate=September 4, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219074453/http://forumbilder.se/images/8317200911401762e1.jpg|archive-date=December 19, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Then he formed the band [[Vinnie Vincent Invasion]] with, among others, former [[Journey (band)|Journey]] singer [[Robert Fleischman]] in the mid-1980s and released two studio albums: ''[[Vinnie Vincent Invasion (album)|Vinnie Vincent Invasion]]'' in 1986 and ''[[All Systems Go (Vinnie Vincent Invasion album)|All Systems Go]]'' in 1988. The band broke up in 1989. After that, the band's singer [[Mark Slaughter]] and bassist [[Dana Strum]] formed [[Slaughter (band)|Slaughter]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\n===Later career===\nIn 1996, Vincent released a solo EP from the studio sessions he did in 1990 (some say 1989\u201391), called ''[[Euphoria (Vinnie Vincent album)|Euphoria]]'', once again with [[Robert Fleischman]] on vocals. Vincent, as well as playing all the guitars, played bass and did the drum programming under the guise of \"V. Meister\". Andre LaBelle provided drum tracks to the CD but they were replaced by Vincent's drum programming. LaBelle can be heard on various tracks on the bootleg Guitarmaggedon/Guitars from Hell CD that featured five more songs than the ''Euphoria'' EP.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nA tribute album entitled ''[[Kiss My Ankh|Kiss My Ankh: A Tribute To Vinnie Vincent]]'' was released by SplitScreen Entertainment on August 27, 2008. The album consists of new recordings of songs from Vincent's careers with Kiss and the Vinnie Vincent Invasion. Featured artists include Steve Brown of [[Trixter]], [[Troy Patrick Farrell]] of [[White Lion]], [[T.J. Racer]] of [[Nitro (band)|Nitro]], Mike Weeks of [[Robert Fleischman]]'s band, [[Sheldon Tarsha]] of [[Adler's Appetite]], [[Chris Caffery]] of [[Savatage]] and [[Trans-Siberian Orchestra]], [[Ryan Roxie]] from the [[Alice Cooper]] band and rock and roll comic [[C.C. Banana]], who performs a parody of the Kiss song \"[[Unholy (song)|Unholy]]\" (rewritten as a roast of [[Danger Danger]] vocalist [[Ted Poley]]).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.splitscreenentertainment.com | title=Kiss My Ankh: A Tribute To Vinnie Vincent | publisher=SplitScreen Entertainment | accessdate=August 31, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080831201119/http://www.splitscreenentertainment.com/ | archive-date=August 31, 2008 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Appearances in 2018\u20132019===\n\nAfter 22 years of being off the radar, Vinnie Vincent agreed to appear at the 2018 Atlanta Kiss Expo in January.<ref>{{cite web|title=Former KISS Guitarist Vinnie Vincent Is 'Happy And Excited' About His Appearance At Atlanta KISS Expo|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/former-kiss-guitarist-vinnie-vincent-is-happy-and-excited-about-his-appearance-at-atlanta-kiss-expo/|website=Blabbermouth|accessdate=October 19, 2017}}</ref> Vincent fulfilled his commitment and appeared at the sold-out expo. He said he considers Gene Simmons and Paul Stanley family, wishing them nothing but the best. After some e-mail exchanges with Gene Simmons, Vincent agreed to appear with Simmons on stage in April 2018 which was the first time they have met in person in over two decades.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Magnotta |first1=Andrew |title=Gene Simmons Reunites With Vinnie Vincent at Vault Event in Nashville |url=https://www.iheart.com/content/2018-04-18-gene-simmons-reunites-with-vinnie-vincent-at-vault-event-in-nashville/ |website=iheart.com |publisher=IHeart Media, Inc. |accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref> He also gave an exclusive interview to [[Eddie Trunk]] for [[Sirius XM]], which was his first in over two decades, and held multiple question-and-answer sessions with fans.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vinnie Vincent Returns: 10 Things We Learned|url=http://ultimateclassicrock.com/vinnie-vincent-return-things-we-learned/|website=Ultimate Classic Rock|accessdate=January 20, 2018}}</ref> \n\nOn February 16, 2018, it was announced via Facebook that Vinnie would appear at the Days of the Dead convention in Charlotte, North Carolina in May 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/daysofthedead/posts/1690709640967382 |title=Days Of The Dead |website=www.facebook.com |access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref>\n\nVinnie Vincent's first concert in 30 years was scheduled for December 7, 2018 at Graceland, in Memphis, Tennessee. However these shows were postponed until February 8\u20139, 2019 in Nashville<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vinnievincentlive.com|title=Vinnie Vincent Live|website=Vinnie Vincent Live|language=en|access-date=2018-08-05}}</ref>, before being cancelled.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ultimateclassicrock.com/vinnie-vincent-cancels-comeback-shows/|title=Vinnie Vincent Cancels Comeback Shows|last=Kielty|first=Martin|website=Ultimate Classic Rock|language=en|access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref>\n\nVincent then announced another show in Nashville called \"Speedball Jamm\", which was scheduled for June 7, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ultimateclassicrock.com/vinnie-vincent-nashville/|title=Former Kiss Guitarist Vinnie Vincent Announces Nashville Concert|last=Irwin|first=Corey|website=Ultimate Classic Rock|language=en|access-date=2019-05-27}}</ref> This show was ultimately cancelled.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ultimateclassicrock.com/vinnie-vincent-cancel-june-2019-show/|title=Vinnie Vincent Reportedly Cancels June Comeback Show|last=Wilkening|first=Matthew|website=Ultimate Classic Rock|language=en|access-date=2019-05-27}}</ref>\n\nTwo months later, Vincent hosted VINNIE VINCENT's BIRTHDAY BASH on August 10th in Nashville, TN, followed by VINNIE VINCENT's MERRY METAL CHRISTMAS on December 14\u201315, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vinnievincent.com/product/vinnie-vincents-merry-metal-christmas/|title=Vinnie Vincent\u2019s Merry Metal Christmas Premium Ticket \u2013 Vinnie Vincent|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nVincent was married to AnnMarie Peters, and has twin daughters with her.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/the-long-kiss-goodbye-the-search-for-vinnie-vincent-187427/|title=Inside a Hair-Metal Meltdown: Search for Ex-Kiss Guitarist Vinnie Vincent|first1=Max|last1=Blau|first2=Max|last2=Blau|date=April 8, 2014}}</ref> AnnMarie was murdered in 1998, after she and Vincent had divorced.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-xpm-2003-02-15-0302151808-story.html |title=MCARTHUR SENTENCED TO 60 YEARS |last=Writer |first=TINA A. BROWN; Courant Staff |website=courant.com |access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Kiss===\n*''[[Creatures of the Night]]'' (1982)\n*''[[Lick It Up]]'' (1983)\n*''[[Revenge (Kiss album)|Revenge]]'' (1992) songwriting credits only\n\n=== Compilation ===\n*''[[Smashes, Thrashes & Hits]]'' (1988)\n*''[[Alive III]]'' (1993) songwriting credits only\n*''[[Kiss Unplugged]]'' (1995) songwriting credits only\n*''[[The Box Set (Kiss)|The Box Set]]'' (2001)\n*''[[The Very Best of Kiss]]'' (2002)\n*''[[Kiss Symphony: Alive IV]]'' (2003) songwriting credits only\n*''[[The Best of Kiss, Volume 2: The Millennium Collection]]'' (2004)\n*''[[The Best of Kiss, Volume 3: The Millennium Collection]]'' (2006) songwriting credits only\n*''[[Kiss Alive! 1975-2000]]'' (2006) songwriting credits only\n*''The Best of KISS: Green Series'' (2008)\n*''Playlist Plus'' (2008)\n*''Playlist Your Way'' (2008)\n*''[[Jigoku-Retsuden]]'' (2008) songwriting credits only\n*''15 Classics'' (2008) digital download only\n*''15 Discoveries'' (2008) digital download only\n*''45 The Complete Collection'' (2008) digital download only\n*''[[Kiss Alive! 1975\u20132000|Alive! The Millennium Concert]]'' (2008) songwriting credits & digital download only\n\n===Vinnie Vincent Invasion===\n*''[[Vinnie Vincent Invasion (album)|Vinnie Vincent Invasion]]'' ([[1986 in music|1986]])\n*''[[All Systems Go (Vinnie Vincent Invasion album)|All Systems Go]]'' ([[1988 in music|1988]])\n*''[[Euphoria (Vinnie Vincent album)|Euphoria]]'' (EP) (1996)\n\n===Black Satin===\n* ''Black Satin featuring Fred Parris'' (1976)\n\n===The Hitchhikers===\n* ''The Hitchhikers'' (1976)\n\n===Wendy O. Williams===\n*''[[WOW (Wendy O. Williams album)|WOW]]'' (1984 Passport)\n\"Ain't None Of Your Business\" Songwriter (Simmons, Carr & Vincent) & Guitar\n\n===Peter Criss===\n*''[[Let Me Rock You]]'' (1982)\n\n===John Waite===\n*''[[No Brakes]]'' (1984 EMI)\nSongwriter \"Tears\" (1981)\n\n===Dan Hartman===\n*''[[Instant Replay (Dan Hartman album)|Instant Replay]]'' (1978)\nRhythm & Acoustic Guitars, Tambourine, Backing Vocal\n\n===Laura Nyro===\n* ''[[Nested]]'' (1978)\n\n===Treasure===\n*''[[Felix Cavaliere#Treasure|Treasure]]'' (1977 [[Epic Records|Epic]])\nGuitar & Lead Vocals on \"Innocent Eyes\" & \"Turn Yourself Around\"\n(with Felix Cavaliere: of The Rascals)\n\n===Felix Cavaliere===\n* ''Castles in the Air'' (1979)\n\n===HEAT===\n* ''Still Waiting'' (1981)\n\n===Tribute albums and singles===\n*''[[Kiss My Ankh|Kiss My Ankh: A Tribute to Vinnie Vincent]]'' (2008)\n*''Virtual Invasion \u2013 Gypsy in Her Eyes'' (2017)\n*''Virtual Invasion \u2013 Young Blood, Young Fire'' (2018)\n*''Virtual Invasion \u2013 Forbidden'' (2018)\n*''Virtual Invasion - Tears'' (2020)\n\n===The Bangles===\n*''[[Everything (The Bangles album)|Everything]]'' (1988) Songwriting credit & Guitars for \"Make a Play for Her Now\"  <ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/everything-mw0000197855|title=Everything \u2013 Bangles &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards &#124; AllMusic|publisher=allmusic.com|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Was Not Was===\n* ''[[Born to Laugh at Tornadoes]]'' (1983)\n\n===Warrior===\n* ''Warrior'' (2017 HNE Recordings). Collection of Demos.\n* ''Warrior II'' (2019 HNE Recordings). Another Collection of Demos.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Kiss (band)|Lead guitarist of Kiss]]| before=[[Ace Frehley]]| after=[[Mark St. John]]| years=1982\u20131984}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Kiss}}\n{{Vinnie Vincent Invasion}}\n{{Portalbar|Connecticut}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vincent, Vinnie}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Bridgeport, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American heavy metal guitarists]]\n[[Category:American rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Lead guitarists]]\n[[Category:Glam metal musicians]]\n[[Category:Kiss (band) members]]\n[[Category:Vinnie Vincent Invasion members]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American musician}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2011}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Vinnie Vincent\n| image            = Vinnie Vincent Invasion - Vinnie Vincent.png\n| caption          = Vinnie Vincent C. 1985\n| image_size       = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1952|8|6}}\n| birth_place      = [[Bridgeport, Connecticut]], United States\n| birth_name       = Vincent John Cusano\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| alias            = \"The Ankh Warrior\"\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Glam metal]]\n* [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]]\n* [[hard rock]]\n}}\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n* Musician\n* songwriter\n}}\n| instrument       = {{flatlist|\n* Guitar\n* vocals\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n* [[Vinnie Vincent Invasion]]\n* [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]]\n* [[Dan Hartman]]\n* Treasure\n* [[Laura Nyro]]\n* Warrior\n* Heat\n}}\n| years_active     = {{flatlist|\n* 1970\u20131997\n* 2018\u2013present\n}}\n}}\n'''Vincent John Cusano''' (born August 6, 1952), better known by his [[stage name]] '''Vinnie Vincent''', is an American guitarist and [[songwriter]]. He is a former member of the rock band [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]] from 1982 until mid-1984 during the band's transition out of their 1973\u20131983 makeup period. Vincent was the last member to wear a unique makeup/costume configuration, as the character of '''The Ankh Warrior''' (a design created by [[Paul Stanley]]), until he and the band were first shown without the makeup during an interview on MTV in September 1983.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/news/23139/greatest-replacement-guitarists-in-rock/|title=Ranking Rock\u2019s 10 Greatest Replacement Guitarists|publisher=VH1.com|accessdate=May 26, 2016}}</ref> He also was the leader of his own band, [[Vinnie Vincent Invasion]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bridgeport.ct.schoolwebpages.com/education/components/scrapbook/default.php?sectiondetailid=30126|title=Central High School Biography of Vinnie Vincent|accessdate=November 3, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.msn.com/music/artist-biography/vinnie-vincent/|title=Vinnie Vincent:Biography|publisher=MSN.Com|accessdate=November 3, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714220445/http://music.msn.com/music/artist-biography/vinnie-vincent/|archive-date=July 14, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nVincent John Cusano was born in Bridgeport, Connecticut, the son of Theresa \"Terri\" (Ferraro) and Alfonso Cusano, musicians. Both of his parents were of Italian descent.<ref name=\"vinnie-vincent\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vinnie-vincent.com/biography/index.html|title=VINNIE-VINCENT.COM \u2013 A Vinnie Biography, Part 1: The Wilderness|publisher=vinnie-vincent.com|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref> He picked up the guitar at an early age and was inspired by [[Bluegrass music|bluegrass]] and [[rock and roll]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Prato |first=Greg |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/vinnie-vincent-invasion-p5765/ |title=Vinnie Vincent |publisher=AllMusic |accessdate=April 1, 2012}}</ref> Cusano's first introduction to working with internationally renowned artists was working with Felix Cavaliere (mostly widely known from \"The Rascals\" and their hit \"Good Lovin\" prior) as part of the band \"Treasure\".  This resulted in an album of the same name being released on Epic Records in 1977. It was recorded in New York City at Sound Ideas recording studios <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.discogs.com/Treasure-Treasure/release/3332637 |title=Treasure \u2013 Treasure (Vinyl, LP, Album) {{!}} Discogs |access-date=April 20, 2017}}</ref>  In 1980, Vincent moved to [[Los Angeles, California]] where he became a staff songwriter for the television series ''[[Happy Days]]'' and ''[[Joanie Loves Chachi]]''. Many of the series songs were written on Vincent's [[acoustic guitar]] while sitting at the Cunninghams' kitchen table on the ''Happy Days'' set, during off-time from the show's rehearsal schedule. Vincent has said the times of working at the Paramount lot were genuinely \"happy days\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kissfaq.com/members/bio_vinnie.html |title=Vinnie Vincent Biography |publisher=KissFAQ |accessdate=July 9, 2008 |date=September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080924134948/http://www.kissfaq.com/members/bio_vinnie.html |archive-date=September 24, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> According to the site \"Kiss Related Recordings\", Vincent has played with [[Dan Hartman]] as well as the bands Hunter, Warrior, Hitchhikers and Heat going as far back as 1970.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\n==Career==\n===Kiss===\n[[File:KISS ankh warrior face.svg|thumb|left|120px|\"The Ankh Warrior\"]]\nAfter being introduced to the band by songwriter [[Adam Mitchell (songwriter)|Adam Mitchell]],<ref name=\"kissasylum\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kissasylum.com/vault/issue9.html|title=KISS Asylum: KISS Thought Vault: Issue #9|publisher=kissasylum.com|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref> Vincent was brought in as the replacement for guitarist [[Ace Frehley]]. Vincent's personality meshed well with [[Gene Simmons]] and [[Paul Stanley]], thus enabling him to play lead guitar on six of the nine tracks on the ''[[Creatures of the Night]]'' album as well as co-writing three. After a disappointing Creatures of the Night/Tenth Anniversary tour, that finished on a high at what ended up being the \"last\" makeup show (and Kiss' largest crowd attendance) at Maracan\u00e3 Stadium, Rio de Janeiro, Brasil, Vincent returned to the studio with Kiss to record the ''[[Lick It Up]]'' album. His work was productive, yielding eight co-writes out of the ten songs on the album (a record for any member until [[Bruce Kulick]]'s nine on ''[[Carnival of Souls: The Final Sessions|Carnival of Souls]]'' and Stanley's ten on ''[[Monster (Kiss album)|Monster]]'').{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nThough contributing to ''Creatures of the Night'' as a session player before being named as Frehley's replacement in December 1982, Vincent, for all the public knew, was the official guitarist in Kiss and played all the lead guitar tracks on ''Lick it Up''. In what was a frequent occurrence for former guitarist Frehley, a \"ghost player\" was asked to play on the album, with [[Rick Derringer]] recording the solo on the opening track.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\n[[File:Exciter with Vincent solo.ogg|thumb|\"Exciter\" by Kiss with Vinnie Vincent solo.| right]]\n\nThough the band seemed to have renewed vigor on stage, all was not well. Vincent's refusal to sign the employment contract strained the relationship with Simmons/Stanley. Due partly to disputes over what his role in the band was and his pay would be (some reports indicated that Vincent had asked for, and was flatly denied, a percentage of the band's gross profits), and despite the exhortations of both Simmons and Stanley, all through his tenure with the band Vincent refused to sign any contract, making his employment unofficial. This ultimately led to Vincent leaving the band after the North American leg of the \"Lick It Up\" tour.<ref name=\"DS 1997\">Black Diamond: The Unauthorized Biography of KISS | Dale Sherman | 1997</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Lick It Up Tour]] ended in March 1984, Vincent was terminated from the band, and replaced by [[Mark St. John]].<ref name=\"DS 1997\"/> Despite parting on bad terms, Vincent was later utilized by Kiss as a songwriter on the 1992 album ''[[Revenge (Kiss album)|Revenge]]'', contributing to the songs \"[[Unholy (song)|Unholy]]\", \"Heart Of Chrome\" and \"I Just Wanna\". Vincent again fell out of favor with Simmons and Stanley, as they claimed that Vincent again began \"making all kinds of crazy demands and pulling the same kind of crazy stuff all over again\".<ref name=\"DS 1997\"/>\n\n===Vinnie Vincent Invasion===\nFollowing his departure from Kiss in mid-1984, Vincent used his money that he made from his tenure in the band to take a long vacation and traveled the world for a full year visiting places like [[Tahiti]], [[Philippines]], [[Mozambique]], [[India]] and [[European Union|Europe]], including a visit to the small town [[Mora Municipality, Sweden|Mora]] in [[Dalarna]], [[Sweden]].<ref name=\"forumbilder\">{{cite web|url=http://forumbilder.se/images/8317200911401762e1.jpg|title=Image: 8317200911401762e1.jpg, (570 \u00d7 784 px)|publisher=forumbilder.se|accessdate=September 4, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219074453/http://forumbilder.se/images/8317200911401762e1.jpg|archive-date=December 19, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Then he formed the band [[Vinnie Vincent Invasion]] with, among others, former [[Journey (band)|Journey]] singer [[Robert Fleischman]] in the mid-1980s and released two studio albums: ''[[Vinnie Vincent Invasion (album)|Vinnie Vincent Invasion]]'' in 1986 and ''[[All Systems Go (Vinnie Vincent Invasion album)|All Systems Go]]'' in 1988. The band broke up in 1989. After that, the band's singer [[Mark Slaughter]] and bassist [[Dana Strum]] formed [[Slaughter (band)|Slaughter]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\n===Later career===\nIn 1996, Vincent released a solo EP from the studio sessions he did in 1990 (some say 1989\u201391), called ''[[Euphoria (Vinnie Vincent album)|Euphoria]]'', once again with [[Robert Fleischman]] on vocals. Vincent, as well as playing all the guitars, played bass and did the drum programming under the guise of \"V. Meister\". Andre LaBelle provided drum tracks to the CD but they were replaced by Vincent's drum programming. LaBelle can be heard on various tracks on the bootleg Guitarmaggedon/Guitars from Hell CD that featured five more songs than the ''Euphoria'' EP.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nA tribute album entitled ''[[Kiss My Ankh|Kiss My Ankh: A Tribute To Vinnie Vincent]]'' was released by SplitScreen Entertainment on August 27, 2008. The album consists of new recordings of songs from Vincent's careers with Kiss and the Vinnie Vincent Invasion. Featured artists include Steve Brown of [[Trixter]], [[Troy Patrick Farrell]] of [[White Lion]], [[T.J. Racer]] of [[Nitro (band)|Nitro]], Mike Weeks of [[Robert Fleischman]]'s band, [[Sheldon Tarsha]] of [[Adler's Appetite]], [[Chris Caffery]] of [[Savatage]] and [[Trans-Siberian Orchestra]], [[Ryan Roxie]] from the [[Alice Cooper]] band and rock and roll comic [[C.C. Banana]], who performs a parody of the Kiss song \"[[Unholy (song)|Unholy]]\" (rewritten as a roast of [[Danger Danger]] vocalist [[Ted Poley]]).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.splitscreenentertainment.com | title=Kiss My Ankh: A Tribute To Vinnie Vincent | publisher=SplitScreen Entertainment | accessdate=August 31, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080831201119/http://www.splitscreenentertainment.com/ | archive-date=August 31, 2008 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Appearances in 2018\u20132019===\n\nAfter 22 years of being off the radar, Vinnie Vincent agreed to appear at the 2018 Atlanta Kiss Expo in January.<ref>{{cite web|title=Former KISS Guitarist Vinnie Vincent Is 'Happy And Excited' About His Appearance At Atlanta KISS Expo|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/former-kiss-guitarist-vinnie-vincent-is-happy-and-excited-about-his-appearance-at-atlanta-kiss-expo/|website=Blabbermouth|accessdate=October 19, 2017}}</ref> Vincent fulfilled his commitment and appeared at the sold-out expo. He said he considers Gene Simmons and Paul Stanley family, wishing them nothing but the best. After some e-mail exchanges with Gene Simmons, Vincent agreed to appear with Simmons on stage in April 2018 which was the first time they have met in person in over two decades.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Magnotta |first1=Andrew |title=Gene Simmons Reunites With Vinnie Vincent at Vault Event in Nashville |url=https://www.iheart.com/content/2018-04-18-gene-simmons-reunites-with-vinnie-vincent-at-vault-event-in-nashville/ |website=iheart.com |publisher=IHeart Media, Inc. |accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref> He also gave an exclusive interview to [[Eddie Trunk]] for [[Sirius XM]], which was his first in over two decades, and held multiple question-and-answer sessions with fans.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vinnie Vincent Returns: 10 Things We Learned|url=http://ultimateclassicrock.com/vinnie-vincent-return-things-we-learned/|website=Ultimate Classic Rock|accessdate=January 20, 2018}}</ref> \n\nOn February 16, 2018, it was announced via Facebook that Vinnie would appear at the Days of the Dead convention in Charlotte, North Carolina in May 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/daysofthedead/posts/1690709640967382 |title=Days Of The Dead |website=www.facebook.com |access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref>\n\nVinnie Vincent's first concert in 30 years was scheduled for December 7, 2018 at Graceland, in Memphis, Tennessee. However these shows were postponed until February 8\u20139, 2019 in Nashville<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vinnievincentlive.com|title=Vinnie Vincent Live|website=Vinnie Vincent Live|language=en|access-date=2018-08-05}}</ref>, before being cancelled.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ultimateclassicrock.com/vinnie-vincent-cancels-comeback-shows/|title=Vinnie Vincent Cancels Comeback Shows|last=Kielty|first=Martin|website=Ultimate Classic Rock|language=en|access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref>\n\nVincent then announced another show in Nashville called \"Speedball Jamm\", which was scheduled for June 7, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ultimateclassicrock.com/vinnie-vincent-nashville/|title=Former Kiss Guitarist Vinnie Vincent Announces Nashville Concert|last=Irwin|first=Corey|website=Ultimate Classic Rock|language=en|access-date=2019-05-27}}</ref> This show was ultimately cancelled.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ultimateclassicrock.com/vinnie-vincent-cancel-june-2019-show/|title=Vinnie Vincent Reportedly Cancels June Comeback Show|last=Wilkening|first=Matthew|website=Ultimate Classic Rock|language=en|access-date=2019-05-27}}</ref>\n\nTwo months later, Vincent hosted VINNIE VINCENT's BIRTHDAY BASH on August 10th in Nashville, TN, followed by VINNIE VINCENT's MERRY METAL CHRISTMAS on December 14\u201315, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vinnievincent.com/product/vinnie-vincents-merry-metal-christmas/|title=Vinnie Vincent\u2019s Merry Metal Christmas Premium Ticket \u2013 Vinnie Vincent|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nVincent was married to AnnMarie Peters, and has twin daughters with her.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/the-long-kiss-goodbye-the-search-for-vinnie-vincent-187427/|title=Inside a Hair-Metal Meltdown: Search for Ex-Kiss Guitarist Vinnie Vincent|first1=Max|last1=Blau|first2=Max|last2=Blau|date=April 8, 2014}}</ref> AnnMarie was murdered in 1998, after she and Vincent had divorced.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-xpm-2003-02-15-0302151808-story.html |title=MCARTHUR SENTENCED TO 60 YEARS |last=Writer |first=TINA A. BROWN; Courant Staff |website=courant.com |access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Kiss===\n*''[[Creatures of the Night]]'' (1982)\n*''[[Lick It Up]]'' (1983)\n*''[[Revenge (Kiss album)|Revenge]]'' (1992) songwriting credits only\n\n=== Compilation ===\n*''[[Smashes, Thrashes & Hits]]'' (1988)\n*''[[Alive III]]'' (1993) songwriting credits only\n*''[[Kiss Unplugged]]'' (1995) songwriting credits only\n*''[[The Box Set (Kiss)|The Box Set]]'' (2001)\n*''[[The Very Best of Kiss]]'' (2002)\n*''[[Kiss Symphony: Alive IV]]'' (2003) songwriting credits only\n*''[[The Best of Kiss, Volume 2: The Millennium Collection]]'' (2004)\n*''[[The Best of Kiss, Volume 3: The Millennium Collection]]'' (2006) songwriting credits only\n*''[[Kiss Alive! 1975-2000]]'' (2006) songwriting credits only\n*''The Best of KISS: Green Series'' (2008)\n*''Playlist Plus'' (2008)\n*''Playlist Your Way'' (2008)\n*''[[Jigoku-Retsuden]]'' (2008) songwriting credits only\n*''15 Classics'' (2008) digital download only\n*''15 Discoveries'' (2008) digital download only\n*''45 The Complete Collection'' (2008) digital download only\n*''[[Kiss Alive! 1975\u20132000|Alive! The Millennium Concert]]'' (2008) songwriting credits & digital download only\n\n===Vinnie Vincent Invasion===\n*''[[Vinnie Vincent Invasion (album)|Vinnie Vincent Invasion]]'' ([[1986 in music|1986]])\n*''[[All Systems Go (Vinnie Vincent Invasion album)|All Systems Go]]'' ([[1988 in music|1988]])\n*''[[Euphoria (Vinnie Vincent album)|Euphoria]]'' (EP) (1996)\n\n===Black Satin===\n* ''Black Satin featuring Fred Parris'' (1976)\n\n===The Hitchhikers===\n* ''The Hitchhikers'' (1976)\n\n===Wendy O. Williams===\n*''[[WOW (Wendy O. Williams album)|WOW]]'' (1984 Passport)\n\"Ain't None Of Your Business\" Songwriter (Simmons, Carr & Vincent) & Guitar\n\n===Peter Criss===\n*''[[Let Me Rock You]]'' (1982)\n\n===John Waite===\n*''[[No Brakes]]'' (1984 EMI)\nSongwriter \"Tears\" (1981)\n\n===Dan Hartman===\n*''[[Instant Replay (Dan Hartman album)|Instant Replay]]'' (1978)\nRhythm & Acoustic Guitars, Tambourine, Backing Vocal\n\n===Laura Nyro===\n* ''[[Nested]]'' (1978)\n\n===Treasure===\n*''[[Felix Cavaliere#Treasure|Treasure]]'' (1977 [[Epic Records|Epic]])\nGuitar & Lead Vocals on \"Innocent Eyes\" & \"Turn Yourself Around\"\n(with Felix Cavaliere: of The Rascals)\n\n===Felix Cavaliere===\n* ''Castles in the Air'' (1979)\n\n===HEAT===\n* ''Still Waiting'' (1981)\n\n===Tribute albums and singles===\n*''[[Kiss My Ankh|Kiss My Ankh: A Tribute to Vinnie Vincent]]'' (2008)\n*''Virtual Invasion \u2013 Gypsy in Her Eyes'' (2017)\n*''Virtual Invasion \u2013 Young Blood, Young Fire'' (2018)\n*''Virtual Invasion \u2013 Forbidden'' (2018)\n*''Virtual Invasion - Tears'' (2020)\n\n===The Bangles===\n*''[[Everything (The Bangles album)|Everything]]'' (1988) Songwriting credit & Guitars for \"Make a Play for Her Now\"  <ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/everything-mw0000197855|title=Everything \u2013 Bangles &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards &#124; AllMusic|publisher=allmusic.com|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Was Not Was===\n* ''[[Born to Laugh at Tornadoes]]'' (1983)\n\n===Warrior===\n* ''Warrior'' (2017 HNE Recordings). Collection of Demos.\n* ''Warrior II'' (2019 HNE Recordings). Another Collection of Demos.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Kiss (band)|Lead guitarist of Kiss]]| before=[[Ace Frehley]]| after=[[Mark St. John]]| years=1982\u20131984}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Kiss}}\n{{Vinnie Vincent Invasion}}\n{{Portalbar|Connecticut}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vincent, Vinnie}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Bridgeport, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American heavy metal guitarists]]\n[[Category:American rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Lead guitarists]]\n[[Category:Glam metal musicians]]\n[[Category:Kiss (band) members]]\n[[Category:Vinnie Vincent Invasion members]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n", "name_user": "2600:1700:e000:15c0:ece6:8dc8:4842:7d64", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added information)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vinnie_Vincent"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oregon", "text_new": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Oregon, United States}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oregon\n| width           = \n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| map1            = COVID-19 Cases in Oregon by counties.svg\n| legend1         = Map of the outbreak in Oregon (as of April 17)\n{{legend|#751a10|100+ confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#bb2919|10\u201399 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#d4796f|1\u20139 confirmed cases}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Oregon]]\n| first_case      = [[Washington County, Oregon|Washington County]]\n| arrival_date    = February 28, 2020\n| origin          = \n| confirmed_cases = 1,785<ref name=\"oha\">{{cite web|url=https://www.oregon.gov/oha/PH/DISEASESCONDITIONS/DISEASESAZ/Pages/emerging-respiratory-infections.aspx|title=Oregon Health Authority : Emerging Respiratory Infections: COVID-19 : Diseases A to Z : State of Oregon|website=www.oregon.gov|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| recovery_cases  = \n| deaths          = 70<ref name=\"oha\"/>\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://govstatus.egov.com/OR-OHA-COVID-19}}\n| hospitalized_cases = 125<ref name=\"oha\"/>\n| ventilator_cases = 28<ref name=\"oha\"/>\n| critical_cases  = 43<ref name=\"oha\"/>\n}}\nThe [[2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the U.S. state of [[Oregon]] on February 28, 2020.\n\n==Timeline==\n{{See also|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Portland, Oregon#Cases}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Oregon medical cases chart}}\nOn February 28, 2020, the [[Oregon Health Authority]] (OHA) reported the first case of suspected coronavirus in a resident of [[Washington County, Oregon|Washington County]]. The patient is an employee at Forest Hills Elementary School in the [[Lake Oswego School District]] in adjacent [[Clackamas County]].<ref name=zarkhin>{{cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/news/2020/02/coronavirus-appears-in-oregon.html|title=Oregon coronavirus case shuts Lake Oswego elementary school|last=Zarkhin|first=Fedor|publisher=[[OregonLive.com]]|date=February 28, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> The patient had not traveled to an infected area, likely indicating that the virus had been contracted within the community.<ref name=zarkhin/> The school district closed the school for three days for deep cleaning.<ref name=zarkhin/> The case was confirmed as coronavirus by the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) on March 3.<ref name=schmidt>{{cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/oregons-first-coronavirus-case-confirmed-by-cdc.html|title=Oregon's first coronavirus case confirmed by CDC|last=Schmidt|first=Brad|date=March 3, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020|publisher=[[OregonLive]]}}</ref> On March 1, Oregon confirmed its second case, a household contact of its first case.<ref name=\"oregon.2.1\">{{cite web |url=https://content.govdelivery.com/accounts/ORDHS/bulletins/27ea91b |title=Second Positive Case of COVID-19 Appears in Oregon |date=March 1, 2020|publisher=The Oregon Health Authority and Department of Human Services |language=en |access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 7, health officials identified four new presumptive positive cases among residents in Jackson, Klamath, and Washington counties.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oregon.gov/oha/ERD/Pages/four-new-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-oregon.aspx|title=Oregon Health Authority: Four new coronavirus cases confirmed in Oregon|publisher=External Relations Division, State of Oregon|date=March 7, 2020|access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref> On March 8, the OHA added 7 new presumptive positive cases to Oregon's count.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oregon.gov/oha/ERD/Pages/OHA-adds-7-new-presumptive-positive-cases-COVID-19.aspx|title=Oregon Health Authority: OHA adds 7 new presumptive positive cases to Oregon's COVID-19 count|date=March 8, 2020|publisher=External Relations Division, State of Oregon|website=oregon.gov}}</ref> On March 10, the OHA announced Multnomah County's first presumptive positive case, bringing Oregon's total to fifteen cases in seven counties.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oregon.gov/oha/ERD/Pages/first-multnomah-county-resident-tests-positive-covid-19.aspx|title=Multnomah County resident tests positive for COVID-19 |publisher=External Relations Division, State of Oregon|date=March 10, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> On March 11, OHA confirmed four new cases, one new case each in Deschutes, Marion, Polk, and Umatilla  counties.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oregon.gov/oha/ERD/Pages/State-announces-4-new-presumptive-positive-COVID-19-cases.aspx|title=Oregon Health Authority: State announces 4 new presumptive positive COVID-19 cases|publisher=External Relations Division, State of Oregon|website=oregon.gov|date=March 11, 2020|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> They later announced Linn County's first two presumptive positive cases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oregon.gov/oha/ERD/Pages/State-announces-2-new-presumptive-positive-COVID-19-cases.aspx|title=Oregon Health Authority: State announces 2 new presumptive positive COVID-19 cases|publisher=External Relations Division, State of Oregon|website=oregon.gov|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAn outbreak occurred at the 154-bed [[Edward C. Allworth Veterans' Home]] in [[Lebanon, Oregon|Lebanon]], [[Linn County, Oregon|Linn County]]. By March 16, the virus was confirmed in 13 residents (most over age 70) and one healthcare worker. With 151 residents and 225 workers, the county health director said, \"I can't stop it. I can't stop the virus. I can't make test kits appear\", but there was some optimism that the spread would be slow since the retirement home is divided into eleven housing units with 14 residents each. In 2016, the average resident age was 85, with an average length of stay being 50 days.<ref name=\"demo_154-\">{{cite web |title=154-bed Edward C. Allworth Veterans Home full by second anniversary |last=Paul |first=Alex |work=[[Albany Democrat-Herald]] |date=November 8, 2016 |access-date=March 13, 2020 |url= https://democratherald.com/news/bed-edward-c-allworth-veterans-home-full-by-second-anniversary/article_36ad01b4-8b1b-50f7-9190-f37c40fb45a1.html}}</ref><ref name=\"oreg_More\">{{cite web |title=More coronavirus cases expected at veterans' home, Linn County says|last=Zarkhin|first=Fedor|work=[[The Oregonian]] |date=March 12, 2020 |access-date=March 13, 2020 |url= https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/test-kit-shortage-slows-coronavirus-checks-at-veterans-home-linn-county-says.html |quote=The day before, two men who live at the home were diagnosed with the virus. Health officials said they don\u2019t know how they contracted it, calling it a \"community spread.\" }}</ref><ref name=\"demo_NewV\">{{cite web |title=New Veterans Home cases bring Linn County total to 8 |last=Day |first=James|work=[[Albany Democrat-Herald]] |date=March 12, 2020 |access-date=March 13, 2020 |url= https://democratherald.com/news/local/new-veterans-home-cases-bring-linn-county-total-to/article_8551ab67-0e85-528a-b9fa-1da9d57fd328.html#tracking-source=home-top-story}}</ref><ref name=\"katu_Oreg\">{{cite web |title=Oregon's newest cases of coronavirus found at veterans home in Linn County |last1=Benham |first1=Steve |publisher=[[KATU]] |date=March 11, 2020|access-date=March 13, 2020 |url= https://katu.com/news/coronavirus/linn-county-coronavirus-cases-at-lebanon-veterans-home |quote=The two latest cases of coronavirus in Oregon, announced Wednesday night, are two men who live at a veterans home in Linn County, according to the Oregon Health Authority. }}</ref><ref name=\"opb._Live\">{{cite web |title=Live Updates: Brown Considering Bar, Restaurant Closures; Clark County Has 4th New Case |author=OPB Staff|work=opb.org |date= |access-date=16 March 2020 |url= https://www.opb.org/news/article/oregon-coronavirus-live-updates-march-16-bar-restaurants-closures-cases/ |quote=The Linn County case is a staff member at the Oregon Veterans\u2019 Home in Lebanon, which has nine residents who have tested positive as of Sunday afternoon. The staff member has remained in isolation in accordance with infection prevention protocols and public health guidelines, according to the OHA. }}</ref> On March 16, [[Providence Health Systems#Oregon|Providence Health Systems]], [[Kaiser Permanente]], [[Legacy Health]], and [[Oregon Health and Sciences University]] formed a coalition to set up a regional [[health system]] in the state in order to address anticipated need for capacity and coordination to address the outbreak.<ref>{{cite web |title=Alarmed by projections of virus' spread, Oregon hospitals team up for expanded role |last1=Manning |first1=Jeff |last2=Sickinger |first2=Ted |publisher=[[KGW]] |date=March 16, 2020|access-date=March 16, 2020 |url= https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/oregon-hospital-beds-coronavirus-covid-19/283-fd53fa56-a1c0-439d-80b0-378fc989b009 |quote=In an unprecedented move, the Portland area's four major health systems say they are uniting to form a regional health system \"to implement a coordinated response\" to the virus. Providence Health Systems, Kaiser Permanente, Legacy Health and Oregon Health and Sciences University are all part of the new coalition. }}</ref>\n\n42-year-old Vladislav V. Drozdek was arrested on March 23 trying to sell stolen [[NIOSH air filtration rating|N95 hospital masks]] in [[Beaverton, Oregon|Beaverton]]. The masks were donated to local hospitals.<ref>[https://www.foxnews.com/us/coronavirus-respirator-mask-oregon-stolen-recovered-portland-police-donated-hospital Thousands of stolen coronavirus respirator masks found in Oregon, donated to hospitals as arrest made] By Travis Fedschun, Fox News, 23 March 2020</ref>\n\n===Incidents by day===\n{{prose|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:Oregon COVID-19 trands chart.png|thumb|Lines show trend using a five-day average.]]\n<div style=\"width: 75%; height: 25em; overflow: auto;\">\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! New Cases\n! Total Cases\n! New Deaths\n! Total Deaths\n! [[Doubling time]] of cases in days\n! Notes\n|-\n|Feb 28\n|1\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|\n|Washington County (1)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oregon.gov/oha/ERD/Pages/Oregon-First-Presumptive-Case-Novel-Coronavirus.aspx |title=Oregon announces first, presumptive case of novel coronavirus in Oregon|date=February 28, 2020|publisher=The Oregon Health Authority External Relations Division : State of Oregon|website=www.oregon.gov| access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|Feb 29\n|0\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|\n|\n|-\n|Mar 1\n|1\n|2\n|0\n|0\n|\n|Washington County(1)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://content.govdelivery.com/accounts/ORDHS/bulletins/27ea91b |title=Second Positive Case of COVID-19 Appears in Oregon |date=March 1, 2020|publisher=The Oregon Health Authority and Department of Human Services |language=en |access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|Mar 2\n|1\n|3\n|0\n|0\n|\n|Umatilla County resident hospitalized in Walla Walla, WA.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oregon.gov/oha/ERD/Pages/Oregon-identifies-third-presumptive-positive-case-of-COVID-19.aspx |title=Oregon identifies third presumptive positive case of COVID-19 |date=March 2, 2020|publisher=The Oregon Health Authority External Relations Division : State of Oregon|website=www.oregon.gov| access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|Mar 3\n|0\n|3\n|0\n|0\n|\n|\n|-\n|Mar 4\n|0\n|3\n|0\n|0\n|\n|\n|-\n|Mar 5\n|0\n|3\n|0\n