 Health Authority : Oregon reports 3 new COVID-19 deaths, 76 new COVID-19 cases : External Relations Division : State of Oregon|website=www.oregon.gov}}</ref>\n|-\n|Apr 12\n|80\n|1,527\n|1\n|52\n|\n|Death: an 89-year-old woman in Multnomah County. She had underlying conditions.<ref>https://www.oregon.gov/oha/ERD/Pages/Oregon-reports-1-new-COVID-19-death-80-new-COVID-19-cases.aspx</ref>\n|-\n|Apr 13\n|57\n|1,584\n|1\n|53\n|\n|Death: a 66-year-old Washington County resident. She had underlying medical conditions.<ref>https://www.oregon.gov/oha/ERD/Pages/Oregon-reports-1-new-COVID-19-death-57-new-COVID-19-cases.aspx</ref>\n|-\n|Apr 14\n|49\n|1,633\n|2\n|55\n|\n|Deaths: a 71-year-old man in Multnomah County and an 88-year-old woman in Benton County. They both had had underlying medical conditions.<ref>https://www.oregon.gov/oha/ERD/Pages/Oregon-reports-2-new-COVID-19-deaths-50-new-COVID-19-cases.aspx</ref>\n|-\n|Apr 15\n|30\n|1,663\n|3\n|58\n|\n|Deaths: an 82-year-old man in Marion County, an 84-year-old woman in Multnomah County and a 92-year-old woman in Multnomah County. They all had underlying medical conditions.<ref>https://www.oregon.gov/oha/ERD/Pages/Oregon-reports-3-new-COVID-19-deaths-33-new-COVID-19-cases.aspx</ref>\n|-\n|Apr 16\n|73\n|1,736\n|6\n|64\n|\n|Deaths: an 84-year-old man in Multnomah County, a 56-year-old man in Multnomah County, a 78-year-old man in Multnomah County, a 69-year-old man in Multnomah County, a 74-year-old woman in Benton County and a 92-year-old man in Marion County. They all had underlying medical conditions.<ref>https://www.oregon.gov/oha/ERD/Pages/Oregon-reports-6-new-COVID-19-deaths-73-new-COVID-19-cases.aspx</ref>\n|-\n|Apr 17\n|49\n|1,785\n|6\n|70\n|\n|Deaths: \n|}\n</div>\n\n==Government response==\n{{See also|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Portland, Oregon#Government response}}\n[[File:Milwaukie, Oregon, April 2020 - 1.jpg|thumb|Coronavirus signage at [[Milwaukie, Oregon|Milwaukie]]'s [[Spring Park (Milwaukie, Oregon)|Spring Park]]]]\n\nOn February 28, Governor [[Kate Brown]] created a coronavirus response team \"tasked with coordinating state- and local-level preparations for an epidemic\" of coronavirus in Oregon. \"[C]omposed of directors or other representatives of 12 state agencies,\" the response team will \"keep the governor posted on the coronavirus situation internationally and give her advice on how to protect the public.\"<ref name=\"Oregonian response team\">{{cite web |last1=Zarkhin |first1=Fedor |title=Oregon Gov. Kate Brown creates coronavirus response team 'in an escalating global crisis' |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/news/2020/02/oregon-gov-kate-brown-creates-coronavirus-response-team-in-an-escalating-global-crisis.html |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |date=February 28, 2020|accessdate=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301184542/https://www.oregonlive.com/news/2020/02/oregon-gov-kate-brown-creates-coronavirus-response-team-in-an-escalating-global-crisis.html |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> She later ordered the cancellation of events for 250 or more people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-and-oregon-schools-whats-canceled-why-arent-schools-closed.html|title=Coronavirus and Oregon schools: What's canceled, why aren't schools closed?|first=Eder|last=Campuzano |work=[[The Oregonian]]|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Oregon Medical Station is a 250-bed emergency hospital being built to treat patients of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] at the [[Oregon State Fair]]grounds in [[Salem, Oregon|Salem]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wweek.com/news/2020/03/18/oregon-is-opening-a-250-bed-emergency-hospital-on-state-fairgrounds-to-treat-covid-19-patients/|title=Oregon is Opening a 250-Bed Emergency Hospital on State Fairgrounds to Treat COVID-19 Patients|website=Willamette Week}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/oregon-washington-northwest-coronavirus-live-updates-march-18/|title=Live Updates: Oregon Medical Station To Open In Salem; 75 Known Coronavirus Cases In Oregon|first=Meerah|last=Powell|website=www.opb.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.salemreporter.com/posts/2088/temporary-hospital-to-be-installed-on-state-fairgrounds-in-salem-governor-says|title=Temporary hospital to be installed on state fairgrounds in Salem, governor says|date=March 18, 2020|website=Salem Reporter}}</ref>\n\nAfter growing calls from local officials, Governor Brown issued a statewide [[stay-at-home order]] on March 23 effective immediately with class C [[misdemeanor]] charges for violators.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gunderson |first1=Laura |title=Oregon stay at home order: Where can I go? |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/oregon-stay-at-home-order-where-can-i-go.html |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=The Oregonian |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, the [[Oregon Liquor Control Commission]] (OLCC) which enforces the [[Oregon Bottle Bill]] suspended the enforcement so grocers can focus on restocking, sanitation and social distancing management.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/oregon-grocers-close-bottle-drop-service-due-to-coronavirus-staffing-issues.html|title=Oregon grocers close bottle return service due to coronavirus staffing issues|last=Harbarger|first=Molly|date=2020-03-18|website=oregonlive|publisher=The Oregonian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> The exemption was originally given from March 15 to March 31, however due to continuing social distancing and staffing concerns, it has been extended until April 30.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kptv.com/news/olcc-extends-bottle-bill-reprieve-for-oregon-businesses-due-to-pandemic/article_39a30206-744c-11ea-b7b3-574ecfd6fa66.html|title=OLCC extends bottle bill reprieve for Oregon businesses due to pandemic|last=Staff|first=FOX 12|website=KPTV.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n[[File:Gas pump in Portland, Oregon during COVID-19 exemption.jpg|thumb|Signage at a gas pump in [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]] showing temporary self-serve]]\nOn March 28, Oregon temporarily lifted the prohibition on self-pump at gas stations at least until April 11 to ensure fuel is available during staffing issues related to the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/news/2020/03/oregon-temporarily-lifts-prohibition-on-self-service-gas-in-response-to-coronavirus.html|title=Oregon temporarily allows drivers to pump their own gas|last=Borrud|first=Hillary|date=2020-03-28|website=oregonlive|publisher=The Oregonian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn April 9, Gov. Brown announced that Abbott ID NOW rapid testing machines were being sent to three rural hospitals: [[Curry General Hospital]] in [[Gold Beach, Oregon|Gold Beach]], [[Pioneer Memorial Hospital]] in [[Heppner, Oregon|Heppner]], and [[Lake District Hospital]] in [[Lakeview, Oregon|Lakeview]]. Fifteen machines were sent to each state from HHS; the destinations of the other 12 machines were not given. Only 120 individual test kits were sent, delaying their widespread use.<ref name=\"oreg_Oreg\">{{Cite web |title=Oregon.gov: NewsDetail |author= |work=oregon.gov |date=9 April 2020 |access-date=9 April 2020 |url= https://www.oregon.gov/newsroom/pages/NewsDetail.aspx?newsid=36326}}</ref><ref name=\"aler_IDNO\">{{Cite web |title=ID NOW\u2122 COVID-19 - Alere is now Abbott |trans-title= |author= |work=alere.com |date= |access-date=9 April 2020 |url= https://www.alere.com/en/home/product-details/id-now-covid-19.html |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, Gov. Brown, together with California governor [[Gavin Newsom]] and Washington governor [[Jay Inslee]], announced the Western States Pact, an agreement to coordinate among the three states to restart economic activity while controlling the outbreak.<ref>{{cite web |title=California, Oregon & Washington Announce Western States Pact |url=https://www.oregon.gov/newsroom/Pages/NewsDetail.aspx?newsid=36352 |website=www.oregon.gov |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Economic impact==\n{{See also|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Portland, Oregon#Economic impact}}\n[[File:Hand sanitizer and gloves sold out due to Coronavirus 10 57 26 366000.jpeg|thumb|right|Empty [[latex glove]] shelves at a Rite Aid in downtown Portland]]\n\nOregon's largest employers, [[Columbia Sportswear]], [[Intel]], and [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]], lost market value because of stock declines.<ref name=Outlook>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/business/2020/03/coronavirus-darkens-oregons-economic-outlook-but-impacts-are-muted-for-now.html|title=Coronavirus darkens Oregon's economic outlook, but impacts are muted -- for now|first=Mike|last= Rogoway|newspaper=[[The Oregonian]]|date=March 10, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDelta Airlines reduced flights between Portland and Japan. United Airlines cut 4 of 20 flights from Portland as well as one from Eugene. Sun Country Airlines reduced flights between Portland and Honolulu, Las Vegas, and San Francisco.<ref name=Outlook/>\n\nPortland's restaurant and event industries experienced slowdowns.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-in-oregon-adds-to-restaurant-owners-worries.html|title=Coronavirus in Oregon adds to restaurant owners' worries|first=Michael |last=Russell |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]]|date=March 4, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/11/21175402/coronavirus-private-events-catering-portland-drop-business|title=Restaurants Brace for Sharper Decline in Events Business With State Ban on Large Gatherings|first=Brooke|last=Jackson-Glidden|date=Mar 11, 2020|website=Eater Portland|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> According to the Multnomah County Health Department, \"some Asian-American-owned businesses in the Jade District around Southeast 82nd Avenue had reported a drop in business 'because of the myths surrounding COVID-19.{{'\"}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/oregon-coronavirus-are-portland-restaurants-safe.html|title=Q&A: In age of coronavirus, is it safe to eat out in Portland? Expert says yes|first=Michael|last=Russell|newspaper=The Oregonian|date=March 7, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://katu.com/news/coronavirus/asian-restaurants-losing-business-blame-coronavirus-outbreak|title=Local Asian restaurants losing business, blame coronavirus outbreak|first=Allison|last= Mechanic|date=March 5, 2020|publisher=[[KATU]]|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> At least two conventions have been cancelled.<ref name=Outlook/>\n\n[[Multnomah County Library]] closed all library branches. The [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry]] and [[Portland Art Museum]] also closed, and [[City Club of Portland]] began hosting activities online.<ref>{{cite news|last=Monahan|first=Rachel|url=https://www.wweek.com/news/city/2020/03/13/multnomah-county-library-closed-as-of-today-in-response-to-the-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Multnomah County Library Closed in Response to the Coronavirus Outbreak \u2013&nbsp;Library director says it's the first such closure in modern times |date=March 13, 2020 |newspaper=[[Willamette Week]] |accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref> The [[Hollywood Theatre (Portland, Oregon)|Hollywood Theatre]] is closed until April 8,<ref>{{cite news|last=Gormley|first=Shannon|title=Portland's Hollywood Theatre Will Close Until April 8|date=March 13, 2020|newspaper=[[Willamette Week]]|url=https://www.wweek.com/arts/movies/2020/03/13/portlands-hollywood-theatre-will-close-until-april-8/|accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref> and the Tillamook Creamery has been closed temporarily.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.kptv.com/news/tillamook-creamery-announces-temporary-closure-of-visitors-center-due-to/article_0d2a1d24-65b3-11ea-9338-97b76380cae2.html|title=Tillamook Creamery announces temporary closure of visitors center due to COVID-19 concerns|date=March 13, 2020|publisher=[[KPTV]]|accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nCannabis dispensaries were given permission to convert to curbside pickup operations by the OLCC . Medical cannabis patients were allowed to purchase up to 24 ounces per day, limited to 32 ounces per month. Cannabis sales increased during the first half of March; sales were 25\u201330 percent higher than for the same period of time in 2019.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/23/28186115/oregon-cannabis-dispensaries-now-allowed-to-offer-curbside-pickup | title=Oregon Cannabis Dispensaries Now Allowed to Offer Curbside Pickup}}</ref> The [[American Herbal Products Association]]'s Hemp-CBD Congress, scheduled to be held in Portland in April, was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/09/28113766/coronavirus-and-cannabis-how-pot-is-impacted-by-a-pandemic |title = Coronavirus and Cannabis: How Pot is Impacted by a Pandemic}}</ref>\n\n===School closures===\n[[Oregon State University]], [[Portland State University]], the [[University of Oregon]], and [[University of Portland]] all moved to online classes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/university-of-oregon-classes-remotely-coronavirus/283-b5b5abc3-463f-442a-abc6-964fb9036d54|title=UO, OSU, PSU, UP to cancel in-person classes amid coronavirus outbreak|publisher=[[KGW]]|date=March 11, 2020|last=Hanson|first=Nate|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://katu.com/news/local/university-of-oregon-urged-to-close-as-virus-spreads|title=University of Oregon, OSU cancel in-person classes, events starting next week|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=March 11, 2020|publisher=[[KATU]]|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/portland/news/2020/03/09/coronavirus-in-oregon-osu-considers-halting-face.html|title=Coronavirus in Oregon: OSU considers halting 'face-to-face' activities; UO, PSU updates|last=Giegerich|first=Andy|date=March 9, 2020|website=www.bizjournals.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref> [[Reed College]], [[Lewis and Clark College]], [[Linfield College]], and [[Willamette University]] did as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reed.edu/reed-magazine/articles/2020/covid-19-dorms-close.html|title=COVID-19: Classes Will Move Online for Rest of Semester|first=Chris|last=Lydgate|newspaper=Reed Magazine|date=March 15, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/university-of-portland-willamette-cancel-in-person-classes-latest-colleges-to-shift-amid-coronavirus-concerns.html|title=University of Portland, Willamette, Lewis & Clark, Linfield cancel in-person classes amid coronavirus concerns|first=Rob|last= Davis|newspaper=[[The Oregonian]]|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, Governor Brown ordered all K\u201312 schools closed statewide from March 16 to March 31, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/portland-metro-school-district-tigard-tualatin-lake-oswego-coronavirus-board-meeting-emergency-covid-students/|title=Brown orders all K-12 schools closed through March|date=March 12, 2020|publisher=[[KOIN (TV)|KOIN]]|language=en-US|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> Just five days later, Brown extended the closure through April 28.<ref>{{cite news |last=Borrud |first=Hillary |title=Oregon schools to remain closed through April 28 |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/oregon-schools-to-remain-closed-through-april-28.html |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |work=[[The Oregonian]] |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[KinderCare Learning Centers|KinderCare]], a nationwide preschool provider based in Portland, closed approximately 1100 of their 1500 centers, leaving the centers that have large proportions of first responders and healthcare workers.<ref name=\"oreg_Kind\">{{cite web |title=KinderCare to close 1,100 daycare centers, refocus 400 on first responders |author=Ted Sickinger |work=[[Oregonlive]] |date=20 March 2020 |access-date=21 March 2020 |url= https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/kindercase-to-close-1100-day-care-centers-refocus-400-on-first-responders.html |quote=KinderCare, the Portland-based operator of 1,500 daycare centers in 40 states, said it will temporarily shut more than two-thirds of its centers because of the coronavirus pandemic.It said it will refocus more than 400 centers to provide childcare for first responders, healthcare workers and families that work in essential services. It could reopen more depending on demand.The company employs about 36,000 teachers and serves 186,000 children every day. It did not say how many of those employees and children would be affected. }}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, 2020, a worker at a [[Hillsboro, Oregon|Hillsboro]] Touchstone preschool, part of the [[Spring Education Group]] of for-profit private schools, tested positive for [[COVID-19]]. The preschool was closed for a deep cleaning and planned to remain closed for 14 days.<ref name=\"oreg_Hill\">{{cite web |title=Hillsboro day care worker tests positive for coronavirus |author=Brad Schmidt |work=oregonlive |date=21 March 2020 |access-date=21 March 2020 |url= https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/hillsboro-day-care-worker-tests-positive-for-coronavirus.html}}</ref>\n\n===Event cancellations===\nPAC-12 and Oregon State University Athletics banned participants from events, in effect March 14.<ref name=\"demo_OSUa\">{{cite web |title=OSU athletics: Events restrictions announced |work=[[Albany Democrat-Herald]] |date=March 11, 2020 |access-date=March 13, 2020 |url= https://democratherald.com/sports/beavers-sports/osu-athletics-events-restrictions-announced/article_0d2114d3-893d-5d5a-be0c-6cf0887b4d9c.html |quote=Oregon State University Athletics, in conjunction with the Pac-12 Conference Chief Executive Officers, announced Wednesday that attendance at all intercollegiate athletic events will be restricted to essential event staff, student-athletes, and coaches. The policy goes into effect Saturday March 14.}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on sports==\n{{See also|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Portland, Oregon#Impact on professional sports}}\n[[File:Providence Park box office notice - closed due to COVID-19 epidemic, 3-16-2020.jpg|thumb|right|Notice posted at [[Providence Park]] indicating the stadium's closure to help prevent the spread of the coronavirus]]\nOn March 12, the [[National Basketball Association]] announced the season would be suspended for 30 days, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Portland Trail Blazers season|Portland Trail Blazers]].<ref name=nba>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |title=Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days |date=March 12, 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>  During the same day, [[Major League Soccer]] announced the league would be suspended for at least 30 days, affecting the [[2020 Portland Timbers season|Portland Timbers]].<ref name=mls>{{cite web |url=https://www.timbers.com/post/2020/03/12/mls-suspends-2020-season-30-days |title=MLS suspends 2020 season for 30 days |date=March 12, 2020 |website=Timbers.com |language=en|access-date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>  On March 19, MLS extended the suspension until at least May 19, 2020.<ref name=\"COVID19MLSSuspension2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2020/03/19/mls-extends-season-suspension-accordance-cdc-guidance-covid-19 |title=MLS extends season suspension in accordance with CDC guidance on COVID-19 |date=March 19, 2020 |website=MLSSoccer.com |publisher=MLSsoccer staff |access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref name=ncaa>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"3\" |2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) Cases in Oregon<ref name=\"oha\"/>\nUpdated April 17, 2020\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |County\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed Cases\n!Deaths\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Baker County, Oregon|Baker]]\n|0\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Benton County, Oregon|Benton]]\n|27\n|4\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Clackamas County, Oregon|Clackamas]]\n|153\n|4\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Clatsop County, Oregon|Clatsop]]\n|6\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Columbia County, Oregon|Columbia]]\n|14\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Coos County, Oregon|Coos]]\n|1\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Crook County, Oregon|Crook]]\n|1\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Curry County, Oregon|Curry]]\n|3\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Deschutes County, Oregon|Deschutes]]\n|61\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Douglas County, Oregon|Douglas]]\n|22\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Gilliam County, Oregon|Gilliam]]\n|0\n|0