p2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Oregon]]\n| first_case      = [[Washington County, Oregon|Washington County]]\n| arrival_date    = February 28, 2020\n| origin          = \n| confirmed_cases = 1,785<ref name=\"oha\">{{cite web|url=https://www.oregon.gov/oha/PH/DISEASESCONDITIONS/DISEASESAZ/Pages/emerging-respiratory-infections.aspx|title=Oregon Health Authority : Emerging Respiratory Infections: COVID-19 : Diseases A to Z : State of Oregon|website=www.oregon.gov|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| recovery_cases  = \n| deaths          = 70<ref name=\"oha\"/>\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://govstatus.egov.com/OR-OHA-COVID-19}}\n| hospitalized_cases = 125<ref name=\"oha\"/>\n| ventilator_cases = 28<ref name=\"oha\"/>\n| critical_cases  = 43<ref name=\"oha\"/>\n}}\nThe [[2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the U.S. state of [[Oregon]] on February 28, 2020.\n\n==Timeline==\n{{See also|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Portland, Oregon#Cases}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Oregon medical cases chart}}\nOn February 28, 2020, the [[Oregon Health Authority]] (OHA) reported the first case of suspected coronavirus in a resident of [[Washington County, Oregon|Washington County]]. The patient is an employee at Forest Hills Elementary School in the [[Lake Oswego School District]] in adjacent [[Clackamas County]].<ref name=zarkhin>{{cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/news/2020/02/coronavirus-appears-in-oregon.html|title=Oregon coronavirus case shuts Lake Oswego elementary school|last=Zarkhin|first=Fedor|publisher=[[OregonLive.com]]|date=February 28, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> The patient had not traveled to an infected area, likely indicating that the virus had been contracted within the community.<ref name=zarkhin/> The school district closed the school for three days for deep cleaning.<ref name=zarkhin/> The case was confirmed as coronavirus by the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) on March 3.<ref name=schmidt>{{cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/oregons-first-coronavirus-case-confirmed-by-cdc.html|title=Oregon's first coronavirus case confirmed by CDC|last=Schmidt|first=Brad|date=March 3, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020|publisher=[[OregonLive]]}}</ref> On March 1, Oregon confirmed its second case, a household contact of its first case.<ref name=\"oregon.2.1\">{{cite web |url=https://content.govdelivery.com/accounts/ORDHS/bulletins/27ea91b |title=Second Positive Case of COVID-19 Appears in Oregon |date=March 1, 2020|publisher=The Oregon Health Authority and Department of Human Services |language=en |access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 7, health officials identified four new presumptive positive cases among residents in Jackson, Klamath, and Washington counties.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oregon.gov/oha/ERD/Pages/four-new-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-oregon.aspx|title=Oregon Health Authority: Four new coronavirus cases confirmed in Oregon|publisher=External Relations Division, State of Oregon|date=March 7, 2020|access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref> On March 8, the OHA added 7 new presumptive positive cases to Oregon's count.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oregon.gov/oha/ERD/Pages/OHA-adds-7-new-presumptive-positive-cases-COVID-19.aspx|title=Oregon Health Authority: OHA adds 7 new presumptive positive cases to Oregon's COVID-19 count|date=March 8, 2020|publisher=External Relations Division, State of Oregon|website=oregon.gov}}</ref> On March 10, the OHA announced Multnomah County's first presumptive positive case, bringing Oregon's total to fifteen cases in seven counties.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oregon.gov/oha/ERD/Pages/first-multnomah-county-resident-tests-positive-covid-19.aspx|title=Multnomah County resident tests positive for COVID-19 |publisher=External Relations Division, State of Oregon|date=March 10, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> On March 11, OHA confirmed four new cases, one new case each in Deschutes, Marion, Polk, and Umatilla  counties.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oregon.gov/oha/ERD/Pages/State-announces-4-new-presumptive-positive-COVID-19-cases.aspx|title=Oregon Health Authority: State announces 4 new presumptive positive COVID-19 cases|publisher=External Relations Division, State of Oregon|website=oregon.gov|date=March 11, 2020|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> They later announced Linn County's first two presumptive positive cases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oregon.gov/oha/ERD/Pages/State-announces-2-new-presumptive-positive-COVID-19-cases.aspx|title=Oregon Health Authority: State announces 2 new presumptive positive COVID-19 cases|publisher=External Relations Division, State of Oregon|website=oregon.gov|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAn outbreak occurred at the 154-bed [[Edward C. Allworth Veterans' Home]] in [[Lebanon, Oregon|Lebanon]], [[Linn County, Oregon|Linn County]]. By March 16, the virus was confirmed in 13 residents (most over age 70) and one healthcare worker. With 151 residents and 225 workers, the county health director said, \"I can't stop it. I can't stop the virus. I can't make test kits appear\", but there was some optimism that the spread would be slow since the retirement home is divided into eleven housing units with 14 residents each. In 2016, the average resident age was 85, with an average length of stay being 50 days.<ref name=\"demo_154-\">{{cite web |title=154-bed Edward C. Allworth Veterans Home full by second anniversary |last=Paul |first=Alex |work=[[Albany Democrat-Herald]] |date=November 8, 2016 |access-date=March 13, 2020 |url= https://democratherald.com/news/bed-edward-c-allworth-veterans-home-full-by-second-anniversary/article_36ad01b4-8b1b-50f7-9190-f37c40fb45a1.html}}</ref><ref name=\"oreg_More\">{{cite web |title=More coronavirus cases expected at veterans' home, Linn County says|last=Zarkhin|first=Fedor|work=[[The Oregonian]] |date=March 12, 2020 |access-date=March 13, 2020 |url= https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/test-kit-shortage-slows-coronavirus-checks-at-veterans-home-linn-county-says.html |quote=The day before, two men who live at the home were diagnosed with the virus. Health officials said they don\u2019t know how they contracted it, calling it a \"community spread.\" }}</ref><ref name=\"demo_NewV\">{{cite web |title=New Veterans Home cases bring Linn County total to 8 |last=Day |first=James|work=[[Albany Democrat-Herald]] |date=March 12, 2020 |access-date=March 13, 2020 |url= https://democratherald.com/news/local/new-veterans-home-cases-bring-linn-county-total-to/article_8551ab67-0e85-528a-b9fa-1da9d57fd328.html#tracking-source=home-top-story}}</ref><ref name=\"katu_Oreg\">{{cite web |title=Oregon's newest cases of coronavirus found at veterans home in Linn County |last1=Benham |first1=Steve |publisher=[[KATU]] |date=March 11, 2020|access-date=March 13, 2020 |url= https://katu.com/news/coronavirus/linn-county-coronavirus-cases-at-lebanon-veterans-home |quote=The two latest cases of coronavirus in Oregon, announced Wednesday night, are two men who live at a veterans home in Linn County, according to the Oregon Health Authority. }}</ref><ref name=\"opb._Live\">{{cite web |title=Live Updates: Brown Considering Bar, Restaurant Closures; Clark County Has 4th New Case |author=OPB Staff|work=opb.org |date= |access-date=16 March 2020 |url= https://www.opb.org/news/article/oregon-coronavirus-live-updates-march-16-bar-restaurants-closures-cases/ |quote=The Linn County case is a staff member at the Oregon Veterans\u2019 Home in Lebanon, which has nine residents who have tested positive as of Sunday afternoon. The staff member has remained in isolation in accordance with infection prevention protocols and public health guidelines, according to the OHA. }}</ref> On March 16, [[Providence Health Systems#Oregon|Providence Health Systems]], [[Kaiser Permanente]], [[Legacy Health]], and [[Oregon Health and Sciences University]] formed a coalition to set up a regional [[health system]] in the state in order to address anticipated need for capacity and coordination to address the outbreak.<ref>{{cite web |title=Alarmed by projections of virus' spread, Oregon hospitals team up for expanded role |last1=Manning |first1=Jeff |last2=Sickinger |first2=Ted |publisher=[[KGW]] |date=March 16, 2020|access-date=March 16, 2020 |url= https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/oregon-hospital-beds-coronavirus-covid-19/283-fd53fa56-a1c0-439d-80b0-378fc989b009 |quote=In an unprecedented move, the Portland area's four major health systems say they are uniting to form a regional health system \"to implement a coordinated response\" to the virus. Providence Health Systems, Kaiser Permanente, Legacy Health and Oregon Health and Sciences University are all part of the new coalition. }}</ref>\n\n42-year-old Vladislav V. Drozdek was arrested on March 23 trying to sell stolen [[NIOSH air filtration rating|N95 hospital masks]] in [[Beaverton, Oregon|Beaverton]]. The masks were donated to local hospitals.<ref>[https://www.foxnews.com/us/coronavirus-respirator-mask-oregon-stolen-recovered-portland-police-donated-hospital Thousands of stolen coronavirus respirator masks found in Oregon, donated to hospitals as arrest made] By Travis Fedschun, Fox News, 23 March 2020</ref>\n\n===Incidents by day===\n{{prose|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:Oregon COVID-19 trands chart.png|thumb|Lines show trend using a five-day average.]]\n<div style=\"width: 75%; height: 25em; overflow: auto;\">\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! New Cases\n! Total Cases\n! New Deaths\n! Total Deaths\n! [[Doubling time]] of cases in days\n! Notes\n|-\n|Feb